\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Prof. Pahl, I want to start by askin
g something about your personal family history. So if you could just tell me when and where you were born to start with, and where you grew up, and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} in 1935. My mother was Scottish and she came down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to be a nurse. She came from a farming family. My father was the son of a businessman, who was quite successful, bought a newly-built house in a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North London{\*\xmlclose}
 suburb to set up his son and daughter-in-law. And so that\rquote s where I was until the War broke out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So was that an unusual union, your parents, do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. I think we\rquote ll come back to that quite a lot, particularly because my grandfather had come across from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in the 1880s, to set up a business.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 This is your paternal grandfather?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That\rquote s right. And \'85 early memories don\rquote 
t come to much, because, again, before 1939, when I was four, it doesn\rquote t add much to my memories! (LAUGHS) Vague childhood memories, I suppose. But we were, actually, sort of bombed out of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. My parents were worried about my safety, really, because of shrapnel coming through the window and being embedded in a sofa that I was sleeping in, and so forth, so they thought it was time to go. We went up
 to an uncle in Nottinghamshire, a dairy farmer, and stayed there. And then my father, who had bad eyes, was sort of \'85
 conscripted into the Air Force to do some admin. job, and that meant that he was pushed around the country from air base to air base, and so we were rather a sort of peripatetic, nomadic life, my mother and I, in the early years of the War.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Following your father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Following him around and staying in digs and so on, until we finally settled in a little village in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}South Leicestershire{\*\xmlclose}. We had a flat in the Vicarage, with a lovely great big garden. I still think of that, it was a lovely place for a young boy to \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Was that still during the War?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yeah. And so in 1943, I went off to a boarding school, a prep school in Leicester, [{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Stoneygate{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
] and was there from the age of eight until eleven, by which time the War was over. I remember that. And then we went back to London, and went back to the house that we\rquote d originally left, and I then
 went to a very dull sort of posh little prep school in North London, which I didn\rquote t \'85 well, because I\rquote d had a tougher, rougher life, by being \'85 knocking around during the War, and they were protected little mummy\rquote 
s dears, which I\rquote d been before I went to boarding school! I think, got a lot of confidence from that, because earlier on, I was promoted up in the class, and put into a different dormitory with older children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So it was a boarding school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yeah. And that was tough. So that \'85 I had a bad time then, you know, the sort of bullying, because I was \'85
 but going to this prep. school, when I was the cock of the roost, really, did me some good, probably. I think that\rquote s rather important.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Where, which {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}North London{\*\xmlclose} \'85 part \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Woodside{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}
Park{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Holmewood{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} it was called.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Where\rquote s 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Woodside{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It\rquote s on the Northern Line! We lived in Friern Barnet, Oakleigh Park, and I must say, I built up a g
reat hatred of the suburbs, I think, partly because I felt superior to these really rather constricted, narrow, middle-class kids, who really hadn\rquote t had much experience. The fact that I\rquote 
d knocked around, had a lot of experience, made me, I suppose, as one does as a child, a bit sort of \'85 you know, a bit superior to them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So what sort of experiences do you mean, that 
\'85 made you feel more confident? Or gave you more confidence?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well \'85
\par 
\par [TELEPHONE INTERRUPTION]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 We were just talking ab
out the childhood experiences that you felt gave you more confidence, or made you a bit different from the other children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, I\rquote d had a degree of what you might call suffering, in the sense that I\rquote 
d been rather lonely and, you know, it was a long time to be away from one\rquote 
s parents at the age of eight, all term sometimes, and I had sort of quite vivid memories of being left, you know, sitting on the wall outside the school, waiting for my father to come and collect me. And because of problems, perhap
s nothing to do with him, or perhaps \'85 I don\rquote t know, he arriving late, all the other kids having gone home, and there I am, waiting all afternoon. So it\rquote s that kind of \'85 feeling that I\rquote 
d learnt to look after myself a bit, because no one else would, maybe. And I remember trudging back on VE Day, when we were all let out of school. It was very difficult to get the transport and so on, and it was a two mile walk from the \'85
 a bit more, perhaps, from the train station at Market Harborough to where we were staying. So I remember trudging along there, it was a very hot day, with a great big bag, at the age of what \'85
 ten or eleven. Eleven probably. And, of course, I had some experiences too. I mean, with my mother, I was, perhaps, too close in the early years, becau
se of Father being away. And there was one occasion when we were staying in rented rooms, and the woman (i.e. landlady) was clearly deranged in some way, and she went at us with a knife. And my mother was scared, and we sort of just went off into the nigh
t in a Thomas Hardy like way. I remember going along and a storm came, and sort of, you know, cowering in a ditch, with the rain lashing down! But that kind of experience of \'85 it\rquote s out of the way of the normal protected suburban life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Right. A lot
 of people would say that made them tougher, you\rquote re saying it helped you to survive. Do you feel it made you tougher?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
I think I spent a lot of time with adults as well, being an only child for the first nine years, until my brother was born. And I\rquote ve got lots of memories of just listening to adult conversation, and they kind of forgot about me, and they\rquote 
d be worrying away about, you know, the War, and where they were going to go and so forth. And life was a bit on the edge, actually, and it was a kind of marginal, that\rquote 
s a key word, I think, a sort of marginal experience of not being in any of the communities that one was staying in, and sort of endless worry that my parents would have about, you know, where my father would go next, and where they\rquote d li
ve, this thing. It was the peripatetic nature of the War years that sticks in my mind, and also being a sort of urbanite in a village, and being got at by the village children. I mean, the first school I went to, we were all in one classroom, round a stov
e, and all the older girls looked after the younger children, and we wrote on slate, so it was all very primitive. And there was a lot of rough, tough, you know, \'93Beat up this little townie, posh bastard bugger\'94, you know, \'93with a smart accent
\'94, and I remember being under a heaving pile of about ten little boys all punching each other. So that kind of experience. I got very used to going off on long walks, by myself, with a dog or with a \'85
 there was another little lad who was a kind of hanger on, but was younger than me, and he came along as my kind of shadow. And I just got very reflective. I got very inward-looking. I remember \'85
 unusually, sort of distancing myself from the world about me, I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
And did that leave you, that sort of characteristic, as you got back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
No, because it became even stronger then. When we came back to London, having had a bit of a cosmopolitan experience, not a big deal, but, you know, something, and then seeing the kind of narrow world of t
hese others, I just felt superior to them, because, you know, I felt they hadn\rquote t done very much, you see. So those years were probably rather sort of cocky years of \'85
 because about then, I discovered I was good at athletics and, you know, come the School Sports Day, I\rquote d just win every race, and that made me feel, and that does give you a sort of a boost, really. So that was until 14, when I moved to St. Alban
\rquote s School, and travelled out from North London by bus, every day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So, from 8-14, you were 
at two different boarding schools?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No, no. No. The prep. school in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was a day school. So I was there from 11-14.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So it\rquote 
s just the first, the 8-11 that was boarding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Mmm. Three years boarding, three years of \'85 [INAUDIBLE], that\rquote s 8-14.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And why did you board during those years?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, that\rquote s an interesting question, because a lot of people have since said, you know, \'93
Gosh, your parents must have been foul, sending you off at that tender age\'94, and, you know, too young, and everything. But I really do remember being in the kitchen, and them putting to me the choice, saying, \'93There\rquote 
s this school locally, where you can go backwards and forwards. Or you can go to this better school, but you\rquote ll board. And what do you think?\'94 They actually put the thing to me, which may have been hard at the age of eight. But I said, \'93No, I
\rquote ll go for the big one. I\rquote ll go for the one in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Leicester{\*\xmlclose}\'94. And they felt, I think, that I wasn\rquote t learning that much in the village
 school. Perhaps they were a bit distressed at me getting beaten up or whatever, and they thought that \'85 you know, they thought I needed to be amongst people, quote, \'93of my own sort\'94, whether that might have been \'85
 I think they were pretty vague about it, actually. I don\rquote t know, I should have asked them before they died, what they thought about making that decision, because, thinking back \'85
 I suppose they felt that if my father moved again, it was disruptive to me. I think, actually, at some point, dimly I remember the \'85 sort of School Inspector, or Attendance Officer, or someone like that, had come round, because I hadn\rquote 
t been at school for a long time. I was ill, I had trouble with my glands, I was in hospital and stuff. And so I think, round about the age
 of five, six, I spent ages not being at school at all, not doing anything much. So I think that they were thinking, you know, \'93We really have a responsibility to give him some kind of stable school life, and maybe this is the way to do it\'94
. I suspect there was something of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So, going back to your parents, you mother was a nurse, you said.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But she wasn\rquote 
t nursing when you were a child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No, no, she gave up, afterwards, foolishly, to be a full-time housewife.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Right. So when she got married, she stopped?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yeah. It was the way in those days, as the \'85
 all the literature points out. But the idea of going back to work, for women in the thirties, in the sort of middle-class, wasn\rquote t really considered as an option. And my mother was probably a bit of a snob, in that \'85
 I mean, she was, if you like, upwardly mobile, and rather liked the idea of having, you know, nice new house, nice new baby, someone that came in and, you know, as she said, \'93polished the silver\'94, although there wasn\rquote 
t much. But, you know, someone who was a kind of nanny person, who pushed me out in my pram, and things like that. And that was her glory years. And she lived for those years. All during the War, she was thi
nking back to these happy years from the birth of me to the time we left, as being her golden age, which was really a mistake, but \'85 you know, there you are.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
That really coloured the rest of her life, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I think so, yes. She felt tha
t she had to go through a lot of trouble, which she was tough and could take. And there were some other good years later, perhaps I\rquote ll come to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So your mum came from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, at what point? Or why, to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, she came from a large family, I don\rquote 
t know how many, but I think my grandmother had, probably, about eleven births. One or two died young. So she came from a large family. She was at the young end of it. I\rquote ve only got one of her siblings left, and she\rquote 
s well into her eighties now. She\rquote s the youngest. And my grandfather came, I think, originally from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}, and \'85
 the book that says all about that, Country Bairns, which is the book by Lynn Jamieson about life in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 at the turn of the century, and it\rquote s almost as if my mother\rquote s speaking, in parts of it, it\rquote s so close. But basically, it was very tough being an agricultural worker then, because there were no middle \'85
 there were either the big lairds with big lands, and he \'85 would be a sort of \'85 what we might call a \'93factor\'94, or \'93manager\'94
, but he was a proud man, and a short temper, and he used to quarrel and get the sack. And so they moved around a lot. And my mother was seen by, I think the school teacher, or the P
resbyterian Minister, as being the sort of bright one, and went up to my grandparents and said, \'93Jeannie is \'85 is clever. You should do something for her\'94. And they didn\rquote 
t know what to do. But then there was a kind of Presbyterian Mafia, I think, and so what happened was that she got sent down to London to be looked after by a Presbyterian Minister in London, and she then applied to be a nurse at St. Thomas\rquote 
s, and got trained, and got a good training. And then she was a private nurse for a time, and was quite competent at it as far as I can make out. She was credited. And that was why she came down South, simply because there was no hope for young girls in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Do you know, did she see that as something exciting, when she did that? I mean, it sounds like quite a wrench as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. It was \'85 but she made new friends, and I think there\rquote 
s a whole lot of Scottish rubbish about people who always say, \'93Oh, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote 
s so wonderful, and it was terrible when we had to leave\'94. Actually, they\rquote re quite glad they\rquote ve gone, because it was so poor. And it\rquote s a big family myth, actually, about wonderful {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. But they don\rquote t actually want to stay there. They\rquote ve got too many hurtful memories. It\rquote s very difficult to talk to my aunt about childhood, because she
\rquote s done very well in life and, you know, is very comfortable now, and she doesn\rquote t like to think about her poor childhood. And she doesn\rquote t even like to th
ink, to talk about her grandparents. So my family history is a bit narrow, really, because \'85 apart from the memories of my mother\rquote s stories, I haven\rquote 
t picked up much from the others. But I did go back to Wigtownshire where they got married in Wigtown, a sort of little pilgrimage back to my roots.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Your mother\rquote s parents, is this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. And I was just shocked by the sheer poverty of the landscape, and the \'85
 the churchyard full of the names of my grandparents\rquote  families, with very early deaths. It must have been a really hard life in the 19th century in that area.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So, your father, can you just say something, a little bit about your father\rquote s background?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, yes. My father had got \'85 he didn\rquote t actually talk about his family either! A
nd I never knew why. I mean, the trouble is, a lot of the skeletons in the family cupboard will remain there, I suppose! So it wasn\rquote 
t until I was 50, actually, and he was dead, that I actually met somebody who told me about my family. There was one occasion when one of my grandfather\rquote 
s business partners, it happened that his grandson was a student at the University of Kent, and so I got links with them, and I got invited up to London to talk about my grandfather. But I was so kind of overwrought, that I nev
er thought to take a tape-recorder. A rather smart sort of dinner party, a lot of wine and stuff. And the guy who was in his eighties, didn\rquote t start talking about him until we\rquote 
d been well wined and dined, and I hardly remember anything he told me, which is so annoying! And he \'85 I\rquote ve got sort of feelings about it, but it doesn\rquote t actually ring true. It doesn\rquote t actually fit with what I\rquote 
ve heard from the others. And one story is that my great great-grandfather lived in Freibourg, and manufactured church organs, and he was the last manufacturer of church organs in that sort of style, and there are churches in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with these things. Whether that\rquote s true or not, I don\rquote 
t know, because my grandfather came from Stuttgart, and had property in Stuttgart, and I\rquote ve since met rather distant relatives, I\rquote ve got the family tree down \'85
 reconstructed, I can tell you all about that, with a diagram. But I only learnt, as I say, when I was 50. And that side of the family are quite different. They\rquote re all \'85 as some cousin said to me, who\rquote s since dead, \'93
Teachers, mathematicians or musicians\'94, that\rquote s the sort of the way the \'85 or artists. Very creative. So that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stuttgart{\*\xmlclose}, there\rquote 
s one second/third cousin, who has a Pahl Quartet, she teaches music at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stuttgart{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and people work with her and play music. And she came to see us once. But, of course, not speaking English was a problem. I had another cousin who was an artist, and that book there that is a catalogue raison\'e9e of his work. And he was \'85 obviously
 a very vigorous man, and his grand-daughter is the only member of the family that I actually got on with. She\rquote s a child psychoanalyst. So, and she\rquote s been to stay here. We get on fine, although we\rquote 
re quite remote. I mean, if you look at the wiring diagram of my kin net, it\rquote s quite \'85 but there is a sort of a \'85 curiously, there\rquote s more of a kind of a rapport between me and she, than, somehow, my mother\rquote s family, that I don
\rquote t somehow get on with, and never did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So was your father born here? Was it you
r grandfather came here?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 He was born, very interestingly, he was born in Stoke Newington, about \'85
 just a few hundred yards from where my daughter lives now! And where my son lives now! So it\rquote s interesting, the Pahls sort of came in to Stoke Newington
 at one stage, Lordship Park, and they moved away as a new start they moved up to Finchley, then lived in a rather substantial house there. My grandfather did. And then, you know, the whole urban cycle changes, and that\rquote s where, you know, one
\rquote s kids end up \'85 with some grotty house, although perhaps I shouldn\rquote t say that! But, you know, it would have seemed to have been a grotty house from my grandparents\rquote 
 point of view, but now, of course, gentrified, looks rather smart.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So, having a German backgro
und from your father, did that have any effect on him during the War?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, of course. I always forget which way round it went. But my grandfather was interned by either the Germans in the First World War and the British in the Second, or the other way round, I\rquote m not quite sure which. And he got out, because \'85
 influential \'85 his influential brothers (?? \endash  202) from this, and he was able to be in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Switzerland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I think, for much of the War. But the business was just stopped. And my fath
er, of course, could speak fluent German. And my mother was terrified, during the War, that we would be got at as German spies, which everyone was scared about. And so she went around saying, she used to pronounce our name, instead of \'93Pahl\'94 
\endash  \'93Paul\'94, and people always spelt it P A U L, and she never corrected them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 For the duration of the War?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. We took a sort of new identity. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Were you aware of that happening?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, to a degree, yes. There\rquote s a danger of applying sort of sociological insight backwards, and saying, \'93
Yes, of course, I was a marginal person between cultures, and was aware of this\'94. And I don\rquote t know, it \'85 realistically, the marginality was a Londoner in a small village. That really was the difference. And I re
member that at boarding school, the \'85 my chief mate, for a long time, was a guy called \'93Millett\'94, we always called people by \'85 \'93Millett\rquote s Stores\'94
 as it later appeared. And there was far more antagonism towards him, as a Jew, than the fact that I\rquote d got a German name. And we were all in the gang, you know, looking for German spies and this kind of thing. But I never felt that the boys were 
\'85 whilst I may have been bullied, for a time, for being cleverer than my peers and, therefore, you know \'85 out of the pres
sure to conform, I never noticed anything to do with my name being a trouble. My mother was far more conscious of it, and I think I picked that up. And she would be nagging my father, you know, to hide any \'85 any feelings that he was \'85
 you know, different from the others. And he \'85 because it was odd for him, because he \'85
 it was really quite a lonely job. And I guess, actually, that it was a kind of control, that there may have been some suspicion about him, and it was safer just to \'85 he was, you know, in the
 Accounts Department, doing some really dull job, but that kept \'85 people knew what he was doing, as it were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Before and after the War, what was the family business?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It was importing watches and clocks. My \'85 an uncle, my father\rquote s uncle, alle
gedly, introduced the pianola into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}, and so there was an idea of bringing things into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And so they brought in alarm clocks, and things that weren\rquote t here, you know, from the Black Forest area and from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Switzerland{\*\xmlclose}
, and in the heyday, which, I suppose, was immediately after the First World War, and perhaps a bit before, and it was the sort of major company in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. So if you talked to old \'85 watchmakers and clockmakers and so on, as I have done just by chance, I said, \'93Well, my family firm was Pahl Brothers\'94. \'93Oh, Pahl Brothers, we\rquote ve heard of that\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But it\rquote s now died out, has it? It
\rquote s not a \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, it collapsed, yes. Well, my father was incompetent as a businessman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Incompetent?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Incompetent, yes. And Smiths and companies like that just came up and said, \'93Oh \'85\'94
 He could have made a huge amount of money, on a number of occasions, and systematically blew it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So when did it collapse, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I mean, he eventually went bankrupt. But he died in the early seventies, so \'85 when \'85 when \'85 I suppose 
\'85 I\rquote m not sure. He had an opportunity to sell up, very advantageously, when I was just graduated, I think, or maybe I was at university. So I\rquote 
d be 22, so it was about 1957 or so. So the late fifties, he was still riding quite high, and could have sold out, and should have sold out. But he was terrified of, you know, being kind of \'85 employee. He was just \'85 self-employed was just kind of 
\'85 he couldn\rquote t abide anyone telling him what to do. So he turned down a very very advantageous buy out, which would have given him capital and income for the rest of his life. You know, madness. Abs
olute madness. I went along there, sort of, you know, as a blithe undergraduate, and said, \'93For God\rquote s sake, take it\'94. And they, in fact, tried to persuade me to join the Company, they said, you know, \'93Pick up a 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} graduate would be very good\'94, of course. I was not interested at all in that. And he was quite shocked that, you know, that \'85
 so then he just \'85 just made a mess of things. He was burgled a number of times and \'85 he wasn\rquote t terribly interested in making money, actually. The big mistake he made was, after the War, he inherited this property in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stuttgart{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which, if he\rquote d kept, we\rquote 
d be multi-millionaires. It was incredibly valuable, and he sold it for a few hundred quid, or equivalent, and he used that money to buy out his brother, to run the business on his own, because he didn\rquote 
t even want to work with his brother. He was just under-capitalised thereafter. And that is basically, he was under-capitalised, and he couldn\rquote t then turn it round. So it just went down and down and down.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
And did he enjoy his work, despite all the money problems? Did he like doing what he was doing? Or did he always want to be doing something else?
