\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No. Mostly now I do walking and swimming. I try and keep fit. And my son has invited me to go trekking in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Himalayas{\*\xmlclose} next month, with his \'93Dads and Lads Group\'94
. One of the interesting things is that, going back to my erm lost brother, is that I somehow transferred the brotherly feeling to my youngest son. And that transference worked so spookily, that he has looked at photographs of my brother, with his sister 
\'85 my brother with my son\rquote s sister, and said, you know, \'93What was I doing there? How could I be playing with Kate when she \'85\'94 I said, \'93It\rquote s not you\'94, you see, and just like they have the same \'85 they have the same way of 
bending down. It\rquote s quite spooky. And so I, for a long time, had all these sort of Freudian slips of calling him the name of my brother. And he got a bit fed up about it, but that all got sorted. That\rquote s one reason I went to \'85
 I felt I had to get this cleaned up, you know \'85 subconscious \'85 after the analytical scrubbing, it went!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Good! Okay. I\rquote 
m jumping backwards and forwards a bit, but I wanted to go back to your parents just a little bit. You\rquote ve talked quite a lot about them. I wanted to ask you a bit about their relationship with each other. What was their relationship like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, it changed, inevitably. To begin with, my mother was just dottily in love with my father, well, they both were, and they were very much sort of \'85 she just thought t
he light shone out the back of his head and so forth, and was really pleased about joining his family. They liked her, a sort of pretty nurse and so forth. And, you know, she did the right thing, producing a son. During the War, she probably felt that she
 was taking more of the burden, that he\rquote d go off \'85 and have a kind of fairly \'85 he\rquote d live in rather dull digs, I suspect, but she felt that she was having quite a tough time, but couldn\rquote 
t really blame him for it. But it toughened her. So instead of her being the sort of sweet little girl from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, she became quite \'85
 you know, streetwise, really, and that hardened her and toughened her. After the War, when the business was going good for a while, and she was getting, you know, trips abroad and that, they did have a time of \'85
 you know, closeness, I believe. But I think that when his business was in trouble, she, I think, got a bit angry with him. Somehow he was letting her down, and then put a bit of pressure on him. Because he was incredibly good-natured, and so she \'85
 she wanted her cake and eat it, because if any of her sisters sort of came, or relatives, he\rquote d try anything, you know, spend all his time preparing a trip, and not worry about his work, take them all round, show them London,
 take them to shows, the whole thing, really just completely laid back. He wasn\rquote t at all \'85 he didn\rquote t worry about the loss of his money or anything. And so \'85
 everyone really looked at my father as too good-natured for his own good, basically. And she got ir
ritated a bit with that, she wanted him to be a bit tougher. But then she liked him for his good-nature, so that was her dilemma, really. And she, I think, controlled him in a really \'85
 unfortunate way, by manipulating her health, I think. You see, she had trouble with rheumatism and fibrositis and headaches and stuff. So he\rquote d get all excited about some kind of outing, and then the morning would dawn, and then she\rquote 
d get a headache. And the poor guy, you know, I felt really sorry for him, he\rquote d get the car \'85 you know, because the car was his big thing \'85 get the car all ready, and ready to go, and the picnic in the back, and then she\rquote 
d got a headache. But then, eventually, by immense patience, he\rquote d get her going, and she\rquote d have a really good time. But, somehow, she got back at him in this way, which I feel very sorry for him. And also, he was \'85
 you know, he really doted on her, and he, I remember, they\rquote d be turning in their graves at this remembrance, but he \'85 he used to want to cuddle her, or kiss her and things, and she\rquote d sort of put on a \'85 \'93Don\rquote t be so \'85
 so sentimental\'94, you know. And I remember how they used to be much more sentimental. But then she sort of toughened up and didn\rquote t want him, and quite cruelly pushing him away. And I felt for him quite strongly 
then. But then, when he got ill, later on, he had trouble with his lungs, he\rquote 
d smoked all his life, she came up absolute trumps, and really, you know, when it was a question of caring for him, she was very very good. But then she did, actually, torture her
self after he died, that, you know, there she was, married to this saint, and she didn\rquote t look after him properly \'85 but which is not true at all, but she invented this saint \'85
 because he was absolutely maddening, you know, he really was! And I had a terrible time with him! For instance, you know, when you had to fill in your form to go to university, to get the grant and stuff, he\rquote 
d never do it. I remember, I would spend a whole term, and I never got my grant through, because he didn\rquote t put it in. You know, he was just hopeless! Just hopeless!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
