\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I don\rquote t know, because it wasn\rquote 
t quite the pattern, to go to university, you know. The great advantage that I\rquote ve had is to have been born in the time I was born, beca
use it was a small cohort, and we really sailed through life without having too much trouble. Just the cohort size, I think. But, no, they picked up what friends and neighbours were doing, and that\rquote 
s what we did, sort of thing, they just took the cues. They\rquote d no idea about what university meant, but, yes, you know, if university was the next thing, do it. My mother had got this sort of Scottish thing, I suppose, about taking \'85
 she was a great believer in education, very very strong. Education was the thing. And she, you know, a tremendous strong push from her. I don\rquote t think my father cared much one way or the other, because he thought, you know, you just \'85
 he still had the sort of business view, and he still \'85 talking about my work, he\rquote d say, \'93How\rquote s the business going?\'94 You know, he \'85 [INAUDIBLE]. But, no, she \'85 she was a great reader, you know, she\rquote 
d really enjoy reading, you know, Trollope, and Austen and stuff, and she used to very much enjoy reading poetry. So she\rquote s the classic kind of \'85 she, I mean, I co
uld see how she was picked out by the Minister and the school teacher as being, potentially, I mean, obviously, if she\rquote d have gone on \'85 today, would have gone on to university. But it\rquote 
s a common pattern. But she had this great love of it, so she must have been well taught.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And she\rquote s from a Presbyterian \'85

