 my paternal (grandmother came to live with us for a time, in Leicestershire during the War. Goodness knows how that happened! Maybe my grandfather died? I really don\rquote t know. Well, I think, in my family tree, somebody\rquote 
s worked out when he did die, so I could check that. She struck me as being very very odd, and quite at odds with anybody else I ever knew. And she was a sort of mystery person in my family history, really, because the Pahls told me \'85
 I know nothing about her, she was a Stahlicker. And there\rquote s a tiny amount of family heirlooms, there\rquote s some silver that\rquote s got a Russian silver mark, and she \'85
 she might have been Polish, or Polish in origin. But she was very much Central European, and she always had a slightly sort of guttural accent. And she was blind. I think my \'85 she went blind at the birth
 of my father. But she, she and I, we used to go for little walks and stuff. I remember her. And she was quite different because, as a child, I remember, she had things about her, personal possessions, were classy, you know. I mean, she\rquote 
