d had a fearful time in the First World War. But he was a hard drinking Scot, and he \'85 he was happy \'85 I think there was some \'85 he ended his days, very modest, very happy. He got friendly with some retired General, an imp
ortant guy, I forget his name, but he \'85 won the War in the Far East or something, and this guy took my uncle as his sort of mate to run his \'85 sort of \'85 I don\rquote t know, not a farm, but a gentleman\rquote 
s thing, where he had all the garden, and some stock and everything. And it was \'85
 a lot of my family were keen on land, and had the complete run, as it were, your own thing, with this gentleman not being much interested, he was just so happy, he really was, and that was up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and he really liked that. And then \'85 I don\rquote t know much about them, actually. I don\rquote t know \'85 oh, my Aunt Lottie, the one in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, she\rquote s a dramatic lady. She\rquote s still in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and guilt comes upon, waves upon us, and we go up and see her sometimes. But she, she \'85 she\rquote s the flamboyant, slightly \'85
 young, very attractive, was a model when she was young. Very attractive. And lives the life of Riley. I think she had a boyfriend at some stage, who left her a lot of money. And, you know, you phone her up, and she\rquote s just back from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Madeira{\*\xmlclose}. And she ran an Old People\rquote s Home up there, and she\rquote ll keep on about \'93my old people\'94, you know, \'93I\rquote ve got to do this for my old people\'94
, and, of course, she was older than they were! And she\rquote s quite \'85 and I went up a long time ago, probably about four years ago when I last saw her, took her out to lunch, and she just drank me under the table! She\rquote 
s really good! And she lives up \'85 I went and stayed, when I was a tiny child, I stayed with her, when my mother
 had an operation, she was ill. And, interestingly, this is a very interesting thing. She accuses my mother of wanting to sort of virtually dump me on her, because she thinks my mother had a whole lot of ideological baggage about being a wonderful mother,
 and a gorgeous time in the period, from 1935-39. But actually, according to my Aunt Lottie, I was dumped up there when my mother was ill, and she had a hell of a job to get me back to her! So maybe I wasn\rquote 
t as closely tied to my mother as she makes out. I don\rquote t know, that\rquote s sort of \'85 but these sort of stories are there in the family. And when I was in the Air Force, we\rquote 
ll come to that later, she befriended me quite well, and I bought an old car and dumped it in her garage, and she was a good aunt to me really. So I ought to really see her, but \'85 you know, that\rquote s a different story.
