\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I know, it\rquote 
s extraordinary! And then we had a long train journey all across the middle of Canada, too, to Moose Jaw in Saskatchewan, where I flew over \'85 not interesting for this, but all kinds of hairy stories about how \'85
 because we were taught under the NATO, the NATO Scheme, there were a lot of Turks there. And the Turks were hopeless! They had \'85 well, driving in the aircraft, they had to send so many T
urks over there, to keep up their quota, but they really were clueless! And they kept crashing their \'85
 in fact, one lot of Turks flew into a Trans-Canadian airline and killed 200 people, so we were very nervous of these Turks. And they were lucky to survive it in a way. Various sort of stories, but that\rquote 
s just sort of chat. And then I came back. But it made me sort of blas\'e9 in a way, you know, you\rquote re flying up there, and the chaps are maybe dying, maybe not. But then, eventually, I was too blas\'e9, because th
e guy that was my instructor was just about coming to the end of his time, and because I knew enough to get by, he thought I knew it all. And so we just went along chasing cows across the prairies, frightening the hell out of farmers by, you know, doing t
ight turns, and, you know, whizzing through clouds, and just, generally speaking, using up our fuel and for our own fun. And then there was some test, and I failed the test. So that all got serious. And I failed it again. And it turned out I couldn
\rquote t judge the height very well for landing, because I wasn\rquote t wearing my glasses. So then I had this interview with this bloke, who said, \'93We\rquote re going to send you home\'94
, which was terrible, you know, the first real major kind of catastrophe. But then the bloke said, \'93Actually, looking at your thing here, when you did the tests, we tested you \'85 actually, on your aptitudes, you should have failed. But because you
\rquote re so enthusiastic, we let you through\'94. Then I had an awful thought, I could have killed myself, while they were just testing how their system worked. You know, they should have failed me, but they said, \'93Go on, give him a chance\'94
, which was nice in a way, but because of that, I could have just \'85 you know. So, that was a bit sad. So I went back and there was all kinds of fun. I came back under a cloud. But, amazingly, they retrained me as a radar supervisor. And I\rquote 
d done no science at school at all. I didn\rquote t even do it at \lquote O\rquote  level. For some reason, I missed out on science. I\rquote d never done any chemistry or physics in my life, at all. Not a sausage! But \'85 I managed \'85
 that always astonished me that the physics in the radar thing, was about first year university level, and was very well taught. So I came out on top of it, I could do it. But, you know, I was amazed by that. And so then I went up to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}, and had a really happy year messing about in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 doing radar, on little tiny radar bases. And I remember, you know, fun, going for walks and \'85 there was just a group of us, jus
t lads, really, running tiny little radar station, I mean, and I got very good at just bending rules, really. I mean, we took turns \'85
 it was like having a Gilbert and Sullivan thing, and a turn at Transport Officer. And the crucial thing about Transport Officer was signing some form to let the chaps go off on \'85
 on Land-Rovers. And, of course, we were isolated the top of the Sidlaws, or one of these hills up there \'85 or was it the Ochils? I can\rquote t remember. And the men were completely, you know, sex deprived, 
and seriously. So I used to sign these things, to collect dog meat, because they\rquote 
d got these wild Alsatians to keep us safe, and they used to have to collect dog meat, and they had to leave at half past eight in the evening and come back at one in the morning, having been down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dundee
{\*\xmlclose} to thrash the place out! And, of course, the only transport they could get was collecting dog meat! So \'85 and of course, you know \'85 there was not much difference between the lads, I mean, he was a good bloke, Ray Pahl, h
e signed the chitties and things! So I was fairly \'85 well, quite close \'85 I went on courses, I went on one course at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Nottingham{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Nottingham Playhouse, on how to produce plays.
