t a big thing. So they all became sort of friends, a kind of gang that went around together. And so one was friendly. I mean, this is the irony that my ex-wife knows only too well. But one of them, I was very very \'85 an amusing and inter
esting person, called Tina Bone she was the daughter of Stephen Bone the artist, who was the son of Muirhead Bone, so it was an artistic family. And I invited her out one evening, to one of these Footlight things. But she couldn\rquote 
t come. And her chief friend was Jan. So, classically, you know, I invited the chief friend. And Jan came out, and then we started, as we were going out together, and you know, we knew each other very well. And I think, that being as friends \'85
 well, not that well, but we got, you know we\rquote d done the same, we were doing the same degree and everything, and we got on fine as friends. I suspect that, I don\rquote 
