\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Up in Hertfordshire, because \'85 that\rquote 
s where I got a job. The two went together. She went off on a holiday in August, so you get a job by the time she got back, which is not an unreasonable thing to do. So I decided, after all the coming and going, that since I seemed to b
e an outgoing sort of person, that I thought of the British Council, but I think I was turned down from the British Council, I didn\rquote 
t seem to have what they wanted. Probably not literary enough. So I went into Adult Education. And I did a short course, and applied for lots of jobs, there were a lot with WEA at the time, but, amazingly, got offered a job by 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose} itself, to work at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, in their Department of Extra-Mural Studies. And it did \'85
 well, it did a course, you see. They did a course, I was on the course, as a student, so they got \'85
 it was like interviewing me for three weeks. So they got the measure of me, and they saw I was enthusiastic and stuff. They were some of the happiest years of my whole career, actually, working in Adult Education. I really enjoyed that. And my heart
\rquote s really never left it. Really tried to communicate to the people who don\rquote t have to be there, and if you don\rquote t, if they\rquote re not interested, they won\rquote t come next week. And that was a real palmy time for me. 
But at the same time, that just gets mixed up with all kinds of things, because it \'85 \'85 it gets mixed up with politics, and the people influencing my political development, which was a WEA Tutor Organiser for Hertfordshire \'85
 I got the Resident Tutorship in 
Hertfordshire, so I wanted to be close to Cambridge, so with a bit of arguing, I managed to move just south of Royston, so I could get to Cambridge easily, because very soon, I was supervising in geography, and, amazingly, sociology, although I\rquote 
d no training as a sociologist \'85 at Cambridge. At the same time, from 1960, I enrolled at the LSE, whilst I was doing a full-time job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So we\rquote 
ve missed something else, because we\rquote re hopping about a bit. Because you did your degree, and then you did your Ph.D.?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No, no. I\rquote m telling you: it happened at the same time. There wasn\rquote t \'85
 the hopping about was simultaneous. So if you start me at 1959, I got \'85 in the autumn of \rquote 59, I got married, got a house and got a job. And then got got at by various people, th
at I ought to put my mind into not stopping my academic life. So, 1960, the following year, in the autumn, I enrolled at the LSE, full-time, whilst I was still full-time at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I did my Ph.D. in three years, with a full-time job!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And what was that like, at the time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Fun! Yeah!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It sounds like an enormous challenge. Was it?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, there \'85
 you see, it was a good job. I mean, mostly, you see, you lecture in the evening. And since I was lecturing on what I was researching, I could say I was preparing \'85 I mean, did actually, a slight deviousness, said, \'93I\rquote 
m preparing lectures. Doing fieldwork\'94, you see, and went off to the LSE for supervisions. And that was my time of converting into sociology. And at the same time, because I was going at \'85 rushing around, the classic story of my life. So I\rquote 
d be going to lectures in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, hearing about what Goldthorpe and Lockwood were lecturing, going down to the LSE and hearing about how to do research from Claus Mo
ser, who was teaching the statistics course. Being taught by John Westergaard about how to handle, in those days, a Hollerith machine, there was no computer! So these things, these cards would rattle through a great big machine and sort them out, and then
 you get print-outs from that. Very very basic. People can hardly believe that, you know, pre-computer age!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So, again, I\rquote m sorry to stop you. I
\rquote m very interested in how you get into sociology, but I want to ask you a bit more about your personal life before we move on to that. You\rquote 
re no longer married, so can you tell me a little bit about your marriage, and when children came along and \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So \'85 we got married in \rquote 59, in the autumn, and Kate, the first-born, arrived in \'85
 June 1962. And Jan had worked as a teacher for a bit before then. I think it was a bit of an effort for both of us to get adjusted to suddenly being married, and she got fed up, very soon, about, you know, \'93Why should I wash his shirts?\'94
 And I was around the house a lot because 
of, you know, that was where I worked from. So we moved house, well, no, before Kate was born, because I remember, very clearly, we moved to a bit of a big house, the back part of a big house in Royston, and I remember the sunny day, her being born, becau
se I had to sort of help with the birth, which I wasn\rquote t expecting \'85 \'93a new man\'94. But the doctor was on a TA camp, and so the midwife said, \'93Will you come and help?\'94 So I was there with my mask on, pulling Jan\rquote 
s legs about, and holding her hand. And then Kate was born \'85 and \'85 with a whole lot of stuff she\rquote 
d swallowed. So I was told to stay awake and watch her breathe for the rest of the night. And so we got very very closely bonded. Me and Kate are really really closely bonded. And so \'85 yeah, one really was \'85
 hanging out the nappies, doing all that stuff, which was unusual, in a way. But, because being at home all the time, you know, it was obvious. You might get a different story from Jan, but, you know, that\rquote s my story and I\rquote m sticking to it!

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So did Jan go back to work, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
No. No, no, she was a full-time mother for just yonks after that, for another 12 years. But then she got, she put her mind to what she was doing with great intensity, so if she was being a mother, she knew everything
 about motherhood, anthropology, the lot. She really got quite into it. And I encouraged her to join me in a project I was doing about managers, and we did a joint book, which was published \'85
 under both our names, with her name first, by Penguin Books, in 1970, \rquote 71. Well, you\rquote ve got it on the thing. And there\rquote s a story about how that happened. I\rquote 
ll keep that for later. So then the next one was John, he was born two years later, \rquote 64. And then Nick was born four years after that, \rquote 68, when we\rquote d already moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canterbury{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And were you involved in their births?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yeah, but not to the same degree, because the \'85 the sort of \'85 you know, the heavies came in \'85 and I wasn
\rquote t needed so much. And I would have been there for the births, because of just being in the house, you know, all the time. But I didn\rquote 
t have that sort of really active role that I had with Kate. And I suspect that in the case of John, I was looking after Kate at the time, or something. I can\rquote t remember. And \'85 no, they didn\rquote t have the same sort of impact, I don\rquote 
t think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So how would you describe your relationship with Jan over those early years of marriage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Very good. Fine. The only problem, in those years, was that her parents just didn\rquote 
t get on at all well, and they would sort of manipulate us quite a bit, to get us on their side. And Jan found it exceptionally stressful, because her parents had got a really nice house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dorset{\*\xmlclose}
, and Jan would go down there with the children for much of the summer, really. But I would \'85 but, after a bit, I would think of excuses not to go, as much as I could \'85 because I found it \'85
 firstly, they [appeared] a bit scornful, that a sociologist was some kind of pariah person, and all the people that one would meet down there would be, you know, make silly jokes about it, because it\rquote 
s a very Tory world, and so one got a bit fed up by endlessly being sort of knocked. You know, \'93A sociologist? How could you possibly be married to a sociologist?\'94 sort of thing. And then Jan also found it a strain, she said, \'93It\rquote 
s bad enough coping with my parents. But with you being sort of truculent and being a bit awkward about it, you know, it\rquote s just too much\'94. So almost an agree
ment, it was better for me to stay away. But, by and large, they were very happy years, I would have said, for more than \'85 for 15 years. That\rquote 
s quite a time. And as I say, without much of a break really. But, the holidays, we went back to the French Alps, where I\rquote d done my research, for a couple of times, because I knew the area, we had a lovely little isolated \'85
 you know, tiny little French hotel. There was one time which wasn\rquote t so successful, because I think probably I was slightly bullying, but Jan came away for a holiday after Nick was born, and left him behind with friends. And she wished she hadn
\rquote t, I think. It was a bit of a \'85 too quick. They looked after him very well, but she should have probably taken \'85 but she thought it would be nice to get out of it. It was a muddled decision, but \'85 and I don\rquote 
t think we stayed away the full time, actually, we came back. But we moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canterbury{\*\xmlclose} in 1965, with me only being six years at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} job. We initially lived in a rather small house in the middle of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canterbury{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but then when Nick was born in \rquote 68, it was really just no good. So, very soon, we moved to quite a big house in a village outside {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canterbury{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, where the children could grow up, and which would be their memories of their childhood. We stayed there till 1987/88.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
How would you describe your relationship with your children, as small children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Oh, very good. I enjoyed them as little children. We used to go \'85 I used to take them swimming every Saturday, 
I remember that, and they remember that too, because there was some arrangement to go to a training college\rquote s swimming pool. And that, you know, very much Saturday, it was off swimming. And I used to take them out walks and stuff. And they\rquote 
d be out in the garden while I did a lot of gardening, when we moved. And they, because \'85 we are very very close, and they seem to have a better opinion of me as a father than, perhaps, Jan has. But that\rquote 
s perhaps what counts in their memories, too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So what happ
ened with Jan? Why did that relationship end?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I mean \'85 the quick answer, I don\rquote t know. But I can give you lots of theories. I mean, I think we \'85
 we sort of drifted apart a bit, after the early eighties, when I bought a little house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Italy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which I\rquote 
d always wanted to do. And she wasn\rquote t keen on it, I think, because she was back into work. And she said, \'93I don\rquote t want to have anything to do with this\'94. And I think I fell in love with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Italy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, rather, and I became very
 happy out there. I used to go out there and do my work, and enjoyed being on my own, actually. I really did. And so that was really a big factor, I think, the house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}
}Italy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I think she\rquote d agree on that. I think that I probably \'85 erm \'85 recognised that I\rquote 
d married, perhaps, without having my, you know, teenage flings. And so was quite excited by the fact that, you know, other women found me attractive, you know, once the children were \'85 so I had lots of women friends, as friends, and I en
joyed that. And that obviously made Jan very unhappy. But there was not sort of a sexual waywardness, but there was certainly, you know, a kind of \'85 a mutual attraction with the sort of women that I hadn\rquote t expected to be attracted to or \'85
 you know, etc.. So that got \'85 got me going a bit, really. But I never had any kind of sustained affairs with anybody, really. But I did have the odd one, but not until the eighties, and it was, you know, in the phase of being at \'85
 and nothing that would have actually \'85 sort of damaged the relationship, had the relationship been any good. So I don\rquote t think it was \'85 and when we finally split, I didn\rquote 
t split with anyone to come to, as it were. Whilst that might have been a factor, I think \'85 the physical side of the relationship was \'85 not what it might have been. Whether that\rquote s applied to her I don\rquote t know. So I think she also got 
