\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Oh yeah, well, that\rquote s \'85 when I was at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I just thought politics was just boring, wasn\rquote t interested at all. Didn\rquote 
t read a newspaper much. But then when I went into the WEA world, I was got at by Trevor Dodd, who was the Tutor-Organiser, who was always Labour, and got heavily into, you know, the iniquities of the world, and how me, a completely unthinking pub
lic schoolboy, had got to get wised up. And he got me quite sussed out and, you know, endless beery evenings. And I was then, suddenly, into the whole business of, you know, class, inequality, you know, dreary Tories, all of that. And then another colleag
ue at the Extra-Mural Board, who was a Communist, made play to get me into Communism. And there was a sort of Communist group at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and I think I got pulled into that a bit. And he suggested that I go off and exchange with someone from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Czechoslovakia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, who would come and stay with me, and I would go with them. But, of course, they were Communist, they were very much party members. But I was na\'efve, I didn\rquote t realise what was being done, actually, to try to treat me as a Commu
nist, because it was a big jump from no politics into Communism. Anyway, I went to Eastern Europe, and carried on going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Eastern Europe{\*\xmlclose}, for a huge part of my life \'85
 [INAUDIBLE] from 1962, because this guy tried to, you know, convert me to Communism
. And instead of that, it had the opposite effect, it made me realise the horrors of State Socialism, so, you know, I was dead against that. And so I became, politically, quite alert, actually. Not in the conventional sense, but because I\rquote 
d always been comparing with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Eastern Europe{\*\xmlclose}. So when people talk about Socialism, I think, \'93What the hell are you talking about?\'94 Are you talking about what they\rquote re doing in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Eastern Europe{\*\xmlclose}, and they don\rquote t know about that. And not many people did at that time. And I stayed in this guy\rquote 
s house for two or three weeks. And I kept going back, and I was quite instrumental in helping people \'85 I can tell you long stories about it \'85 1968, getting Czechs out of Czechoslovakia, and later helped to get guys out of prison in H
ungary. I had a lot of spooky, you know, being followed by secret police, and I had quite a hairy time, actually, with \'85 well, politics in Eastern Europe and being, you know a liberal in a sense. So I found that I couldn\rquote 
t get on terribly well with, you know, the conventional Labour Party, Old Labour, because they didn\rquote t, they didn\rquote 
t seem to know what they were doing. Same thing happened with the Tories. So I was actually Liberal, in a sense, because I couldn\rquote t find anywhere else to go, for a short time. An
d they tried to get me recruited at the Communist thing, but the [British] system got me in the mid-sixties, because \'85 knowing various people \'85 I was \'85 the Chief Planner in the Department of the Environment. Said, \'93Look, you know, you\rquote 
re the kind of person, it was a classic kind of recruitment. You\rquote ve had a great education, you\rquote ve sailed through everything, you\rquote ve got a Ph.D., you\rquote ve got to give your country something. So it will be no sweat for you\'94, you
\rquote ve got to sweat a bit for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, sort of thing, you know! And I believed that, I thought, \'93Gosh, yes! Now\rquote 
s my chance to serve my country. Now I\rquote m a clever person, and I know all these things\'94. So I got whistled up there in 1968, to be a sociologist, because I\rquote d only been a sociologist a couple of years. We\rquote 
ll talk about this when we come to the academic things. But I was appointed to a government job, seconded to the government, with all the trappings of a big office in Queen Anne\rquote s Gate, overlooking St. James\rquote s Park, and all of this at
 the age of 33. And so when I got on the inside of the British government machine, and got to know the top civil servants and was in all kinds of special Clubs that only elite people get into, and realised, after a bit, that it was all a have-on. They wer
e all \'85 they all thought they knew what they were doing, and claiming to do things they couldn\rquote 
t do, this goes back into the academic thing, in terms of all these planning exercises. And I got completely disillusioned. And this links in with the courses I was teaching in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at that time, so I \'85 roundabout early seventies \'85
 (my political career was quite short, I suppose!) I got the idea that ordinary people know what they\rquote re doing a lot more than these politicians who are acting for them. That if you\rquote 
re going to make decisions about society, then not make too big ones, because the bigger the decision the bigger the cock-up. And it probably will go wrong. And all this intervention of big plans, and bustling away with 
social policy, and trying to make the world a better place, it\rquote s a terrible mistake. You don\rquote t know enough to do it. And the idea that some experts could know enough is worse, because then you\rquote 
d be, you know, social engineering. So I got massively disillusioned with this whole social policy thing, just at the time when Jan \'85
 or just before Jan was getting into the big thing. So she thought I was an old worn out, you know, world-weary cynic. And I thought, you know, because I\rquote d been thrust into this from the beginning, and had seen what had gone on in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Eastern Europe{\*\xmlclose}, I\rquote 
d seen what was going on with the Fabians, bloody cocky people, you know. I remember having dinner with Brian Abel-Smith, and he was Chief Advisor to Barbara Castle at the Department of Health. \'93
Well, Barbara and I are going to do this. And Barbara and I are going to do that\'94, as if, you know \'85 Lordlings bossing the people around. I couldn\rquote t take that. So, you know, I\rquote d done a part of this kind of thing, and so I\rquote 
d never be in a political party. Can\rquote t \'85 can\rquote t take it really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
