\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, that wasn\rquote t so mysterious, really, because \'85 well, I told you about the little project I did at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, comparing these two villages \'85 for the geography degree. So when I w
as in Hertfordshire, I was living in a village, and I was going round looking at how the villages were changing, because a lot of the classes were in villages, so I was talking to people. And, of course, a lot of the people who came to the classes were co
mmuters, immigrants to the village, and we would then have the local village people, so we\rquote d often discuss \'85 because discussion was the main part of it \'85 about the problems of \'85
 they would have this sort of world view, and the villagers would have a more local view. And so I got interested in that. And so it wasn\rquote 
t really a big step to say what has actually happened to villages and village life, with this being close to London and, you know, quite a lot of commuting and \'85 new people coming into the countrysi
de. So I chose three villages. One with hardly any change, and it was owned entirely by one landowner. One where there had been quite a lot of change, but there was still some part-landowners, and one where it had been \'85
 you know, the estate was sold up long ago, and it was mainly commuters. So I did a massive sort of survey of all of this, and it\rquote 
s in the Archive, and a bit embarrassing, this naivety. But we did find a lot of information about this, and I got some help from \'85 one of the young women who did
 some of the interviewing for me. That was fine. I enjoyed that. And that started me off with the idea that it\rquote s fun to do co-operative research. I enjoyed that a lot. And that developed a number of things. Firstly it developed a real love of \'85
 of doing one\rquote s own ethnography, just going out there and finding out. I really enjoy that. And I read the community studies that were being done about that time, and I got really quite excited about them, and thought that\rquote 
s where it all was. John Westergaard taught me that you\rquote 
ve got to be very rigorous, in terms of numbers. He was, you know, he would just see a false percentage point, just looking at a string of figures and see what was wrong with them. I learnt a lot from him at the LSE. I wasn\rquote t, really, by nature,
 keen on that kind of thing. So I got interested, and he was very much dominated by class, so I got into the whole of analysis of class from him. I also was muchh struck by the way that people deluded themselves by the way that they described what was goi
ng on, because you\rquote d become a bit like God in one of these Community Studies because you get all the stories of everybody. You can see what\rquote s going on, and then you think, \'93Well, how the hell can these people really believe that? It
\rquote s just not true!\'94 And I developed this notion of a \'93village in the mind\'94
, and the sort of way they put their world, it was all just props that fitted their kind of model of what they wanted the village to be. And I saw that very clearly, and wrote it up, and then everyone said, \'93Why \'85 why do you say these things?\'94
 they said.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Who objected?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The people, the respondents. You know, \'93We\rquote ve told you all this, and we know it\rquote 
s true, but why do you have to say it?\'94 So, yes, it\rquote s this idea of people wanting to live in their delusions. I was very puzzled about that, and I always have been \'85 in life generally, how people do that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, maybe you were exposing something that was uncomfortable \'85
