\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Oh, it was right to do it. I think I best \'85 a new phrase I picked up this week is, \'93
Telling the truth to the powerful\'94. It\rquote s mostly the powerful that have been disturbed by it. The people on the bottom of the pile haven\rquote t got much to lose, because they know what\rquote 
s going on, in a way. I mean, how can they delude themselves, when they\rquote ve not got much? So \'85 we\rquote ll come to my Sheppey Project later on, because that was very important. And when you say, what led me to change? It was that. I didn\rquote 
t change much until then, I don\rquote t think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So, before you changed, how would you describe yourself, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I think, to be honest, when one\rquote s younger, one\rquote 
s a bit cocky, and one took pleasure, I think, probably in discomforting the powerful, just for the hell of it, you know. A sort of mockery, really. It was a combination of sociology and \'93Beyond the Fringe\'94, really. It was a bit of \'85 you know 
\'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 S
o who were the powerful that you were mocking?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Pompous people. Always \'85 I mean, a lot of people have to do that to defend themselves. If you\rquote 
d have studied the managers, when I was at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I interviewed them first, they would give you one story, then they\rquote d say, \'93
But, of course, you know, this is what the wife thinks\'94. But then the wives would write to us and tell us some quite different story. And when Marie Corbin was working with me, she\rquote d get an interview with the wives at their hom
e, and get a different story, depending whether the chap was in the kitchen or not, whether he could hear. And then, sometimes, going back to the train, he\rquote d tell her, \'93Of course, the wife said this\'94, or \'93
I told you this was from the wife. But really, I\rquote ll tell you what it really is\'94. So there are all these layers of what, really, people think are going on, and what they wanted to believe. And I suppose that I always felt, well \'85 it\rquote 
s exposing that. It\rquote s exposing \'85 it\rquote s a kind of a \'85 a defence. A social con
struction of reality that prevents them seeing how vulnerable they are. We all do it. A chap that influenced me a lot, actually, in this particular approach, apart from Berger and Luckmann, since we\rquote 
re being more sort of work-oriented. Joe Benshan who wrote a book called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Small Town in Mass Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
, and a number of other books, and he had this sort of \'85 very sharp way of exposing what advertising executives, and, of course, they were a great target for it and the public relations people, and all this stuff,
 and there was a style that I think people like Michael Frayn, a columnist in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Guardian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
 at the time, also adopted, and, to some degree, Miles Kington in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Independent}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  has been doing it in recent years. It\rquote 
s just seeing the complete nonsense of a lot of the public life. The sort of play acting that people are doing. You know, it may be necessary for the world to go on. But Jan didn\rquote 
t like that degree of what she thought was destructive. But I think, maybe, you know, some sense of this is an excuse, perhaps, can be something of the sort of court jester that can point out \'85
 the court jester was paid, in mediaeval times, to say the unpalatable. And there\rquote s a role for that. But the co-option has been so vigorous in recent years, that people are rolling over and having their tummies tickled by what they call the \'93
users\'94 and \'93beneficiaries\'94 now in the world of ESRC grants. You have to please your users and beneficiaries, which is the very people that you are, in fact \'85 Jack Winkles did some research in the earl
y seventies, on Boards of Directors, and we just sat as a fly on the wall in the Boards of companies like ICI, and just watched what they were doing, and watched them at lunchtime and stuff. And Jack was very perceptive, very perceptive himself, and he wa
s very good at this. The tragedy is he never then wrote it up. But, these were the movers and shakers of capitalist economy, and when you see them, you know, feet of clay, as it were, you ruin the minds, you couldn\rquote 
t run a society if everybody saw their powerful as people with feet of clay. It couldn\rquote t be done. So there has to be this kind of setting up of positive \'85 And Paul Stirling, who was my professor at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he\rquote d got a very good way of seeing through pomposity, and so had Ernest Gellner. And so \'85
 there was a certain style of people who, I think, have done quite good in opening this up. But if you go in the whole social policy area, you have to take everything far more seriously, and, you know, you start believing the stuff. Instead o
f maligning it, you support it. And that\rquote s been \'85 that\rquote s a big, big \'85 sort of theme in my early work. And in the early 1970s, I did this course with Krishan Kumar, called \'93Sociological Theory and Social Practice\'94
 which is, you know, how can you make the world better, and what could sociologists tell you about it? And it was a good course, actually. But to begin with, the Professor of Social Policy kept \'85
 into a compulsory class for his social work and social policy people. But it became so dangerous, damaging to them, that he stopped them taking it, because it made them \'85 well, it rocked them too much from the kind of \'85 you know \'85
 the quasi-certainties that they needed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So what do you think the role of the sociologist should be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15615334\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Tell it as it
 is as best you can. Telling the truth to the powerful. There needs to be some kind of theory, but I think that \'85 I\rquote ve always been \'85 really, a disciple of David Lockwood, How is Social Order Possible? And he\rquote 
s struggled with it all his life, and he\rquote s not sure. In fact, he says in the book of his life work, a very ambiguous book, that the great thinkers of sociology haven\rquote t sorted it out. You know \'85 there\rquote 
s a great conflict, really, there, between the work of Marx and the work of Durkheim, and there has to be a result. Each beats the other, and they can\rquote t be brought together, which is the essence of his thing. So if you\rquote 
re with a subject that has got a basic ambiguity, an unresolvable ambiguity at its core, it\rquote s going to be dead difficult for students to grasp that, because they need a bit of maturity to cope with an ambiguity. That\rquote s why sociology at it
\rquote s lowest level, \lquote A\rquote  level, is a most bizarre subject, because of the constructions, and you have to spend a lot of time getting rid of. So, no, I\rquote m curious ab
out how society could operate, and then how the sort of structures and roles and relationships, within that society, work out. I\rquote 
m always interested in some of the kind of empirical findings, those are slightly counter-intuitive. Like, no matter how rich a society, it\rquote 
s the level of inequality between the rich and the poor that determines the quality of their health, because rich societies that have a \'85 even though the poorest here are richer than some other societies, then the inequalities increase. And that
\rquote s an interesting finding.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
You wrote in the CV that you sent to me, that you\rquote d combined a career of sociological research with public service. And I wondered what \'85 you said, earlier, something about why that had come about, in a sense, initial
ly, I think. And I wondered if you could say more, really, about why it came about, and whether it was a natural alliance for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, because \'85 I mean, I\rquote ve changed, you see. I really did think that one ought to try and \'93do good\'94
. So I would probably say that I thought I was going to put the world to rights. And so \'85 some years I worked inside government \'85 as insider, trying to tell these sort of stupid people outside what to do. And I got disillusioned with it really. But 
\'85 I think that particular CV that you\rquote re reading \'85 I\rquote m slightly embarrassed, because it was aimed at persuading somebody that I wanted to do something else, which \'85 perhaps is \'85 a reflection \'85 just I don\rquote 
t want to do. So that was a kind of construction. Anyway, when I worked on the Archbishop\rquote s Commission on Urban Priority Areas, I wish, actually, I\rquote d put more time and effort into that, because I didn\rquote 
t think it was going to have the kind of impact that it did.
