\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Faith in the City}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 ? That\rquote s
 right. And I sort of went along with a kind of Fabian interventionism because, you know, that was the way that everyone was going to agree, instead of actually recognising that the critique of the New Right was more powerful than we were giving it - what
\rquote s the word? - credibility for. We didn\rquote t think it was that important, but \'85 it turned out that if we\rquote d attacked that more directly, we\rquote 
d have had more of an impact. But in terms of sort of doing good, I did work for the University Grants Committee for ten 
years, and the results were good, because Mrs. Thatcher came in determined that sociology should suffer, because she thought it was complete rubbish, didn\rquote 
t she, as we all know. And the civil servant was phoning me up to sort of sound me out, says, \'93You know, you are going to have a tough time, because sociology is not going to be the flavour of the month for the next few years\'94
. And I think, I mean, sociology was hugely more strong at the end of the period than when it began. It really flourished in the 19
80s. How did that happen? Because throughout that period, I was the one that was, you know at the money-bags end of it, in sociology. I think that partly it was collegial support, that other people on the Committee wouldn\rquote 
t stab Ray in the back when he was in the room, and they couldn\rquote 
t do it when I was outside the room, because, you know, the others would notice. So just being there was important. Not saying anything, but, you know, being agreeable, and looking reasonably presentable in a suit. I think tha
t is as important as anything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Why? Why was that so important? Because you were a well-known figure?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, because \'85 because the general \'85
 the old style of academics favour decency, but, you know, who are we, as economists, or as psychologists, to put the boot into sociology, even if Mrs. Thatcher wants us to? Because here\rquote s Ray, we don\rquote t do that. We\rquote 
re open to a diversity of opinions. We\rquote re not thinking sociology\rquote s that marvellous, but they\rquote re not actually going to collude in destroying it. Number two thing \'85
 is that I had to go round all the universities and look at sociology and encourage it, and point out the good things and the bad things, and I tried to do that fairly. And I think \'85 my experience was that the Vice-Chancellors listened t
o what I said, and members of the committees listened to what I said. It\rquote s not unreasonable, and one doesn\rquote t seem to be an ogre, they just didn\rquote t see me as an ogre. I think there\rquote s not so much what I did do, as what I didn
\rquote t do. I mean, I didn\rquote t put people\rquote s backs up, they didn\rquote t feel that, you know, here\rquote s someone to be afraid of. I just said, you know, \'93We, as a group of sensible academics, can see there\rquote s a problem here\'94
, you know. \'93Vice-Chancellor, what are you going to about sociology in your university? The students want to do it, it\rquote s an interesting subject, but I really think we should appoint a new Chair\'94. \'93Thank you Professor Pahl\'94
. And since the UGC was sort of \'85 their grants, in those days, was geared much to what we said, sociology \'85 I did all k
inds of special visits to different universities that were in trouble, and gave a fair account of the good things and the bad things that were being done there. So just by \'85 by no great ideology, but just by \'85
 in a sense, common sense and being supportive, I think that we \'85 sociology grew very strongly in the eighties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So although you\rquote 
ve become cynical about working with the government, you, nevertheless, have had an impact, a positive impact. That sounds like what you\rquote re saying.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, I think you\rquote re right. Yes. Yes, I don\rquote 
t think I wasted my time. But the sort of sad thing is that I was talking to someone the other day about Housing Corporations, who\rquote d got a big idea to generate social mix in housing areas, as a way of making people happy. An
d that was an idea that I was exploring 25 years ago \'85 35 years ago, in 19 \'85 well, no, let\rquote 
s modify that! Twenty-five years ago. And I was working in the Department of Environment, we put out a guidance to people about social mix, telling them, you know, the pros and cons of it. And it\rquote s just disappeared \'85 no one thinks about it. It
\rquote s probably on a file somewhere. It\rquote s all being done again. So that\rquote s the sad thing, that there\rquote s no kind of cumulative understanding of things that actually could \'85 people don\rquote t
 learn, they have to start all over again, each new government gets new people, and new youngsters come along and discover the wheel. So that\rquote s a slightly world \endash 
 weary theme. And I know, when I first got my job at Cambridge, and the Secretary of the Extra-Mural Board, and I was full of ideas of things to do, and he said, \'93No, no, no. In 1922 we tried that, and we know all about that\'94
. And I was so angry. When now I found myself doing the same. It does seem that people have to discover for themselves, really. They can\rquote t take \'85 they have to keep on digging up the carrots to see if they\rquote re growing. I\rquote 
m getting tired! [I was probably getting ill and didn\rquote t know it]
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid15929336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par Part Two: Interview with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele Abendstern }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 held on 14th July, 1998
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I\rquote 
m interested in tracing the development of your research ideas, right from your Ph.D. through to your current work. And I wondered if we could start with a brief chronology of the main areas of work, the main publications, and then go back to those in mor
e detail.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, it began, I suppose, when I was a geographer. One of the ways of seeing the story is this shift from being a geographer to being a sociologist. And I had this grant to go and study these two villages in, in the French Alps, as a geogra
pher, and I really enjoyed the whole idea of somehow encompassing the complexity of everything, because in geography, there was a big discussion on what geography was, and I\rquote 
m interested in that. And this is significant, because this idea that geography had to make some kind of case that the physical, the material, and the sort of \'85
 human, all linked together. Otherwise, what was the point of having it as a single subject? That has changed in the last 20 years. People are doubting whether it can be a single
 subject. But when I did it at Cambridge, there was a big emphasis on the kind of \'85 notion of zusammenhang, the fact things all fit together in a holistic way, and you could really understand \'85 you couldn\rquote 
t understand by abstracting, you understood by putt
ing things together. By abstracting, I mean taking bits out. And so whilst most of the social science disciplines developed as sort of you know, torches in the dark, so that people looked at the elephant and some saw the foot, and some saw the eye, and so
me saw the tail, and so on, but to see the whole was a bringing together, and social science had moved away from that with disciplinary specialisation. And that\rquote s the sort of story we\rquote 
ve got as geographers, that we were, somehow, able to bring together, qua
si-Renaissance people, knowledge about geomorphology, and knowledge about economic systems, and knowledge about anthropology and cultural systems and everything. And that followed, really, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}French{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} of \'85 of Human Geography \endash  
people like Vidal de la Blache, and Jean Brunhes. And I got really keen about that kind of \'85 which later developed into the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Annales{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and so that brought in the history and so forth, and historical demography. So I think it\rquote s p
retty important, it carries right through my intellectual career, this early geographical notion that things all hang together, and that trying to pull bits out gives you a rather false and misleading impression. So that when I started to think of a topic
 for a Ph.D., it was pretty obvious that this experience as an undergraduate, looking at these two villages in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Alps{\*\xmlclose}
, was in my head. Okay? So I chose these three villages in Hertfordshire, we can come back to that, and that led me to think about wh
at, what were these processes that were causing change? Because, obviously, the change was as much outside, more outside than inside. So I got the idea that zusammenchang acted upon, and I picked up, I think, pretty oversimplified \'85 sort of a \'85
 quasi-Marxist approach, I mean, it\rquote s comic really \'85
\par 
\par [TELEPHONE INTERRUPTION]
