\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
And the geographers would be appalled, because they were a pretty sort of reactionary bunch, many of them. But there was a kind of \'85 unstated materialism about it. The basic physical 
and economic forces which led to a kind of superstructure, and they wouldn\rquote t really go along with that explicitly, but that was what I picked up. And, therefore, when I was looking at these Hertfordshire villages, I wasn\rquote 
t really expecting to find whatever
 was changing within them, within them, I had to look outside. And so, of course, I was much struck with sociology, because one slightly felt that this was the wicked, exciting subject that had been kept from us as geographers, particularly as, at that ti
me, there\rquote d been big debates in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 about whether there should be sociology, and it was thought to be a slightly subversive, slightly dangerous subject. And I remember one particular occasion when \'85 I think it was at our house in Royston, and my wife\rquote 
s aunt was a Fellow of Newnham, and somehow or other, the Principal of Newnham, Ruth Cohen, I think was there for tea or something, and she was one of the most vigorous opponents of sociology in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And she picked on me, poor \'85 you
 know, clueless, just-graduated person, to sort of harangue me about the followers of this non-subject, and what a stupid thing it was for people to introduce it into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And, of course, that had the effect of stirring me up \'93Why are you so much against it? There must be something that\rquote s worth doing\'94
. So it had the opposite effect. And so it was really liberating and exciting to come across sociology when there\rquote d been this rather heavy-handed geography. And so it was the enthusiasm, the new 
convert, to put it like that. But I carried with me, this kind of latent materialistic approach. So when John Westergaard came over with a very strong view about the role of class and inequality in contemporary {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I was just waiting for it really, it sort of seemed right. So I \'85
 developed an analysis based on class differences, and I remember trying to bring together, in a diagram, which I must still have somewhere, and ought to put it in the Archive, because it relates to the study which is all in there \'85
 the papers relating to it, the three villages \'85 trying to get some kind of model of the local and the national, and how these two worked together. How the local social system, status system, which is on a face-to-face basis, relate
s to these more impersonal forces. And very soon after I was playing around with this, Margaret Stacey\rquote s book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Tradition and Change}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  was published [in 1960], which \'85 she did it very well, this distinction between the locals and cosmopolitans. So that sort o
f opened me out a bit, and so in the early sixties I was moving from the kind of zusammenchang approach, to realising that things like urbanisation and the development of a large scale industrial site created class differences, which couldn\rquote 
t be explained from the local. And we used to set exam questions about, \'93How far can you understand the British Class\tab  structure from looking at a particular locality?\'94
 So I got very interested in this distinction between class and status which, actually, I carried with me for \'85 the rest of the time. Well, then \'85 I achieved some notoriety by writing an article based on my research, called \'93
The Rural-Urban Continuum\'94, and that really had a much bigger impact than I ever expected at the time, because it was really a mind-clearing exercise for myself, really. I was trying to work out, \'93
Well, what is this rural? What is urban, in an urbanised society?\'94 And it was inevitable, I suppose, that after I\rquote d been appointed to the Lectureship at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}
University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that I should move into urban sociology, because it seemed to me urban society \'85
 and really worked hard, in the late sixties, reading as much as I possibly could about urban sociology. A wonderful opportunity, because we just could build up whatever
 courses we liked. And I just toiled away, reading, reading, reading in what was known about the topic at that time. And, at the same time, I was doing this work with the government, which we can go into in detail later. But the effect of that gave me a s
ort of theoretical insight, by real chance, actually, and it just came to me one day, because the problem was, for me, was, \'93Well, what is this urban sociology? We know about the sociology of the family\'94
, because we know what the family is, or we think we do \'85 or the sociology of crime. \'93But what is the sociology of urban? What is, essentially, the urban?\'94 So my solution, which wasn\rquote t the only possible solution, as we\rquote 
ll come to, was to say, \'93Well, what makes the urban is the kind of structuring of life chances that comes from the people who\rquote ve got the power\'94
, who I called the managers of the urban system, who allocate resources to reinforce, reduce or reflect, so that people living in urban areas actually have their life chances changed by these decisions. S
o these scarce urban resources and facilities, which may be anything from the way that the transport system is arranged, to the way the housing is allocated, all these things, they accumulate up, and some people do better, and some people don\rquote 
t do so well. But that was my essential insight.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So where did that insight come from, then?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Because I was working with the people who were throwing this stuff around. They were the planners, were saying, \'93
We are going to do this. We are going to make people happy or unhappy\'94, and so on. And that was a completely misconceived notion, I later worked out. Because I was relatively inexperienced then, I thought, seeing what they were doing, \'93
These are the people that are determining people\rquote s life chances by the decisions they\rquote re making\'94. So that\rquote s what the social element of the city is. The city isn\rquote t \'85 the bricks and mortar aren\rquote 
t doing things to us, it\rquote s the way people are interpreting these, and using them in different ways, and fixing rents and all this kind of thing. So if you\rquote 
re going to make it a social entity, you have to look at the actual actors in this. Now, I made this argument about managerialism, and that got a very big run for its money, and people wrote theses about it, and became known as \'93The Pahl Managerialist 
\'85 Neo, Weberian Thesis\'94. And that ran for about six years. I first wrote it in 1969, in an article for the Centre for Environmental Studies. I was involved with that at that time, anyway I had a seminar. And I refined it and worked with 
it for about six years. And became, really, quite influential. People picked it up and put it in text books, and conferences were held around that theme and so forth, so that people would talk about the housing aspect, the transport and \'85
 so that was, in fact, my kind of golden glory days of, you know, contributing to \'85 I was quite flattered, really, that one sort of rocketed it up with a relatively simple idea, as I thought. I mean, I didn\rquote 
t think it was that profound, but it had a lot of mileage to it, an
d I did a huge number of talks and seminars, and invited to different universities, and publicised a lot. Now, that may have been a bad thing at the time my third child was born, and I was rushing round doing all of this, because, chronologically, it
\rquote s dif
ficult to sort out my career at this time, because I was doing three or four things at the same time. I was involved with the government, doing the planning bit, very seriously, because the Greater London Development Plan Inquiry, which I was on from \'85
 well, \lquote 70-\rquote 72, was a four day a week job. That wasn\rquote 
t a minor thing, that was a serious, serious job. I was also developing this managerial thesis, I was also developing a new lecture course, which I mentioned before, and I was also doing research with Jack Winkler on the directors. And I\rquote 
ve now realised I missed out telling you about the managers book, which was a carrying over from my work with the Cambridge Extra-Mural Board, and that actually started before I moved to Kent. So it was a really busy time from about \'85
 and starting up a new university, endless sort of committees. So there was a period, I suppose, before 1970, when \'85 well, I was still doing work with the government then. I mean, I don\rquote 
t know how I did it all, because I was doing a day a week, at least, doing that, and doing the work at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and writing two or three books. I think about three books came out at the same time \endash  the managers\rquote  book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Whose City?,}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Patterns of Urban Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , all round about 1970
/71. So that must have been pretty busy. And then I was even busier after that. So that decade, \lquote 65-\rquote 75, was really hard work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Yes, it must have been. It sounds a very exciting time as well, though.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The development of ideas. 
Who were the major influences on your thinking at that time? \'85 academics, individuals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
At the beginning of the period, clearly, John Westergaard was enormously influential. He, I changed a bit as my career developed, and he made me a bit sad that I d
id. But he was enormously helpful, and really converted me into sociology. Also the Lockwood and Goldthorpe, because I went to David Lockwood\rquote s lectures at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and also some of John\rquote s, John Goldthorpe\rquote s, and I got the idea that the really c
ore element of sociology was stratification, from that, from those three people. And that carried me, very strongly, through my undergraduate teaching at that time. In terms of the urban area, certainly Herb Gans, who became a friend, Professor Gans at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Columbia{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose}, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}New York{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, he was very influential. His style of research, I really felt it, I felt that was great.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Which was what?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That he was very much in ethnography, he wrote a book called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Urban Villagers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 People and Plans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and that kind of thing. So I think I found his approach very congenial and still do. I think that he\rquote s a very informative \'85 and \'85 I like his spirit. It\rquote 
s very much in the spirit of C. Wright-Mills, I suppose, and I was also into that. So, because of being involved with the planning, I was someone who had his feet on the ground, or, at least, that\rquote 
s what I was trying to do, but also was interested to \'85 how shall I say? Speak for the people. There was that kind of populist feel ab
out it, which was there with C. Wright-Mills, and there with Herb Gans. So there was a kind of tension there, looking back, between the more theoretical approach of people like David Lockwood, and then this rather \'85
 yes, populist approach of Herb Gans. I hope he wouldn\rquote 
t think that was in any way derogatory, but he strongly felt that he was speaking for the people he was writing about, and I liked that. Who else? Because I was working in so many different areas that \'85 I discovered, very early on, that excit
ing things were happening in France, and Manuel Castells wrote an article that, initially, wasn\rquote t much noticed, about, \'94Could there be an urban sociology?\'94
 What is the scientific object of urban sociology? And since I was probably in a bit of a muddle, looking back, because I was trying to bring together everything \'85 urban anthropology, and \'85
 you know, I was slightly overwhelmed with it all, and edited a set of readings \'85 that was a bit of a ragbag, I suppose, looking back. But he had a different approach t
o what the urban sociology was, and it turned out to be pretty Marxist and Althusserian, but, at the time, I thought, \'93Gosh! This is really exciting. The French are picking up something that\rquote s really special\'94
. And so I went up to Manchester to Manuel, who 
was a friend of Chris Pickvance, and I did a very good turn for the University of Kent, I think, because I recognised that what Chris Pickvance was doing in translating Manuel Castells, was going to be extremely important for urban sociology. It was the 
\'85 
the key point, in fact, in the world. I felt they were way ahead of what was going on in the States, with all this rather empty demography at the time. So I fell for this, even though it was dead against, well, not dead against, but quite different from w
hat I was doing, because I was later categorised as a Weberian. And I \'85 tried very hard to persuade Chris Pickvance to leave {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose} and come to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent
{\*\xmlclose}, and teach Urban Studies at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which he did. And built up the Urban Studies at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to be, for a time, the best anywhere. So that was, that was just \'85 many people have said to me I\rquote ve kind of got a nose, I\rquote 
ve got a kind of feel for things. Sometimes, you know, a bit ahead of the pack I just do have a
 kind of intuitive feeling sometimes. And that was one of those times. And that was very important, I think, intellectually. And a whole stream of intellectual work has developed from that, because I got very active in the International Sociological Assoc
iation\rquote s Committee on Urban and Regional Development, which that\rquote s what it was called at the time, and it\rquote 
s sort of stuck with that. The Research Committee 21. And I got very much into the international circuit from the late sixties. I mean, goodness knows 
how I did all this! But for ten years, I really networked like crazy, building all this up, with others, with Manuel Castells, and Michael Harloe, and Chris Pickvance, and Enzio Mingione from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Italy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. It was very international. Ivan Szelenyi from Hungary, Jiri Musil from Czechoslovakia, it was all \'85 a tight-knit group of friends \endash 
 Edmond Preteceille, and that began \'85 and to whiz through, I \'85 rose up the hierarchy and became President of this Committee, and went to all the World Congresses and \'85 I forget when I was President, but sometimes \'85
 it perhaps says in the thing \'85 was it \rquote 78 or something? And then we started a new journal, following this, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The International Journal of Urban and Regional Research}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and that was massively successful. So successful, it started to make huge sums of money, because it was a world-wide thing. And we set that up, eventually, as a separate company, and \'85
 with a Charity. And I\rquote m the Chairman of this Charity, so it goes right back to 1971 or \rquote 72, to 1998, where we have a Charity where we give away Studentships and research grants based on that, and it\rquote 
s been an enormously interesting success story. And we\rquote ve now got a \'85 a Yugoslav, a Serbian young woman, who\rquote s in California, who\rquote s researching this, who\rquote s writing the history of it, and she\rquote 
s been round interviewing us, and that\rquote s a very interesting sort of strand in the history of science, really. I see the beginning, for me, as a combination of travelling a lot in Eastern Europe, which I haven\rquote t yet mentioned, I was 
doing that as well, and meeting people in Hungary and Czechoslovakia, meeting people at Varna, in, I think it was 1970 or \rquote 72, I forget, setting up this \'85
 or being at the beginning of this new Committee, and then following it through. I mean, others took on the \'85 carried the torch through. But certainly I wouldn\rquote t want to \'85 I\rquote 
d be over modest not to say that I had a big hand in the beginning, because we set up a kind of \'85 manifesto about what we were going to do in this new Research Committee, which I was l
argely responsible for writing. And it got chucked out and modified and changed and so forth, but there undoubtedly was a strand of intellectual work that has gone world-wide, that began from this tiny beginning. And, in fact, it\rquote 
s now being seriously documented. So I don\rquote t know where that gets us, because it\rquote s difficult, because all these things are interwoven. But you asked me about people that are influential and, clearly, it wasn\rquote 
t just Manuel Castells, it was Jean Lojkine and Edmund Preteceille and a lot of other French people who were most dynamic. And at the time, I think urban \'85 I think it\rquote 
s a bit rude about the French! I think they had a lot of bright ideas, but the British were better at somehow tying them down and making them empirical. So I think, actually, that \'85 that the \'85 the Channel slightly moved \'85 they wouldn\rquote 
t like this, they\rquote d say that was sort of Anglo-Saxon arrogance! But it was a creative tension, shall we say, between the French and the \'85 the Brits, and we had joint conferences and so 
forth. But that was very exciting, no question it was very exciting intellectually. At the same time, of course, I was doing research on elites, and that\rquote s when I first met Tony Giddens at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, as a colleague.
