 supportive environment, and meeting young researchers. And that paper was about this. But what is urban sociology? Answer is this managerialist thesis, you see. That was by \'85 so that was in response to the question, \'93What is it?\'94 But \'85
 and I provided an answer that I later decided wasn\rquote t quite right, as I\rquote ll come to. But for a time, it did sweep the board. I think people would say that. It was a heresy they\rquote 
d now say. It was wrong. But for the time, that was the answer to \'93What is urban sociology?\'94 until we had this Castells thing. Because I didn\rquote t actually read the Castells article, it was written in French, obviously, and a not terribly
 accessible source, I can\rquote t remember. But I wrote my piece about \'93What is urban sociology?\'94 without really seeing the full significance of what Castells was doing. It would have been better, probably, if I\rquote 
d been more fluent in French and had got into the French argument sooner. But I got sort of pretty entrenched in my position, and so it, you know, as things happen in the academic world, you get this debate, and it became \'93The this against the that\'94
. So if you read text books like Peter Saunders, the early text book about urban sociology, you see me set up in opposition to the rather \'85 you know, in a rather strong way in relation to Castells, which wasn\rquote 
t the case. I was more sympathetic to him than perhaps \'85 I don\rquote t know, but the interesting thing was that we all got on as friends, and people like Enzio Mingione (Italy) were somehow getting \'85 it\rquote 
s really quite remarkable this, getting insights from both sides, and somehow holding it all together. So we didn\rquote t get, initially, anyway, into major squabbles, e
