s offices in the City \'85 and it was really quite Dickensian! I mean, I remember going up some creaky stairs to this beamy old dusty office, where this publisher was there, you know, quite different from nowadays \'85
 manuscripts all around him. And because I\rquote d got a lot of sort of numbers in my thesis, lots of tables and things, he thought it was boring as old boots, people wouldn\rquote t read it. He said, \'93No, that\rquote s not interesting. We don\rquote 
t want this sort of \'85\'94 And I was quite \'85 cast down, only one publisher. And I think it was Sprott, Professor Sprott who was Professor of Psychology at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nottingham{\*\xmlclose}, and he didn\rquote 
t think much of it, so \'85 I came back with my tail between my legs. And Emrys Jones at the LSE said, \'93Well \'85 \'94 he was a bit cross about it, because he thought it was quite \'85 you know, a good th
esis, and the examiners had suggested it should be published. And he said, \'93Well, do it at the LSE, but you\rquote ll have to shorten it\'94
. So because he did it for the LSE, and it was a geographical paper, and I think Weidenfeld and Nicolson somehow did the distr
ibution, I really blew it quite seriously because, you know, the sociology was taken away, in a sense, to make it more geographical, and it\rquote s still used \'85 it\rquote s still on geographers\rquote  reading lists as a sort of classic study. And it
\rquote s really annoying because, you know, given that it\rquote s had a long innings, I mean, over thirty years \'85
