\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I got the stuff out in the sociology \'85 the articles in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Sociologia Rurals}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  and everywhere else. But the point is that \'85 it\rquote 
s a bit sad that the book that could have been selling, and been read as a book, and also at various times, because I was also sent references from ESRC \'85 sorry, research applications to referee, for years and years and year
s, because I was the kind of urbanisation of rural areas person, I mean, I was seen to be. And they kept rediscovering the wheel! I mean, you\rquote 
d get other people doing studies, coming up with exactly the same results, and then after a bit, mine got forgotten. There was an argument about this \'85 rather a heated argument \'85 quite recently, with threats of libel and suing and I don\rquote 
t know what, by a chap at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, who runs the rual unit there you would know. Simon \'85 I can\rquote t remember his name. But he
 accused some of the new fashionable geographers, who are up to their eyeballs in not well understood French social theorists, in his view \'85 (and mine too, actually) \'85
 making heavy weather of changing rural areas, and not coming up with anything different from what I said thirty years ago. So it still runs. It still runs. And people say, you know, it\rquote 
s ridiculous that Ray Pahl said all this years ago, and all this rather heavy verbiage and jargon and such, but it\rquote s actually not saying that much different. Well, maybe I\rquote 
ve got delusions of grandeur here, but I do, I am surprised that there hasn\rquote t been \'85 and I\rquote ve read as much as comes my way, really substantial developments from \'85
 they come back with the same sort of thing. Not very surprisingly, really, because, you know, the phenomenon is the same. What happened in Hertfordshire in the fifties, happened in \'85 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Sussex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in the sixties and seventies, and it\rquote s happening in Wiltshire now, or in Gloucestershire now. So new generations of people come
 through and discover that change in the village, newcomers coming in, a clash between the old and the new, traditional and non traditional, all these things they come through, so it\rquote 
s not very surprising they come up with the same thing. But I think if my book had been, if Urbs in Rure had been more established in the way it was published, then I think more people would have seen it, and I wouldn\rquote 
t have had to come. What I should have been told at the time was, \'93Look, this is a little bit, you know, brash and na\'efve\'94, as theses tend to be, \'93Think about it for a bit more, work it up, and we\rquote ll publish it \'85 rather wider. Don
\rquote t just make it the thesis, bring in other things too\'94. I could have made a very good book out of it which would have \'85 you know, it\rquote s a shame. So I think that\rquote s a missed opportunity, but I\rquote 
m grateful to Emrys Jones for helping me getting it published. But I remember that John Westergaard was very sceptical when he said, you know, \'93I don\rquote t think it should be published as it is. You should do more work and develop it\'94
. And he was right. So, there we are. So that\rquote s an interesting thing that still, now, people come up to me and say, \'93Oh, you\rquote re Ray Pahl. I did geography and I read your thing as a student\'94, quite recently. So I\rquote 
m astonished, absolutely astonished that \'85 and some people say, \'93Because you\rquote re a geographer\'94. You know, it just ran through, kept going. Oh, I forgot! Another theme altogether. Yes, I published a \'85
 with the sort of New Geographers. I forgot about that. In the early sixties, when I was working at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, we arranged courses at Madingley Hall for geography teachers. And I was friendly with Peter Haggett and Dick Chorley, who were the sort of stars in the Department of Geography, well, they\rquote d been my teachers, but,
 you know, I suppose being a bit of an older undergraduate, one got more friendly with them \'85 because they weren\rquote t that much older really. And it wasn\rquote 
t difficult to persuade them to take part in a course for geography teachers to sort of, you know, zap them up to speed to the new ideas and things. So I was just the kind of facilitator for that, but I suppose, partly out of kindness, because I wasn
\rquote t necessarily, I mean, I was terribly young, I was brought into these new frontiers in geographical teaching, and models in geography and stuff. And I have to say, looking back, that they\rquote 
re extraordinarily embarrassing contributions, because I really didn\rquote t have the maturity to do it. I was really naive as anything! And I launched off into Sociological Models in 
Geography, hardly knowing what any first year sociologist now would know about the subject! So, looking at them, one\rquote s really appalled at my naivety, and I suppose I shouldn\rquote 
t really have been asked to do it. And the books are still selling, you know, I still get royalties from these things \'85 quite undeservedly, about \'a3
5 a year, because they were, again, crucially important in switching geography from the geography that I\rquote d been learning, to the new geography which hit the universities in the seventies and \'85
 swept on, and is now quite different, and some would say has turned into a kind of sociology! So, in fact, probably if I\rquote d read geography in the eighties, I\rquote 
d never have left it, because the sociology was there anyway! So that was interesting, I just found myself, just by chance, just by being there, and that really was, not because I\rquote d got any great intellectual contribution to make, not at all \'85
 in fact, it just was an embarrassment. I wrote a different piece for geography, just to complete my geographical career. Because \'85 rather touching, I was very \'85 very \'85
 yes, warmed, by the way that geographers are very loyal. They kind of hold to you. And they say, \'93Ray Pahl\rquote s really a geographer\'94. \'93I can\rquote t understand it, he\rquote s really a geographer\'94. \'93You may think he\rquote 
s cavorting off with these sociologists, but he\rquote s not really, because he speaks to undergraduates \'85 really a geographer\'94. A lot of people still say that. And sociologists in answer to it say, \'93
Well, of course, you never really became a sociologist\'94. And geographers try and claim me. Anyway, my old tutor, Gus Caesar, was coming up to retirement, and I had to give some Festschrift for him. Michael Chisholm was then Professor at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and got together the cream of us to write a collection of articles. And I wrote, for that volume, \'93Poverty and the Urban System\'94
, and the book was called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Spatial Policy Problems of the British Economy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and my article, again, was \'85 very \'85
 more by luck than by judgement, I don\rquote t know, but anyway, it was this sort of nose thing. But what I was saying that the change in occupational structure of London, and migration of the middle people out, was in danger of creating a kind of \'85
 I didn\rquote t use the word \'93underclass\'94, but an element of people in poverty, with nobody above
 them, as with the middle levels going, that they were stuck there in the inner city. There was a great deal of wealth coming into the inner city, so that there was a sort of polarisation going on. Well, if I had the wit, and I didn\rquote 
t have the wit at the time, to develop that idea, that was a terrifically good idea, because it was an idea that really took off twenty years later.
