\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Right. Well, my approach, generally, is to jump in at the deep end, and just go round talking to people. I really enjoy doing that. Basically, I think research is fun, and most of my academic life has been play, really. That\rquote 
s basically it. I mean, it\rquote s amazing, people pay you for this! So I just love the sort of mooching around and getting the feel of a place, and just looking a lot. So, in each case, you know, I\rquote 
d drive around and just explore the place to begin with, and stop and talk to people, the Vicar, and anyone that\rquote s about, and just chat, you know, what it\rquote 
s like living here, and so forth. Just very vague questions. And they just chat. And I get a feel, from talking to different people, about what it all is. So \'85 and that isn\rquote t actually ever reported, because that \'85
 I make notes, perhaps, but not terribly systematically. I\rquote m not very good at that. I\rquote ve got a bit better, I think, as time went on, as I\rquote 
ll explain. But then, I was just, really, being curious. I have this great curiosity. I really find it very interesting to find what other people\rquote s lives are like, and how they \'85 how they see it from their point of view. So it\rquote 
s kind of their perspectives, really. And I\rquote ve got a curious capacity, which - I just seem to have it - but that I can slip into \'85 the mode of the person I\rquote m talking to. So if it\rquote 
s a kind of farmer, or farm worker or something, I can somehow get an empathy, and I can\rquote t imagine that the last person I spoke to was somebody quite different, because I\rquote m sort of like a chameleon in a way
, I can do it. And people chat away. And I\rquote d got an excuse, you see, because I was meant to be organising adult education, so I was actually paid to go round talking to people, who was interested, who you should talk to? And people would say, \'93
Well, why don\rquote t you go and talk to Mrs. So and So\'94, or, you know, \'93So and So up at the big house\'94. And I \'85 a very brash thing, I used to just burst in on people and say, you know, \'93I\rquote 
m the Resident Tutor in Hertfordshire, and I\rquote m interested in possibly starting classes here, or finding out what the village is like\'94, so it\rquote s this general \'85 being about, really. I really believe in that.
