d always had this puzzle about why people work so hard. I can\rquote t understand it really. That\rquote s been right at the very beginning. All my career, that\rquote 
s been a sort of puzzle really. And, of course, that came up in the directors, too. But these chaps went on this course at Madingley Hall, to be managers. And I\rquote d worked on other courses, I\rquote d been \'85 I can\rquote t bel
ieve how easy it all seemed to be! Because people would put \'85 I was on a course for AEI at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, that was Associated Electrical Industries, it was taken over by Weinstock. A big company. I also did a lot of work for BP and for Shell, and related
 British companies, that asked me to talk about changing social patterns or something or another. And I lectured on sociology, which was the smart subject in the sixties, to these management courses. I forget what I said, but \'85 I\rquote 
ve no idea what I said! So I got to know managers, and sort of a bit about their culture and what they were doing, from these courses. And I couldn\rquote t understand why they were \'85
 what they were up to, really. And why they worked so hard, and what was in it for them, really. So \'85 it\rquote s in the Archive now, so I can\rquote 
t go and look at the questionnaire, but I decided that there was a good chance to do some research. So when they were captive at Madingley Hall, for two or three years, I got them all to fill in a form about \'85 about their work
, and what they wanted in life, and how they got on with their families, and \'85 I think it was pretty vague, actually, what \'85 I can\rquote t remember now, actually, what got me into it. I really can\rquote 
t. Except this business of why do they work so hard, and what\rquote s i
t all for? And they kept saying they were doing all this for the wife and the family, and, you know, they were just being selfless people, driving ourselves on, as they were sort of sitting around in the bars and stuff. And they\rquote 
d sit around, you know, drinking away, and talking about \'85 not much \'85 golf and stuff, and then they\rquote d get a worried look on their face, and they\rquote d slip round the back and you\rquote 
d hear them putting the money into the phones, phoning up wifey to, you know \'85 and coming up with \'85 their whole face would change, \'93Oh, it\rquote s very hard\'94, you know, \'93Working like crazy\'94, and so on. And \'85 \'93Whew! Job done\'94. 
\'93Right lads!\'94 you know, and they\rquote d be back for another pint. And so it was this kind of two worlds that they were being \'85 \'93Oh, doing it for the wife\'94, you know, sort of thing. And yet, it was obvious that they didn\rquote 
t think about the wife except as some kind of chore. So \'85
