all being done for the wife, maybe they should have been back with the wife! I don\rquote t know! Anyway, so I sent off questionnaires, because I said, \'93Give me your address. And would you mind if I \'85 got some information from your wives\'94
, you see. I was smart, actually, I can\rquote t think what got me into that. And the idea that I actually asked their wives too, it was a bit avant garde in those days, and partly \'85 yes, partly, I \'85
 I got into Feminism! This was astonishing really! But \'85 I don\rquote t know how this happened r
eally. But in the early sixties, when I was being heavily pressured by Trevor Dodd to get all into the workers and apprentices and, you know, the man on the shop floor, for some reason, I got into my head, something I\rquote 
d been reading, I suppose, that, you know, why are we making such a big effort to get these people that don\rquote t want to come to our classes, when there are loads of people who do want to come, but they\rquote re women, and they\rquote 
re stuck at home\'94. So I went, this was important, when I think about it. I went around Stevenage New Town and, without any trouble, got together groups of housewives during the day, to give them stuff about \'85
 about gender, I suppose, and the new family life, basically \'85 what it\rquote s all about. And they\rquote d come with their kids, because it was \'85
 quite informal, these little kids crawling on the floor, and me lecturing Margaret Mead, or very sort of anthropology that I was teaching them. How this happened, I don\rquote t know! And I was in my kind of, you know, radical phase, and I remember \'85 
getting on with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Femine Mystique}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  by Betty Friedan, which was an early one, you see. And giving this thing, you know, 
\'93What do you think about being at home all day, kind of just being this little housewife?\'94 Subversive about housewife. I think that\rquote s basically what I was. I think that\rquote 
s how I got to managers and wives, through Betty Friedan, I think that was it. And I remember, it would be a real horror, because they\rquote d all moved out from London, they were terribly pleased because they\rquote d been really no
t very good housing conditions there, and they\rquote d got these nice little boxes in Stevenage, which they filled with little ticky tacky, you know, like Pete Seeger was singing, \'93Little boxes, little boxes, little boxes on the hillside\'94
, and I scared the wits out of them. I said, \'93Why is it so important\'94, I said, \'93Imagine you\rquote ve just got the new television\'94, which was just coming out, \'93or a new table, and little Willy down there takes his car and goes \lquote 
Whoooosh\rquote  right across it, with a big scratch\'94. And they all went white, you see, and winced! And I said, \'93Now, why is that so important? Because it\rquote s just as good a table. Why does that scratch worry you? What is it about that?\'94
 And, you know, \'93Is it right, do you think, that you should be the person that makes sure that everything\rquote s clean? And what about this \'85 why do you clean? And what\rquote 
s the importance of cleaning? Why is the house so much a kind of object? You know, when, in fact the kids might be happier with more muck\'94, you see. So I really got them upset, and they came back and said, \'93You know, we didn\rquote 
t sleep for two nights. I was talking to my husband about this\'94, and I realised it was dynamite! Actually, this is probably the answer to your question. I just stumbled on dynamite, that there was this tension
 between the women who were getting fed up being housewives, and I just somehow put my finger on the button. Again, it was the nose, or something. And, you know, I was scared, because then they said, \'93Well, you\rquote 
ve upset us so much, our husbands want to come along and see this man that\rquote s upsetting their wife\'94. So I ran a thing for the husbands, and had a lot of trouble. They didn\rquote 
t take to it like the wives did, at all. They thought, you know, they were very \'93suspicious.\'94 And that also led through to the managers themselves being suspicious. So that\rquote s what \'85
