o, I applied for a grant from the Nuffield Foundation to explore, really, informal work. I felt that there were a lot of things going on that people were not talking about. Maybe one of the ways in which they were surviving in these difficult times, was d
oing things informally. And this really just picked up on the kind of chat, and feeling about it. So I got this grant in order to do informal \'85
 just interviews, in a very unstructured way, in order to explore the idea of the informal economy, I think it was probably \'85 \lquote 77/\rquote 78, that sort of era, you know. And I managed to get the time off. I can\rquote 
t remember quite how I managed that, because I know that I had quite a lot of time for interviewing, even though I was doing a lot of teaching. And what I did was to go to a very radical vicar, [John Absalon] who\rquote 
d turned his church into, really, a sort of \'85 outreach for dealing with the poor and the oppressed, in the Medway towns, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Rochester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I think it was. And he introduced me to a really strange world, underworld, of quasi-crime and deviance, and people on the verge of prison and so forth, and how they were managing. And because I used his name, they trusted me. I couldn\rquote 
t have done it otherwise. He \'85 he just said, you know, \'93Ray\rquote s all right. You can talk to him\'94. And so I picked up a tremendous amount of information which \'85 I think \'85 I can\rquote 
t remember whether I did record that, I think I must have done some of it. And I realised that the thing was just so complicated, because whilst some people were being devious and being criminals, in fact; a lot of people were \'85
 simply trying to survive. They were not criminals at all. They were caught in a world where everything was against them, and there was a kind of radical critique that I picked up, of people who r
eally resented the capitalist system. They resented working in garages where the boss of the garage told them to put their boot into the exhaust pipe when the car came in for a service, and then they\rquote d say to the person, \'93
Oh, your exhaust is duff, we\rquote ve got to replace it\'94
, and also to charge the person a huge amount per hour, whereas the chap doing the work got very little of it. So they were really angry at the way they were being done down. I remember one guy who, I forget what he\rquote d done, it was a pretty 
minor thing, but he was going to go to prison, I believe. He was pretty sure he\rquote d go to prison. Or he\rquote d been to prison, sent down by the \'85 the magistrate whose house he\rquote 
d just rewired, being paid in cash. And so one sort of picked up the huge kind of cynicism and disillusion of people who were really struggling, who felt that society wasn\rquote t on their side, there wasn\rquote 
t much they could do otherwise. And I got really sympathetic to people in utter sort of poverty where, you know, they\rquote d invite you in, and it would be really \'85 really sordid and really poor. And lads that were just squatting, and I don\rquote 
t think one could get lower, in terms of the \'85 the situation was miserable. And young lads who were working on the market, and they\rquote d go around the markets, and they\rquote d get very little money for what they did, very long hours \'85
 get up at the crack of dawn, go off in a van somewhere. And there was this really kind of unstable world of people who were trying to survive in an environment which seemed to make it very dif
ficult for them to survive. And my memories of that period are curiously vague, although I do remember struggling around very poor parts of the Medway towns, trying to find people and \'85 I don\rquote t think \'85
 parts of it were as poor as anywhere in the country, all the kind of indicators \'85 it\rquote s like the worst part of the \'85 worst part of \'85
 de-industrialised Britain. So pretty grim it was. So I was completely baffled, really, to know what to do, because it all seemed too much for me. I felt that I would see that I couldn\rquote 
t cope with the complexity of the Medway towns labour market. I had to put it in some kind of context, and it was too difficult. And then somebody said to me, \'93Why don\rquote 
t you go and look at the Isle of Sheppey? Because they really do know how to fiddle out there, and they\rquote re skilled at it \'85 and there\rquote s the docks and there\rquote s all kinds of stuff gets heaved over the dockyard wall\'94. You know, they
\rquote ve got all these stories about people with freezer loads of stolen meat and so forth, because they imported the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}New Zealand{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 meat at that time, and the story was that, you know, old ladies got killed as sheep came flying over the wall and landed on them, or something! Endless stories about. So I rather liked the kind of romantic notion of this wi
ld and uncontrolled Isle of Sheppey, that could be \'85 I could grasp it. A population of 32,000, I could understand. And back to old zusammenhang \endash 
 I could connect with the whole of it. So, after a bit, I went out there and decided to interview people about how they got by. And got some very interesting stories from people, which \'85
 which were extremely misleading, as it turned out, but very convincing, about the time. There was a guy that was, basically, a hunter and gatherer, he just went out on the marshes 
and shot duck, and swapped, rabbits or something, and swapped that for vegetables from the local farmer, and just produced the food. And there were those that went out into fishing and things. Or there was somebody else who, a professional market gardener
 on his allotment. And so I got the idea that there were strategies of survival, rather like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Third World{\*\xmlclose}
 strategies. And because, you know, there was no sample at all, I mean, I was really ashamed of this, that I wrote an article talking about \'85 using 
these case studies, to present an argument that the informal economy was much more important and salient to people\rquote s lives, and I\rquote d been talking with J. Gershuny, and if you\rquote 
re looking for influences on my work, I mean, J. Gershuny, from about 1977, or \rquote 78
, was very important in getting us going about the informal economy. And Krishan Kumar, who I worked with very closely, became my closest collaborator, really, in terms of teaching, had been running some seminars for the Acton Society Trust, which was int
erested, which focused on this topic. And so I wrote various pieces in a thing called the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 New Universities Quarterly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
, which Boris Ford edited, and which collaborated with Krishan Kumar in producing some of these seminars. I think they got money from the Rowntree as well. So \'85
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15929336 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Krishnan Kumar, through the Acton Society Trust, in the seminars he ran, and Edward Goodwin was behind some of this, and he was also in contact with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Universities Quarterly}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and they published some articles, one of which I did jointly with J. Gershuny, which is about Britain in the Age of the Three Economies \endash 
 the Formal, the Informal and the Commonunal Economy. So we had an idea about different forms of economic life. And t
hat paper rattled around the world and was reprinted all over the place, the one that J. Gershuny and I did. So people started to get very interested in informal work, because up to then, there hadn\rquote 
t been that much done, apart from what anthropologists had done. Keith Hart and other people had picked up the idea in about 1972, that\rquote s the earliest that people were writing about it in \'85
 in Kenya, and then Ron Dore put me on to that, and said that the ILO thought about this thing a few years earlier, but it wasn\rquote 
t that many years earlier. But J came into it not from anthropology, but from his interest in household production, and his interest in time budgets. So he came at it from the household, and I was coming to it from the position of how people are gettin
g by, informally, in the urban system. And so I wrote this article, \'93}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Work and Employment and Domestic Division of Labou}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 r\'94
 or some such thing, which was published (in the journal that we helped to found,) in 1980, the International Journal of Urban and Regional Research. And that was really, again, embarrassingly influential. It got reprinted and was taken up on the new \'85
 the Open University, as one of its articles that everyone read and things, about it\rquote s all going to be alright, because the informal econom
y is a great survival strategy for the poor. Now, I did have a conscience about this. I knew that just going around and talking to people in a somewhat arbitrary way, whilst it produced a very convincing argument, in fact, I think people still, sometimes,
 would prefer to believe my article rather than the proper Sheppey study, which refuted the article. But I thought, \'93Well, this is something that really is worth developing\'94. And so then I approached the ESRC, I expect I was \'85
 or SSRC I think it was then, on committees, and I got the idea to run a series of linked workshops on local labour markets, because I was really confused. I thought that local labour markets were very important for people\rquote 
s life-chances, and we didn\rquote t know enough about them, and that we ought to get a number of studies in these areas. And I got that going, and I got very good links with people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}
, through that, we got very good workshops going, and also met up with people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Paris{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And one of the nastiest 
things that happened to me, actually, in my academic life, was related to that, because we produced a report from these local labour market studies, which brought together the papers that were given, and a sort of working bibliography, which we compiled. 
I
 think we asked, we got the money from the ESRC to get these bibliographies, and we had to edit them and put the papers together. And since I was the one that set the thing up, you know, it would be appropriate for me to be the editor. But there was some 
problem about simply getting them duplicated. And Bryan Roberts, who was at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}, had been very enthusiastic about supporting these studies, I think he was on the Committee, said, \'93
Well, you can get this done at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\'94. And I said, \'93Fine\'94. And then when it finally came out, I was really shocked, I won\rquote 
t mention the name of the guy, it was someone in the Department who\rquote s since left, who simply put his own name on it! And that was the worst bit of academic plagiarising I\rquote d ever known. I was completely flocked. I mean, I\rquote 
d done all the work, done the whole thing, and \'85 and the thing was out as his name. I don\rquote t know what he did, perhaps \'85 and I was just absolutely shattered. In fact, so upset, that I didn\rquote t take any steps. I couldn\rquote t beli
eve that someone could do such a dirty trick. Anyway, you could say that I\rquote d been a bit fly, although I hadn\rquote 
t planned this when I set the thing up, because, having set up this series of workshops, and having been successful, the obvious thing was to do some research to follow this thing through. And the Committee was \'85
 you know, a lot of these workshops were pleased with the results, and J thought, \'93Yes, well, we ought to get some more empirical work going\'94. Bryan Roberts was very helpful, because he was a
 strong believer in doing fieldwork, because he had a strong anthropological background. So I think he was pretty pivotal at the time, but others as well on the Committee, who were showing the same feelings of distress, that British sociology was just goi
ng along with these very abstract notions, and there\rquote 
d been very little detailed empirical research work for years, of any substance. Anyway, I put forward, after a lot of sweat, quite a big proposal. A very large proposal, in the money levels of the time, you know, \'a3
100,000 was seen to be enormous in the late seventies. But we couldn\rquote t see a way of doing it cheaply, because I actually went to SCPR and said, you know, I wasn\rquote t a great spark on the whole mechanics of large-scale survey research, because I
\rquote d mostly done sort of, you know, my own small-scale thing. So I felt that I couldn\rquote 
t cope with this without having professional support. And the SCPR were very sympathetic. They cost it to the bone, because they wanted to get into academic research work.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Who were the SCPR?
