\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Social Community Planning Research, some of the biggest research consultants now. So they actually costed the whole of the survey, and so I pushed it in with myself as the chief investigator, and Claire Wallace as the researc
h officer. Well, that was a huge risk, because Claire had come roundabout 1978, I think, to be a graduate student to do research on the transition from school to work. And she\rquote d just started her Ph.D.. Must have been \rquote 79, I suppose. So she
\rquote d just done a year of her Ph.D.. But I really took to her as someone who\rquote 
d got the same sort of spirit, and being able to do good fieldwork. She was just terribly good at really getting stuck into a really tough environment. And she proved herself by her courage, really. I\rquote 
m embarrassed when I think back about it, but I insisted that they lived on the island, or she lived on the island, to find out about it. And she got various lodgings. But she got mixed up with quite violent criminals and it was not \'85
 I was a bit uneasy about her living, having lodgings in a house where people were being beaten up, and someone was murdered \'85 and it wasn\rquote t at all an easy place for a young girl to be. But she\rquote 
d got an amazing capacity for just getting on with people. People just liked her. And she could go to the pub, she could go \'85 so we really got to know the sort of underlife of \'85
 of the Isle of Sheppey, before we actually started work, because a lot of the kids that were at the school that she was getting to know \'85 I\rquote d got another project in the school, by the way. I didn\rquote 
t mention that. That was a sort of by-product of the Nuffield Project, which was \'85 I mean, I was actually interested in how kids got jobs too. So I\rquote d done a little bit on that, which was published in New Society, by gett
ing them to write retrospective diaries of their lives. And that was very interesting. A very interesting study. And I sat in on the Careers Advisory people and stuff, in the late seventies. So I knew a bit about it, I knew a bit about the school, so I co
u
ld get Claire into it. And we just had the same sort of feeling about doing fieldwork. But really, she knew absolutely next to nothing about running a big survey. So it was really daft, in a way, that I took that risk. And there were certainly problems. S
o, anyway, come 1980, we got funded, and the University was quite good, because, really, she was grossly under-qualified as a \'85
 she should really have got a Ph.D., but she was only just starting her Ph.D.. But she was enormously enthusiastic, and very willing, and worked very hard, and had good ideas, and so off we went. But because she was so inexperienced, I don\rquote 
t think that the kind of organisation of the project was as good as it might have been, in terms of just being systematic. I don\rquote t think I have to
 emphasise that to the Qualidata people who have got trouble in labelling tapes and things like that. I mean, things like that just got missed. But we appointed as the Project Administrator, Jane Dennett, who was a model of efficiency, although in some de
spair about us, and she did a terrific lot to keep the project in some sort of order. But, of course, the main survey was being done by SCPR. But the way we approached it, in terms of research technique, is \'85
 but the first year, really, some of which was before the project began, just getting the feel of the place. And we were following the research side, which had been done in the States, in Michigan, which J. Gershuny put me on to, which was that you \'85
 basically, got the feel of the place, to learn the rig
ht language to ask the questions, because what we wanted to know was how a set of predetermined tasks got done, you know. If you were going to get your roof fixed, or whatever it was, who would you get to do it? You know, would it be a neighbour, friend, 
f
ormal building firm, etc., etc., which we could then categorise as being within the household, informally by a non-household member, or formally by paying for it. So, basically, it was a who provides what service. Not what do you do for others? But what d
o others do for you? So it was supply rather than demand. And that way we could be sure, say, that they were more likely to be honest. But we didn\rquote 
t know, say, if the, in the formal provision of services, whether the people that were providing it formally w
ere being honest in the way that they declared their money to the tax people. So there were methodological troubles. But it was a well-proven research strategy, which, I think, was okay. So we went into the field, the SCPR were very good at discussing the
 questionnaire. There was a huge mistake in it, because endless revisions of the research instrument meant that certain things are bound to, in my experience, is that you\rquote 
re bound to make some mistakes. And we made the silly mistake of forgetting, somehow, education. I mean, we\rquote 
d got something about it, but it just slipped out. It was there earlier in earlier drafts, but somehow it just went. But, by and large, it wasn\rquote t a bad research instrument. And they got a very high, very high response rate, and I was 
extremely pleased with the stuff at the time. While this was being done, I did another survey with Jane Dennett, of all the employers on the island. And that was really interesting, because we just did the complete labour market \endash 
 every employer that emplo
yed more than five people, I interviewed, and did it all myself, largely. And that became a sort of separate project. Jane wanted, also, to be academically involved, and she got interested in various aspects like allotments and things like that, not all o
f which got properly published. But she did make a contribution. And later on, I can\rquote t remember when, but Pat Wilson got involved, helping us on the project, and we had two linked studentships \endash 
 Frances Evans, who was interested in doing a Ph.D. on women\rquote s unemployment, Bill Gourlay, who came to do a Ph.D. but never completed it, on taxi drivers. He was going to look at the taxi \'85
 that was a very dangerous area to work in, because there was a lot of violence between rival firms, and quite a lot of danger, really, working there. Jenifer Mason \'85 wasn\rquote 
t specifically on the Isle of Sheppey, but she was around, working as a graduate student, towards the end, and then went on to work with Janet Finch on family and kinship. And who else? We had one or two others tha
t wanted to come and work with us, but since I insisted that, you know, they live out on the island, some just couldn\rquote t stand it, and just left.
