\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So was it your choice and your decision, really, the people who came to work with you? Were you in charge of that side of things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Yes. We had money from the ESRC, and we could advertise and we could choose the ones that could manage it, yes. And actually, I bought a house, we had, actually, a house on the island, and \'85
 I had a room there, to stay overnight on occasions. I think I was a little bit romantic about what we were going to do, because, you know, I had the idea that we\rquote d all be going off and 
doing our various ethnographies and coming back to the house and talking about it and everything. But that didn\rquote t work. I think that there were tensions and \'85
 personal animosities between the groups. And that was probably the most exhausting part of the project, just coping with other people.
