\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid15929336\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Yes. I mean, she was just only \'85 \'85
 a bit like the Marxists had been in the seventies, she was being in the sort of Feminist \'85 a hard line Feminist, and did cause a lot of aggravation about \'85 you know, thi
s sort of thing was absolutely clear. We did get some extra money. She got some money to do an ancillary project on peri-natal mortality, which wasn\rquote 
t actually directly related to her project, but did bring her money, and she was doing that on Sheppey too,
 with a GP. And she did that very well, I think. And so that was a stress. Then there was, you know, whether I could give equal attention to everybody. And where was I, and what was going on, and so forth. Because they were really interested in getting th
eir theses done, they really didn\rquote 
t give a toss about the project. Whereas they were meant to, as part of the deal, be involved with the project and sort of feed into it, because they were linked students. It was a good idea in a way, but then they said, \'93Well, you\rquote 
re not teaching us about what\rquote s going on on the project\'94, because it was just too much for me. I couldn\rquote 
t somehow cope with doing the project, getting their Ph.Ds. going, and also teach them about the project. It was probably a scheme where you should have actually put in time for that, and that alone. So I can\rquote 
t say that that was entirely a happy time on that front. Claire and I would get on fine, doing the fieldwork, and it was a bit of a \'85 I think there was too big a gap between me and everybody
 else, because I had to work with everybody, and they all expected me to be giving them, you know, totally undivided attention, and there were all these different sort of strands going on. And where were we going? And then when it came to the analysis of 
the data, I wasn\rquote 
t up to doing smart regressions and logic models and all that, so Spyros Missiakoulis, who was a researcher at the Personal Social Services Research Unit, he was paid by the project, I think for one day a week or something, to help with the
 analysis. And he and I got on to that. Claire, this is very ironic, because Claire\rquote s now quite a big shot in handling large complex data sets, and can do all kinds of statistical things. At the time, she just sort of \'85
 had a complete block about anything to do with computers. I mean, you know, if there was a \'85 doing SPSS, in those days, it was pretty important that you didn\rquote t miss out commas, and she\rquote 
d always miss out a full stop or something, and it never worked, and she\rquote d never know why, and she\rquote d get an
gry, with a headache, and blow up in the steam! It was just awful, you know, dealing with these kind of tantrums, of everybody. And so I sort of thought, you know, \'93God, why can\rquote t a woman be like a man, a bit, you know?\'94
 So Bill Gourlay traded on that, to be sort of \'85 you know, \'93We chaps ought to go away for a quiet beer\'94, and sort of \'85 but that was dangerous if I did that, because then immediately the Feminist thing \'85 so \'85
 and Bill was having trouble with his research, quite serious trouble. It wasn\rquote t getting on as well as \'85 because he somehow couldn\rquote 
t write. Huh! So that all seemed absolutely exhausting. And then Claire and I had the idea that we were going to do follow-up interviews, sort of subsets from the original sample, that we would actually intervi
ew ourselves. And that meant an immense amount of \'85 time, really, in finding the people from the sample, writing to them, saying, you know, \'93You\rquote ve been interviewed, but can you see us again?\'94 Getting a time \'85
 because Jane was having to do a lot of this as well, when are they actually free to see us. And then, of course, you\rquote d go there, and they\rquote d forgotten all about it. And, of course, it\rquote s miles out to Sheppey! Well, the island\rquote 
s a hell of a long way. So, you know, we\rquote d spend hours and hours wasting, and drinking cups of tea with people who we didn\rquote t really want to spend the time, because there was someone else waiting to be interviewed. But then, you know, you can
\rquote t not do it. And then we\rquote d end up in the pub, and, you know, there\rquote s a sort of release of tension, we\rquote d sort of down this strong beer that they made out there. God, it was really powerful stuff! When I think about it, I don
\rquote t know that the drink and driving laws were strong then, but it was a long way back, and \'85 I don\rquote t know!
