t entirely enamoured of his friends, but, you know, one is actually working in a country, and money had come from the government and so, you know \'85 you may not like the Prime Minister, but you do \'85
 so I put my suit on, and I went up there to Downing Street, and went into Number 10, not to see Mrs. T, but saw her smart-suited \'85 advisors, as they say. And th
ey sort of listened to what I had to say. And the interesting thing was that all my clever social science, - they didn\rquote 
t really pay much attention to. But when I told them one or two anecdotes, they completely believed it. And, I think, did something to get the government off the back of scroungers, for a time. I think they realised that \'85 \'85
 So, in terms of outcomes, positive outcomes, that I think was important, was that I did have \'85 that went straight through to the Cabinet Office. I did get a massive sor
t of programme of volunteering. Elizabeth Hoodless, of the Volunteer Centre, somehow got money for a person to go down to do a project with the unemployed. And there was a big scheme, whereby the firms in the area started to take youngsters on and give th
em training, even though they didn\rquote t have jobs for them, and so they hoped to get them off somewhere else, so that Abbotts Laboratories, and some of the big employers did that. And there was a lot of money, and the island became a sort of \'85
 a scheme for guilty people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Maidstone{\*\xmlclose} who, you know, had heard about this. And I did get a lot of publicity. And the third thing is that one of the main conclusions was \'85 that it wasn\rquote 
t the poorest who were most involved in the informal economy, but actually the households that already had resources. In other words, you know, if you\rquote ve got a car and telephone, and money to go to pubs, you\rquote 
re more likely to hear about extra jobs, and you\rquote re also more into doing work on your home, and you\rquote re more likely to own your ow
n home, and have your own capital equipment to work on, and so forth. So I discovered that there were sort of work rich and work poor households, there was a kind of polarisation going on. And although one or two people had mentioned that as a likelihood,
 it hadn\rquote t, again, I was ahead of the field, noticing this enormous importance of multiple earners households, which almost overtook class, because, you know, multiple earners were more \'85
 were richer households than one single middle-class earner, with his wife not working. So that has now become \'85
 my work-rich/work-poor distinction, is now part of common currency. You can see it, you know, mentioned in editorials and newspapers all the time. And that was \'85 I mean, they don\rquote t know where it came from, but tha
t was actually a notion that had long-running policy implications right through until now, and what you do about this sort of cycle of \'85 benign cycle of \'85 if you\rquote ve got one earner in work, it\rquote 
s more likely that others will, because the children will get th
e knowledge of jobs from their dad or their mum, and so forth. And so you can get four, or even five earners in a household with teenage children. Next door, where someone loses their job, and it\rquote 
s not worthwhile the woman, because of the tax benefit system, no one\rquote s in work. And so you get this dramatic difference in fortunes, just happening almost arbitrarily. So that was a big conclusion, although now, with hindsight, it\rquote 
s obvious, because everyone\rquote s seen it. But \'85 that put that thing on the map.
