Well, they were true, but idiosyncratic. And it was only when I did things systematically, through the survey, that I realised that whilst there were the odd sort of \'93urban pirates\'94 as we called them, that we were put on to, 
most of the people who were out of work, weren\rquote t involved in the informal economy, and, in a sense, there was nothing to hear from them. But when I was looking for \'85 I was looking too much for the glamour, really. That\rquote 
s one of the dangers: [of going], you pick up the sparkling story, someone says, \'93Go and talk to old so and so. He\rquote ll tell you how to get by\'94. So that\rquote 
s what happened. I picked up perfectly true, but they were not typical. And that most people, the typical story, which is the one I told in Downing Street, was of \'85
 this woman who, whose husband was unemployed, and who explained in great detail how she could just about manage to give them, you know, eggs on one day a week, and meat on another and stuff, and it was really very tight. But the hous
e was a tip. And I sort of said, \'93Well, why can\rquote t your husband do a bit of work around the house to get everything in order?\'94 And she was really angry with me, saying that, you know, he couldn\rquote 
