\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5903709 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 \'85
 in reporting and writing about the project, was that I got into quite a familiar tangle about how all the different forms of knowledge I had about the island, could be brought together. And I don\rquote 
t think I really resolved this, because on the one hand, I felt that it almost needed a soap opera to describe people\rquote s lives and the complexities and so forth, to get the depth of it, almost fictionalizing in part of it \'85
 and maybe, also, people ought to have a more visual impact, and that\rquote s one of the reason why we\rquote ve got photographs in the book \'85 maybe to make a film about it would have been good, in way that \'85 sort of cinema verit\'e9
, sort of TV programmes, with a fly on the wall, would be one way of doing it. And that by abstracting, in the endless print-outs, from the large-scale survey, this didn\rquote t actually get to the reality of what people\rquote 
s lives were like, and what the problems were in getting by in the early eighties. And then there were all these detailed qualitative interviews. Well, the conventional way of doing this, and what I started doing, was to get quotations from the intervi
ews, and categorise them, and to splice in the quotations in with the statistical account, so that the qualitative and the quantitative complement each other. But I got sort of cold feet about this, which people say was probably a mistake. I felt that I c
ouldn\rquote t really be sure that the quotes that I\rquote d got, plucked out of context, were really right. Although the conventional thing in British sociology, you know, from Young and Willmott\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Family and Kinship in East London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  onwards, was to do this, to get, you know, the quotes that stick in the head, and to put them there. I got sort of \'85
 for some reason, purist about it, and said, \'93This is going to slant people\'94, and I really wanted to put whole transcripts in, so people could get the real flavour of some \'85 and then if \'85
 [INAUDIBLE] the transcripts had got limitations, because it was only the result of three-quarters of an hour tape or something \'85 so I got the kind of anthropologist\rquote s disease of, how do you describe something in such complexity? And I got sligh
tly scathing of the traditional sociological approach, which was to find the issue in the literature that people are worrying about, whatever it happens to be, the problems of the \'85
 you know, the tension between domestic division of labour and labour market
 position, or something, and write one of these highly focused articles based largely on the data in relation to these issues. Because I felt there were emerging issues that people, in the future, might want to pick up, which I couldn\rquote 
t actually see for myself, and that maybe just \'85 almost the data could speak for itself, in the way that some oral historians have produced books like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Studs Terkel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  and so forth, where the richness of the data is there for people to mine in different ways. So this dilemma between diffuse presentation and focused presentation, I didn\rquote 
t really cope with very well. And I think that\rquote s something \'85 and maybe }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Division of Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
 is, in some ways, a sort of cop out, by limiting myself to quite a good analysis 
of the SCPR survey data, but leaving out huge chunks of work that Claire had done, and Jane had done, and our labour market study, which was in two parts, that is to say, I interviewed all the employers at the beginning of the project, and again five year
s later, has never been published, although it\rquote s available in working papers. It\rquote s one of the few detailed studies, actually, of how employers actually do think about what they\rquote 
re up to in relation to their workforce, and all the rest of it, and very frank,
 you know, all verbatim accounts. So, you know, one of the troubles of my academic career is that I sort of rushed on far too fast from one thing to the next. And whether it was because of boredom, because I got fed up with it, or burn out, or, to be hars
h on myself, irresponsibility, I\rquote m not sure. But I think that other people would have stuck longer with it. And one of the things that, you know, I\rquote 
m anxious to put on record, really, is that as a result of the Sheppey study, and other studies that were don
e in the early eighties, in South Wales and Sheffield, Sheffield with John Westergaard, South Wales with Chris Harris, the ESRC funded a really massive programme of research, called, \'93The Social Change in Economic Life Initiative\'94 \endash  SCELI 
\endash  which was a huge project which went on in the late eighties and nineties, which followed from, really, right back to the \'85
 my workshops on the local labour markets, because this was a local labour market study which went out to tender with six different studies. But, to 
my great sadness, the director of that project, Duncan Gallie, decided that it was better to scramble up all these six distinctive labour markets into one, because, you see, the differences between them were not so great as to justify \'85
 so the thing that I struggled for, which was to try and see the thing in its rounded and its context, specific labour markets, disappeared. And I didn\rquote 
t actually put forward such a strong case for justifying the local approach, which I might have done. And then I saw it sort of disappear. And the SCELI, people have different views about that, and how influential it\rquote 
s been, but it was a very very rigorous and professional enterprise which took the whole sort of empirical tradition in British sociology a step further, but what it\rquote s long lasting impact will be, I don\rquote 
t know, because they, again, left out nearly all their qualitative material, much to the chagrin of those who were really committed to doing that.
