\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So what led to On Work in 1988?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, partly it was pressu
re of publishers, partly it was that I was extraordinarily fortunate in that, as a result of the work on Sheppey, I was approached by Robin Guthrie of the Joseph Rowntree Memorial Trust, and he said that the Rowntree Foundation was extremely interested in
 the future of work, and that the kind of things that I\rquote 
d been doing seemed to be spot on. I was pretty anxious to get Claire to finish her thesis, and wanted to carry on in this area so that she could have some support. And so we got some very generous fun
ding from the Joseph Rowntree Memorial Trust, to enable me to carry on working on different aspects of work, following Sheppey. And so Claire and I wrote a number of papers, which didn\rquote 
t do her any harm, as far as getting a job and career and so on. She finished her thesis on Joseph Rowntree money, and I did another piece of work with Pat Wilson, on work and the family on the Isle of Sheppey, which was published in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Sociological Review}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  in 1988. But because I had made this big distinction, which I don\rquote t t
hink had been widely accepted before, between work and employment, people \'85 certainly in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, called \'93The Sociology of Work\'94
, they talk about the \'93Sociology of Work\'94 when they meant \'93Sociology of Employment\'94. But since I had enlarged the notion of what work was, to all forms of work \endash  informal, formal, and all the stuff that\rquote s in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Divisions of Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  \endash  that struck a spark with Rowntree, they liked that idea, that all forms of work, particularly \'85
 it also resonated with Feminism, because it meant that housework could be seen as work. So the \'93Sociology of Work\'94 wasn\rquote t simply manual workers in factories. So \'85 I was pressed to write a book about it. They said, \'93
Look, your little book about work will be just fine\'94. But I said, \'93Well, I just can\rquote t do that\'94. I\rquote m not very good at text books, I didn\rquote t really want to do it, basically. So in the end, I compromised, and said, \'93Look, I
\rquote ll write very long introductions to sections of a Reader, if you\rquote ll buy the idea of a Reader\'94, and they said, \'93Well, fine\'94. There was that or nothing, really. So that\rquote 
s how On Work got to be done. And it was helped by the Joseph Rowntree money, and again, bought me out from teaching at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, a proportion. I went half-time in 1984, which is, perhaps, an important point to remember, that \'85
 I saw the horrors of the senior administrative responsibility being, you know, landed upon me. And I didn\rquote t become a university teacher to become a manager to fire one\rquote s mates. So I said, \'93No, I want to carry on doing research\'94
. So the University said, \'93Well, fine, but you\rquote ve got to find your own money\'94. So that\rquote s what I did. I was paid half-time by the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose}
 of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which I used to complain that I was just being paid to do a teaching job, which, in effect, is what it was, but the other half I got from Rowntree.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So, can I ask you a bit more about your connection with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kent{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}University{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, then? Because that is a very long-standing connection. When you first got a job there, did you imagine that you would be involved with the University for so long?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I don\rquote 
t think one was thinking very much about the future, actually. One was just jolly pleased to be in what seemed an exciting new devel
opment, which turned to disillusion, partly because of the drying up of government funds. But, no, one began enormously enthusiastic and loyal, and excited about, about being part of a new university project. And it seemed to be, you know, real going back
, to think of going back to a conventional university after that, that to go off to some, you know, Manchester or \'85 or Liverpool, after being at Kent, would seem to be losing all the excitement of these very flexible and friendly sort of \'85
 well, a new institution, it developed its own pattern. And it was a nice part of the country to be. So we were all happy to just get on with it. Particularly as the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was extraordinarily kind of relaxed in letting people get on with what they were doing. I mean, it\rquote 
s all changed now, but in the early days, we were all just allowed to go our own ways, really. There was very little control and guidance, in the managerial way which we have now. So it was just \'85 everybody did their own th
ing, and it worked, initially, very very well indeed. Because in the 1980s, I mean, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was ranked 5 in the Research Assessment Exercise twice, which is \'85 at that time, as high as you could go. So the, you know, the trajectory was good, and one has one\rquote s ups and downs with colleagues, as is always the case, but I didn\rquote 
t sort of really think where ambition might take me. I couldn\rquote t see me \'85 I could go wherever I wanted, but I\rquote d still stay at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, basically, so what was the point of \'85
