\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So why did you end? Why did it end, then, after so long?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well \'85 I mean, a number of reasons. Firstly, the \'85 I\rquote d been involved with 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} in the eighties, when I was hired as a consultant to help develop their Research Centre. And that\rquote s a separate story which, which was quite good for Essex, because I\rquote 
d been doing some work with Unilever, and gave a lecture about the importance o
f the household as a consumption unit, and that they ought to focus more on the household, rather than simply the housewife and the supermarket, in their marketing. And I gave a sort of \'85 I did a gig, which they video\rquote 
d, and sent round all parts of Unilever, and it all went down very well about this idea of the household. And so I said to them, \'93Look, you know, why not do some research on this?\'94 And they said \'85 so I asked Unilever whether they\rquote 
d be prepared to provide a research grant to enable some work to be done. And it was dead good. They said, \'93Yes. Well, how much do you want?\'94 So I just plucked the figure of \'a330,000 out of the air, and they said, \'93Well, who shall we pay it to?
\'94 It was like that! And I said, \'93Give it to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\'94
, because at that time, you know, they were trying to get this Research Centre going, and Kent, I don\rquote t know what they would have done with it. And I was a bit grieved at the time about research support, I mean, they \'85 didn\rquote 
t have such a good research infrastructure at Kent for various reasons, and any where to put researchers and \'85 oh! So, David Rose was delighted with this, and got the project, and they worked it at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose}, and he then used that to put in a proposal to the ESRC for a Centre, based on a longitudinal study of households. And he did a lot of work, because he\rquote d got this as a sort of \'85
 you know, it was the kind of sprat to catch the mackerel. He\rquote d got the results of this, about what households could do, and how the dynamics of what goes on in households is crucial to understanding this. So he got it. He got \'a3
7m! And that was very good. And so they were all very pleased at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}. So that put me in a frightfully good position! And then I was on the Steering Committee of the 
Centre, and I got to know about it, and was involved in the selection of the new Director of the Centre, who turned out to be, surprise, surprise, J. Gashuny, who I\rquote d worked with years ago. And so when he said, \'93
Look, have you ever thought to come and be at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}?\'94 it was very tempting, tempting thing. So that\rquote s how it happened. And I thought, \'93Well, you know, I don\rquote t want to be \'85\'94
 Also, things weren\rquote t that good between me and Jan, and she was up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} a lot, and \'85 that\rquote s a different story. And I thought, \'93
Yeah, a bit of a change would be right\'94. Her view was that if I\rquote d changed earlier, it might have been better for both of us. That, you know, I was there too long, and I could have gone off somewhere else, perhaps. But as and it happened, 
I think {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} is a great place to be, and I\rquote m very glad I did. And, as I say, I haven\rquote 
t mentioned that I had another research project about historical demography of the Admiralty Dockyard in Sheerness, but Nick Buck was the researcher on that, and he\rquote 
s the Associate Director of the Centre. So people that I worked with, you know, J. Gashuny in the late seventies, and Nick Buck in the early eighties, are now my bosses! (LAUGHS)
