\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Can we move on to, I think your most recent publication, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 After Success}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, there\rquote 
s quite a bit that comes between. That should have been, that should have been a follow up to our On Work, but it got delayed. Now let\rquote s explain why it got delayed. I got irritated, in the middle eighties, about the Conservative view
 that businessmen really needed to have very little taxation in order to make them work, the sort of joke about, you know, \'93The rich won\rquote t work unless the taxes are reduced, and the poor won\rquote t work unless they\rquote re increased\'94
. And so, I mean, that seemed such a daft notion that I thought, \'93Well \'85 \'94 again, \'93Why do people work so hard, and what are the incentives that successful people have?\'94
 I had the answer before I wrote the book. I mean, I assumed that, you know, brain surgeons, financiers, Generals, barristers \'85
 ballet dancers, worked for quite different reasons, and to think they wanted it just for the money was a nonsense. So I had the idea of interviewing these people, and pointing out that there were a wide variety of incentives, which were all to do wi
th self-fulfilment, and creativity and whatnot. And so I started interviewing with that in mind. But once into it, I got very bored with it, and thought, \'93Well, it\rquote s bloody obvious, isn\rquote 
t it! Of course people work for different reasons! And who\rquote s going to be very interested to read that over and over again?\'94 So I didn\rquote t \'85 okay, I started the interviewing, and I\rquote 
d got a little bit of money from the University of Kent, enabling me to get the expenses for it. But that was a mistake, because whilst my expenses were covered, or mainly just transcription, the other half of my salary wasn\rquote 
t covered at all. I hadn\rquote t thought about that! Up to then I\rquote d been doing the Rowntree money, and then suddenly I was on half salary! So to do research, that\rquote s just doing itself, i
s no good. You have to think of some big project. So I can\rquote t remember \'85 how was it I got into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 again? There must have been some meeting or other. But I was travelling backwards and forwards quite a lot to Eastern Europe, from 1962, and had written a piece about the urban situation there in the late seventies, about \'93collective consumption\'94
 as it was called in those days, but I hadn\rquote t really done much at all in the way of serious scholarly work. I mean, I got fed up with the politics of it. I mean, I think the Soviet Union was just so dismal \'85
 but then, in 1989, things were changing so much, and I went back there \'85 for a reason I can\rquote t remember \'85 a couple of times, and got involved with Teodor Shanin, who had got huge money from the B
ritish Council and the Soros Foundation, and the British Academy, to put on a big Summer School. I think I went and spoke to the Summer School in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, in the first year, which must have been 1989. He was very quick off the mark. The idea wa
s that the Soviet Union, previous Communist world, had not had much in the way of social science, serious social science, and that we would give them a crash course in Western social science, and this was, you know, the \'85
 [INAUDIBLE]. Well, I found it was a very exciting prospect, actually. It tied in \'85 I\rquote d actually got more experience of being in Russia, I\rquote d been on British Council trips, and I\rquote 
d been in Hungary and Poland and Czechoslovakia a lot. So I was very keen to sort of understand this transition, 
which seemed to be just the most amazing kind of social science laboratory. And the ESRC had decided to set up a new research programme on this too, and at the time, it was set up to show the contrast between East and West before \rquote 
89. And I got on the Steering Committee of that, so I was involved in the thinking about what research should be done in the post-Revolutionary time. Anyway, Teodor Shanin asked whether I\rquote 
d be interested in running the second Summer School. That meant going over to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose} and recruiting 20 or so really really bright people, not just from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Moscow
{\*\xmlclose}, but from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Georgia{\*\xmlclose}, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ukraine{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Belarus{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or whatever. So that really took up a huge amount of time, actually, because there were lots
 of meetings. And it was a three month course in the summer of 1990, and I had to set up a staff, a big budget, I mean, over \'a3100,000, and we got \'85 the person who\rquote 
d been the administrator before, Caroline Schwaller she came, and it was, you know, a 24-hour job from June through to September of that summer, really sort of serious work. And it meant that, what with trips to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to sort of get them \'85 general planning ahead and things, it was a very seriously big administrative job.
