\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I mean, I didn\rquote t realise that that\rquote 
s what was going on, but he was always talking about Communism, he was a member of the British Communist Party, and did a lot to try and make out they weren\rquote 
t ogres. But I made my own mind up about it, and, you know, very soon, in the sixties, I got in with the subversives, in particular \'85 Ivan Szelenyi I met in 1969 at a conference. You see Jiri Musil a well-known Czech 
sociologist, escaped after the events of 1968, when the tanks came into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Prague{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and he came to me, and he came to live, for a short time, with us in Patrixbourne before getting a job at the LSE. And so I was massively involved with the whole kind of emotional thing of what happens to someone who\rquote 
s, you know, fleeing their homeland, and are they going to be a refugee, and all that. And then in \rquote 69 I met Ivan Szelenyi, and we got on very well, and we were talking about the whole new sociological \'85 he
 was then influential, but, I mean, intellectually \'85 he\rquote s been kind enough to say that I influenced him, but he certainly influenced me. A very good approach to sociology, an excellent sociologist, I think. So \'85
 he got involved with the editor of a journal in Budapest, of a \'85 a manuscript by Mikos Haraszti, and he was a sort of Maoist dissident, and to cut a complicated story short, he was \'85
 he was attacked for this, and arrested, and put in prison. And I was involved with this, also with Herb Gans, whom I mentioned before, in trying to get him out. And we did get him out. And he, again, came to me in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Canterbury{\*\xmlclose}, and for a time lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Canterbury{\*\xmlclose}, for a time for a year nearly, as a refugee before getting a job in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And now, of course, he\rquote s one of the most distinguished sociologists in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So I was involved, you know, not with the system, but with the counter-system. And then I went off to Moscow, although I was a bit wary about the Russian
s, on a British Council thing, and Novosibirsk, and I just met \'85 I drew up a network of people across \'85 because there weren\rquote 
t that many people who did travel in the sixties and seventies, in that area, and so the liberal dissidents assumed I must be their chum, really. And I suppose I was. But when things got nastier, and \'85
 the sort of Leon Brezhnev times, I felt it was just too awful to go there, and didn\rquote t. So there was a bit of a gap. But I did go a lot in the seventies, to conferences and the like. And 
the links with Musil and Szelenyi, carried on strongly over that period. I didn\rquote t use it to \'85
 I only wrote one article based on that experience, which is the one which is criticising Manuel Castells. But I got the personal contacts, and I think that they tied in with the urban network too. So I wouldn\rquote t \'85 I wouldn\rquote 
t underestimate that on my thinking, actually, on my political thinking. It\rquote s all become conventional wisdom now, you know, about the collapse of \'93actually existing\'94 Socialism and so forth. And I 
was astonished at how few people really understood what was going on. I mean, you\rquote d get the sort of daft Marxists talking as if it was all great over there, you see. I just couldn\rquote t bear \'85 I found one of the most curious things about \'85
 about the academic life, is really \'85 the way that \'85 I can\rquote t understand how people change, how they can completely switch. You know, they can switch between a sort of a \'85
 you know, Catholics and Communism, almost, you know, without seeming to notice it. So all these people, in the seventies, who were all these big Marxists, are now going on about how they\rquote re great Liberal Democrats and how \'85 you know \'85 I can
\rquote t think how they can be so foolish, really, to want to be so taken up with the spirit of the age, they can\rquote t stand up aga
inst it. And I was really critical of Manuel Castells for this, who always was on the wave of what was fashionable at the time, although I would think now, he\rquote s actually come round, and he\rquote 
sproducing exceptionally distinguished work. But, for a time, he and others with him, were just sort of \'85 be like something like a weather vane, that whatever the current of the thing, mainly the French current in intellectual thought \'85 and I couldn
\rquote t be bothered with that, it seemed to me that \'85 I just sort of plodded on in my own way, and didn\rquote t change much. And haven\rquote t changed much at all really. And gradually it emerged, I\rquote 
m talking about political position. The other thing that I find odd about the sort of sociological profession is the deadly seriousness with which they take things, the lack of kind of humour. I mean, a lot of what I read in sociology is awful! It\rquote 
s absolutely, I mean, mind-numbingly dreadful! And \'85 you know, I\rquote ve done all kinds of lecture courses, on just about everything. But so much, the stuff is so dull, I mean, you think about the poor students having to read it, and there\rquote 
s so little in it of any kind of, you know, real intellectual challenge. The only really decent books that get published, and I wouldn\rquote t necessarily class my own amongst them, a
re very very few, that you really want to read again, or have. And all this stuff, you know, just picks up the kind of arguments of the moment. It\rquote s all this or it\rquote s all that, you know. I think \'85
 and then people start lecturing on the, on the mistakes of the past, that \'93Early Feminism was like this\'94. \'93Late Feminism was like this\'94. \'93Middle Range Feminism like this\'94, and it\rquote 
s all so very narrow, and very superficial. And so one has to do it, because you have to set the essay questions and stuff. And it\rquote s very sad. And the basic core questions of sociology haven\rquote t been properly answered, everybody\rquote 
s just jumping around from them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So why do you think that happens?
