\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I think it\rquote s happened because \'85 ooooh! Oooooh!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Difficult to answer!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well \'85 I could dare to commit myself. I mean, a lot of people aren\rquote t very clever, they\rquote 
re really not. They\rquote re really pressed, and \'85 and they do their best within a narrow area, and they slog away, and they produce their papers, their conferences, and they toil around, but they\rquote 
re frightened - effect of educational system - they don\rquote t know, they\rquote re not adventurous. And I reckon that, you know, when I\rquote ve been supervising undergraduates at Cambridge, the undergraduates, in their first year, are often far brig
hter and quicker and generally more intellectually alive than established lecturers in, you know, less prestigious universities. They don\rquote t have an intellectual spark. I think that maybe \'85 maybe there aren\rquote 
t that many people that have this kind of spark, that have ideas and enjoy throwing them around \'85 and aren\rquote t frightened. There\rquote s a lot of sort of frightened people in academic life. Maybe they\rquote ve been made like that, I don\rquote 
t know. Maybe it\rquote s the terrible \lquote A\rquote  level, with \'85 you know, everything into little boxes, and everything categorised, and \'93There are six main theories of this, and there are four of that, and three of this\'94
, and so forth, and the way that knowledge has been compartmentalised and put into bits that you learn \'85 whereas \'85 I noticed this, it took me ages to get used to teaching undergraduates, because they\rquote 
d believe everything I said. Whereas, you know, in the adult classes, they\rquote d say, \'93That\rquote s rubbish. So why are you saying that? We know that\rquote s wrong\'94 and so forth. So for years, I thought, \'93Cor! I wish I\rquote 
d never left Adult Education, that was where you could really teach, and people would be interested, and they\rquote d argue back, and so forth\'94. And, of course, with the globalisation of British universities, you get this awful problem of what I di
sparagingly call \'93The inscrutables\'94 and you can decide for yourself where they come from, but the inscrutables from another part of the world, they just wait for the teacher to open their mouth, with words of wisdom to come out. You, they don
\rquote t understand about irony, you\rquote re just mocking this rubbish survey about this, that and the other, and this little study of things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 A sort of misplaced respect?
