\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, that\rquote 
s a good issue to think about. Well, I was asked, at very short notice, whether I would set up this new Department of Sociology, and get the syllabus and everything, and get the students coming in. They wanted them, and this was something like May. And Ge
orge Soros was the international financier, one of the world\rquote 
s richest men, I suppose, and very generous in his support of Eastern Europe, and worked in a rather sort of Renaissance Prince sort of way, you know, you just sort of do it, and if you didn\rquote t do 
it, then somebody else would go and do it. So, would I do this? And I said, I think I mentioned this earlier, that I\rquote 
d only do it if there was somebody permanently out there to provide the continuity, and Claire Wallace, surprise, surprise, was the person 
I suggested. And Krishan Kumar and I met for, you know, pasta and a bottle of wine one evening, and devised the syllabus, around at his place, and we said, \'93Yes, okay, it\rquote s going to be that\'94. And we had modules, and it wasn\rquote 
t that bad at all. It was a good start. And they recruited some young tutors to be out there permanently working with Claire, to teach the students, and I ran their projects. I went out there and they had to do a special project. It\rquote 
s a one-year course, and I told a group of them that I would go and advise. So I came at intervals and did that, and gave the odd lecture. And they were a really bright lot. And, you know, you\rquote 
d realise the difference between the Rumanians and the Bulgarians and the Ukrainians and all the rest of it. The Poles were a bit ahead. And some of them were \'85 they\rquote d come from non-sociological backgrounds, so they\rquote 
d be journalists or something, and they\rquote d be quite sort of challenging. So other people would say not much at all, and you\rquote d wonder what the hell they were th
inking. But it was, it was interesting times, and, generally speaking, in the coffee and smoke-filled rooms of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Prague{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, it was quite exciting. We went around, and there was a gang of people there. I actually got Ernest Gellner to go. I introduced him to George Soros. And I said to George \'85 George Soros, at that time, was being very friendly to me, and I\rquote 
d go round to his place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose} and we\rquote d talk about it when he was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But then things didn\rquote t go well, because he had a kind of quick hire/quick fire policy, and he was inclined, as he jetted round the world, to meet the various distinguished people, telling them he was setting up this new university, and said, \'93
I want you to get involved. And Ray Pahl\rquote s the man who\rquote s doing sociology. Just talk to him, and he\rquote ll find something for you\'94
. So I got really irritated, and wanted to have a degree of autonomy, which is what I think you have to have if you\rquote re building up a place, and to say, \'93Look, I know about how to set up this syllabus, and you mustn\rquote t interfere\'94
. So, and I suggested that we had regular meetings, and that decisions were taken in the proper way, and it wasn\rquote t easy to get people to turn up to meetings, and, basically, he thought that I was upsetting people by \'85 trying to 
carve out a degree of autonomy for the academics. Anyway, I was sitting in my room at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Kent
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} on one occasion, and I just said I wanted to speak to him, because I was unhappy with what he was doing. So he phoned me up from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}New York{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And I was really angry with him. I said, \'93Look, you know, I respect your generosity and so on, but what you\rquote re doing is just not the way you get a university going. It\rquote s not a sort of little club that you set up. It\rquote 
s an independent thing and you\rquote ve got to have \'85 expect people to disagree\'94, and I really ranted away at him. And I put the phone down, and I thought, \'93My God! This guy is one of the most powerful people in the world, and you\rquote 
ve brought the \'85 [INAUDIBLE] down a bit later, he\rquote s \'85 \'94 [INAUDIBLE]. Well, of course, he fired me! And the people there were a bit sort of embarrassed, because they realised that I\rquote 
d set them up, and Claire, ever diplomatic Claire, got just a brilliant tactic of just keeping her head down. And it carried on for a bit longer in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Prague{\*\xmlclose}, and then he moved it to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Warsaw{\*\xmlclose}, and then left and went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Vienna{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and a lot of the early spirit disappeared. He appointed another Rector and then fired him. So I\rquote m in very distinguished company with the people who have been and gone as it were! And I suspect there were faults on my side too, but he wasn\rquote 
t the sort of person to talk things through, he was just, \'93Agree with everything I say, or you\rquote re out\'94, and so out I went \'85 I\rquote d been doing it for two or th
ree years. But it was terrific fun, and Krishan stayed on a bit longer, Krishan Kumar, he stayed on for another year. And I went on about what a quisling he was and so forth! But he was enjoying it. And Ernest Gellner was sharper, and had got himself a co
ntract, which I didn\rquote t have. I really should have got a contract. It was madness not to have a contract. And he got a contract which meant that Soros couldn\rquote t fire him. And so he stayed on until, coming back from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Budapest{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} one day, he fell down with
 a heart attack, at 67, which was a bit of a fright to all of us. But, of course, he was perfectly suited to it, and it would have been wonderful if he\rquote d \'85 but he\rquote 
d have been fed up, the way it changed. No, that was an exciting time, and it was very exciting for me to do it at the age of \'85 whenever I started, 55, 56. It was like, you know, starting a new university when you were 26, really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 You just mentioned earlier that we haven
\rquote t said anything, really, about your lecturing at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and the development of that. Do you want to say something about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, what\rquote 
s different about what I did from what any other professor would have done? I mean, I think if one tries to answer that question \'85 I suppose I\rquote ve spread around mo
re than many. I mean, many professors have stuck with their specialism and lectured on it all the way through, whereas I got fed up with urban sociology. I enjoyed teaching the course on sociological theory and social practice with Krishan. And I\rquote 
ve taught just about every course except political sociology. I\rquote ve taught family and stuff. But one of the \'85 I became almost a supply teacher after \rquote 
84, because when people were off on leave, they sort of asked me to stand in, very often, because I could turn my ha
nd to it. And I learnt a lot, you know, doing different courses on work and organisation, and a bit on theory, and so on. In the early days, I did more on theory. I had a course called Principles of Social Interaction, which I enjoyed teaching with Krisha
n
, that went on for some years. That was a very popular course. But then, towards the end of my time at Kent, I took over from Mary Evans, the Sex, Gender and Society course, which was, you know, very touchy/feely, and packed out with, you know, about 50 y
oung women and two men, all wanting to learn about, you know, exciting Feminist things. So \'85
 about this time, I was also getting very interested both in theory and practice, and psychoanalysis, and so, you know, really took Freud and all the rest of it on b
oard, and was much interested by the way that Feminists had approached that, and thought there were some interesting, really interesting, ideas there, that were important for me as a person, as well as the students. The students found it a bit tough going
. I think I was a bit mean, in that I was probably, you know, teaching to teach myself, as much as anything else. But it was important, I think, to avoid the kind of trivial approach, the sort of percentage pointism which some, I feel some Feminists \'85 
\'93There\rquote s only 47 per cent of accountants are women, and until we\rquote ve got 50 per cent of all accountants as women, then it\rquote s a terrible disaster in the world\'94, and that kind of percentage point thing, you know. \'93
Women have only got 38 per cent of the salary of a person in this job \'85 until we get more \'85\'94 all that stuff. So, and that just becomes stories, really, because \'85 you know, what\rquote 
s interesting is not the fact of the stories, but what is it that makes the difference, and why? And, you know, patriarchy, capita
lism, you know, all these things. But how you actually put that down into practice, how you work that through, what is patriarchy? So I found that the whole issue was really very interesting, but a \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 \'85
 Feminist theory and psychoanalytical theory as well have influenced your work, then, rather than your personal life. How do they influence your approach to research, and the ideas that you have?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I think they made a lot of the assumptions of sociology seem rather naive really. On, you know, the sort of \'85
 the debates about the essentialist versus the social constructionist and so forth, I mean, how far are we basically gendered by biology, and how far \'85 you know \'85 is it socially constructed and things? And, obviously, the thing is exception
ally complex. And the work of Nancy Chodorow and her disciples, who looked at psychoanalysis and Feminism, opened up for me a whole host of ideas about, you know, how we relate to each other, and, if you like, principles of social interaction, which I rea
lly hadn\rquote t considered when I\rquote d done the course before. And I think we dodged a lot of the questions. Since then, I\rquote ve been in correspondence with a chap called McInnes, at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and he has written a book which h
as put together, brilliantly, I think, a lot of the sort of doubts and posits I had, influenced by another book, Dorothy Dinnerstein, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Hand That Rocks the Cradle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 . So I realised that somehow, one had to incorporate psychoanalytic insights into the explan
ation of gender differences and outcomes. But the problem is that the psychoanalytic insights that can be dismissed as fairy tales, it\rquote 
s very difficult to give them a really sound empirical base. And yet they do seem incredibly powerful, you know, the unco
nscious and the implications of it are very great. And it just made me very humble, actually. I realised that a lot of what sociologists said was so blooming crass and na\'efve really, so I was thinking that \'85
 that anthropologists are more subtle about this, and go along with \'85 with a lot of the comparative work that good anthropologists will do, but that sociologists seem to be just \'85 chatting on, really. There wasn\rquote 
t much of real bite, and grip. When I think of a really good, good Feminist sociologist, where do they get their \'85 where do they get their theoretical/analytical bite from, if it hasn\rquote t come from outside sociology? What\rquote s it\rquote s \'85
 apart from just numbers \endash  percentage pointism \endash  you know, that \'93in this industry or that industry, there\rquote s a proportion, this percentage\'94 and so forth, little stories. And going back, there\rquote 
s an enormous lack of historical depth too, to what \'85 I mean, Feminism is a multi-faceted beast, and it\rquote s got all kinds of \'85 but incredibly powerful, I mean, one of the big influences on sociology was, clearly, Feminism \'85
 from the early eighties onwards really. But I get a bit worried about what they were actually teaching, and what the students were getting out of it. And also, I have to say this, huge resistance \'85 I was surprised about t
his. When I was teaching this in the 1990s, there was almost a full cycle from what I was teaching in the sixties, because when I came to the University of Kent in the sixties, I was all hot from \'93The Feminine Mystique\'94
 and, you know, the young women of Stevenage, and I tried to get some discussion of women\rquote 
s issues in the course on Contemporary Industrial Society. And after a struggle, they allowed one lecture, and I gave that lecture about Women as a Minority Group, because it might have been a topic of a
 paper written in the sixties. And I had fearful trouble in \'85 actually, in \rquote 68, I remember trying to get students to write essays on it, and they wouldn\rquote t. And the girls would say, \'93We\rquote d love to iron our men\rquote 
s shirts, but just give us a man!\'94 I mean, any idea that the Swinging Sixties were to do with equality is not right at all. And then we had the seventies, and it was all a bit hard, and \'93All men are bastards\'94
 decade, as I experienced it, a bit. And intellectually, it was just as shoddy as you could get,
 but if you said that, you were just another male bastard putting it down! But once one gets some really serious feminine scholarship, like Lee Davidoff at Essex and other people like that, - really serious people, then it became much more difficult and m
uch more complex, and much more challenging and much more difficult. But then I got the students, you see, saying, you know, we\rquote d allocate the seminars at the beginning of the term, I said, you know, \'93You\rquote 
ve got to do one on this, and one on \'85 and what about Feminist Theory?\'94 No takers. So I said, \'93Look, come on, who wants to do this?\'94
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 This was well in the eighties?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No, no, in the Nineties. Nineties. \'93Oh God!\'94 they said, \'93Just give us a break!\'94 you know! So what\rquote 
s the matter? \'85 \'93God, our mistress at school, you know, she\rquote d come in in bloody dungarees, and we\rquote ve just had too much of it\'94. And they just killed \'85
 the seventies feminism into the schools, and just completely bored the pants off them! And they just thought, you know, women are \'85 that we\rquote re interested in this, because we\rquote 
re interested in the sex, but actually, we want to go out and be good lawyers, and all this stuff about \'85 by the way, I\rquote ve missed a whole research project. In the late eighties I did a project about yuppies. I somehow 
got tacked on to some other ESRC project [Buck, Gordon and Harloe]! And I interviewed, and you haven\rquote t got these in the Archive, ha ha! I interviewed all the members of one {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose}, that went into the City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, who k
new each other and what they did, and compared the attitudes of the men and the women. It was really quite a shattering experience, because there I was, in 1988/89, on half a professor\rquote 
s salary, and there they were, but with, you know, four times what I was earning, at age 26 or something! And the men, it was interesting this, I mean, it was not a proper sample of course, it was just those few people. But the men would say, \'93
Why am I getting up in the morning and starting at eight, and going through the day, and completely shattered at the end of the day, I can\rquote t keep this up\'94. Whereas the women were saying, you know, \'93
I want to end up as a partner in this merchant bank, and I\rquote m determined to do it before I get married that\rquote s what I want\'94, you see. So there was disjunction, really. I know that Linda McDowell at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 has written a book sort of criticising that position and saying that women are still done down in the City. But it depends where you start from. And, you know, if you start from the 
fifties, the change has been absolutely enormous. If you start from 1985, it doesn\rquote t look so good, you know. It depends where your perspective is. But I wouldn\rquote t be surprised if, you know, in 50 years time, banking is a woman\rquote 
s profession. I wouldn\rquote t at all. So things like that are really happening. Now, it\rquote s very difficult, I think, to teach a course in sociology, in that sort of area, when you\rquote re not so well served by literature, when there\rquote 
s a lot of this sort of \'93we\rquote re all victims\'94 sort of stuff, which doesn\rquote t really get you anywhere. The percentage points, people argue that \'85 there\rquote s legislation in this country to equal opportunity, it doesn\rquote 
t actually happen, for a variety of devious reasons. But, I mean, I think most people have recognised that, that Tony Blair\rquote 
s got into government with hugely more women, and, you know, do we see massive differences in the way things are done? Is the world now, you know, all heading for Utopia? Certainly not, you see. So that the disillusion of post-Feminism is there,
 and it was a real mine-field for me to lecture in, which I found quite exciting, actually, that \'85 yeah, I quite enjoyed it, I have to say, because \'85
 I could be accused of bringing the personal, in the lecture room, because I did make it personal in some ways, and challenged them personally. And I\rquote 
m never quite sure about this, but it really did relate to their lives, some of the seminars about sex barriers, you know, when somebody says, \'93Well, my father married someone that wasn\rquote t much older than me, and I
 get on very well with her mother\'94 and so on, \'93more than my own mother\'94, and complicated things like that, but not talking about. Everyone was very interested. And if they were discussing anorexia, you know, there\rquote 
s almost certain to be an anexoric in the class, so it does relate to them. And so it somehow does become a bit therapeutic and a bit self-indulgent for some of them, I suspect. And then \'85 yes, you see, it\rquote 
s very difficult to separate out the sociology from the \'85 from the therapeutic. I remember discussing \'85 oh, the new masculinity, and the new man, or something, and this guy was terribly good! I mean, he\rquote 
d got all the right language about how you get on with the, you know, the new woman, new man and so forth. And then it turned out afterwards that he was a complete lad, really! And I said, \'93Well, what are you playing at?\'94 He says, \'93
Times have changed, new games, new times, you know. This is the way you\rquote ve got to do it\'94. And he was just completely cynical about doing it, but very very good at doing it. He could really put over the kind of \'85
 and then, of course, that made a mockery of a lot of the sociology, because sociologists said, \'93The men are different \'85\'94 and this guy was just completely joking about it. So, in a sense, one was doing research, or
 not doing research, one was doing teaching as research, because what one was trying to describe, the people in front of one new more about, they were it that one was talking about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
That rings bells to what happened in Hertfordshire all that time ago, for you. It feels like, you know, your teaching and your research meet up again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That\rquote s true, they meet up again. I think that, you know, to answer your question, where our researc
h ideas come from, and what gets us going, and a lot of this is irritation with silly ideas that you can\rquote t bear, or just wanting to find out what really \'85 it doesn\rquote t seem right that we spend all this time in classrooms, ranting on about 
\'85 you know, the Marxist thing in the seventies, or the evils of patriarchy in the eighties. What is this patriarchy? It\rquote s a label. \'93It\rquote s like this because it\rquote s like this\'94, is basically what it says, and you don\rquote 
t get any further. Whereas once I get into psychoanalysis, I can
 really see differences. I can really see the problem in the play, in a way, of men being caught in a kind of ambivalence between love and hate, simply because, you know, the good breast, and the bad breast, and the feelings of rejection when the mother g
oes, and the feelings, the guilt about dealing with them, and \'85 and so \'85 the same book influenced John McInnes as it did me, it was Adam Jukes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Why Men Hate Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , which is \'85 very disturbing, really. They don\rquote t teach you this kind of stuff. It is disturbing for both men and women, and it makes \'85 this so trivial, you know, women\rquote 
s studies type course that you get in the States, and so much of their teaching is so \'85 some of the stuff that one was discussing, could probably change them and make them think differently about themselves for the rest of their lives.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It sounds like you\rquote 
re almost getting disillusioned with sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Who isn\rquote t! (LAUGHS) Yes, I think that, I think I\rquote 
d be in very good company to say that I was saddened by the way that sociology changed, but, I mean, I\rquote 
ve been accused of being part of the destruction, in the sense that I wrote another article casting doubt on the centrality of class, which caused a lot of feathers to fly, and got into some debate with John Goldthorpe and G
ordon Marshall. And then I made a bit of an idiot of myself, because I was conned into it by my mates on the Journal [International Journal of Urban and Regional Research], who said, you know, \'93
We want a controversial article about theory for urban studies\'94, and I did go a bit over the top on it, but it seemed to me that class had become a mantra, and had lost all interest amongst students, they didn\rquote 
t want to know about it. So instead of the class theorists saying, \'93Well, why is this?\'94 Why is it \'85 is it simply that the Thatcherites have killed discussion of class, or is there other things that we should be thinking about?\'94 you see. \'93
And if we\rquote re getting no theoretical purchase with the idea, why bother with it?\'94 And that\rquote s what I said, and my article was entitled, \'93Is the Emperor Naked?\'94
. Now, I believe that there has been some absolutely excellent sociology done by a few people, over the last 20 or 30 years, but it\rquote s not what\rquote s been taught, necessarily. I mean, David Lockwood\rquote s book on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Solidarity and Schism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  also casts doubt on the sociological enterprise, in a very deep and complex way. It\rquote s not an easy book to read. I don
\rquote t think many sociologists can actually manage to read it! Or understand it, it doesn\rquote t make it easy for them, in the way it\rquote s written. Bu
t it is worrying that, even at a graduate level, I bet you could add up, you know, not get very far, with the number of people who\rquote ve actually engaged with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Solidarity and Schism}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  as part of the undergraduate course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So do you feel that the subject\rquote 
s sort of stuck? It\rquote s not moving forward?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I think, in the States, it\rquote s got method obsessed, and so, you know, it\rquote 
s all to do with the complexity of analysing large data sets, which some people would say, that\rquote s the only way you can go, the soc
iology is the method. But people are scared about ethnography, and being laughed at, and of being scorned for not being rigorous, and it\rquote s just sort of travellers tales and anecdotes, and how do we know that, you know, somebody else isn\rquote 
t going to pick up 
a different story and pull it out. And I think that, as I was writing, on this very morning, that a lot of the agenda is being set by people outside the discipline, the so-called users and beneficiaries which influence the ESRC, because the ESRC which, of
 course, does determine a lot of the research that\rquote 
s done, because they pay for it, is mindful of getting its research budget increased by the government and so forth, so they will go with the spirit of the age as hard as they can, because the spirit of the
 age is what helps to get their grant up. So if everyone\rquote s worrying away about social cohesion, or lack of social capital, then that\rquote s going to be part of their priority, you see, and away they go. And sociology might say, you know, \'93
Okay, if that\rquote s the game we\rquote re going to play, sure we\rquote ll play it\'94, and they go along with it. So that\rquote s corrupting. It\rquote 
s very corrupting. And, you know, one finds oneself in an awful position. Because on the one hand, I hear myself saying, advising people, as I\rquote ve been advising Cambridge recently, \'93Unless you get big research grants, buddy, you\rquote 
re just not going to be able to go ahead, because, you know, you\rquote ll not get assessed highly, and you\rquote re not going to get the research training, you\rquote ve just got to get a lot of money\'94. Other people at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose} say, \'93Well, you know, you\rquote re asking us to go down the slippery slope\'94. And I\rquote m saying the same, in a different context. So it\rquote 
s a real dilemma, I think. And I just think I\rquote ve been so lucky that so much of my career has been pretty much, you know, before that. I\rquote m hitting it now, when we come to the last instalment, about, you know, I\rquote 
m forced to play the game a bit. But, you know, if you said, well, if we were starting the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now, in 1998, rather than in 1965, when we sat under a tree in St. James\rquote s Park, and planned the syllabus, the four of us that were going to teach it, and there wasn\rquote 
t that much argument about what we should teach. There was quite a consensus about the core issues. We, erm, you couldn\rquote t do it. There\rquote d be great argument on what on earth we should teach. And \'85 there\rquote s arguments that \'85
 that the subject should either become cultural studies, which is, a lot of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Essex{\*\xmlclose} is cultural studie
s. And Tony Giddens has gone to the LSE and has just appointed a Professor in Cultural Studies, to boost the \'85 the media, and this kind of thing, which is very close to the Humanities, and I\rquote m not sure why it should be necessarily sociology or 
\'85 or English, really. So that that\rquote 
s been the huge shift, into cultural studies. Or whether it should be statistical model building, which is very difficult to get the two together. And whether the, the sort of founding fathers, the Marx, Weber, Durkheim, are not rele
vant, because, really, it\rquote s some form of social \'85
 a benign form of Social Darwinism as Gary Runciman suggests, that sociology, that societies evolve and change, and have, you know, cultural metamorphoses, as species would, and that the person who\rquote s really 
the founding father of sociology is Darwin, you see. And then there are others who\rquote d say, \'93Yes, well, what about Freud?\'94 So that there\rquote s a debate about which would be our \'85
 fathers. And the sort of debates in the middle of the century about functionalism, which everyone at the time thought it was all about, you know, Parsons and Merton, people don\rquote t even know they exist, there\rquote s no concern any more. They
\rquote re just not raised. So since some of the best ethnography is done outside sociology, by people like Tony Parker, People of Providence and so forth, you know, why be a sociologist? If you\rquote 
re just with a tape-recorder, you could be a journalist. So I think there would be enormous difficulty now, and I\rquote m faced with this, being on the Electoral Board for the new Professor at Cambridge \'85
 what kind of person, ideally, in the best of all possible worlds, if they were all interested, should one recruit to be the Professor of Sociology at Cambridge, one of the most prestigious universities in the world, what kind of p
erson do you look for? And how do you justify that to the political scientists on the Electoral Board, who say, \'93What\rquote s going on in your discipline?\'94 Now, do you say, nudge, wink, \'93Have X, because he can bring in big research grants\'94, I
\rquote ve found myself saying that. I mean, that\rquote s really a complete betrayal. But I could come back to this one, because there\rquote s more of my research career to come, from \'85 well, to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Art of Success}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and then the current work.
