\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And they were working very hard, and they made out that they weren\rquote t going to carry on like that. I haven
\rquote t, perhaps, mentioned that. So I thought, \'93Well, why don\rquote t I find people who are really successful and talk to them about why they\rquote re working so hard?\'94 Now, there\rquote 
s a big confession coming here, because I started the work, I can\rquote t remember the exact dates, but it got \'85
 it got taken over by some of the other activities in Eastern Europe and the Summer School, particularly the Summer School, so there was a gap between when I started it, and when I actually carried on and finished it. And in that gap, I cha
nged my ideas of what I was doing, very substantially. I thought it was a daft idea to ask people why they worked so hard! And partly, because, you know, one\rquote 
s going to get right away from any kind of sociological understanding, to either individual accounts of, you know, compensating for \'85 a father that wasn\rquote t adequate, and they\rquote 
re trying to do better, and all this stuff. There was a surgeon I interviewed, amongst the early interviews, who was completely obsessed! I mean, he started work at quarter to eight in the morning, and he\rquote 
d carry on till midnight, day after day, after day, after day. And his father had been a surgeon, and his grandfather had been a surgeon. And he was neurotically obsessed with his work. But, in every way, a nice man, and doing good
 work, and a private practice as well as his National Health Practice, and one might say that he\rquote 
s a person with a big sense of public duty. But he had the support staff of about three nurses and receptionists, and a wife all working for him, but basically as \'85 and so I thought, \'93Well, if I\rquote m going to explain this \'85 you\rquote 
ve got to say a lot about the individuals. I\rquote m not sure I\rquote m saying much in general about surgeons, I\rquote m talking about this particular chap\'94, you see. So that worried me. I thought, \'93What am I
 doing? Perhaps I should be doing a big survey of \'85 an attitudinal survey\'94
, because there were lots of attitudinal surveys about why people work hard, and, you know, whether they want to spend more time with the family, and you can provide a lot of informa
tion about it. Anyway, I lost interest, actually, in the specific motivations of people for working hard, which was what started me off. I got into trouble, too, financially, because the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} provided a little bit of money to do transcriptions, but once I was rolling, I couldn\rquote 
t get any money for anything else I was stuck, having to do it myself, really. Which meant I couldn\rquote t do anything else. So I was stuck for money, basically. I was doing research 
in my own free time, because I was half-time, so I did the other half. And then I got interested in this idea of success. What is success? And why should it be a work success? Well, that obviously, goes right back to the \'85 sociological \'85
 sort of classics, 
really, about the Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism, and why people are seeing individual success as being what makes their identity and virtuous in the sight of God, and all the rest of it. So exploring the idea of success seemed a much more 
interesting idea, particularly as the Americans had done a bit about this. I mean, there\rquote s something subversive about it as well, because when one thinks about lots of people one knows, one recognises that they\rquote 
re living good and interesting lives, but not in the style of your success, which is a simple point. I don\rquote t say I\rquote ve discovered anything profound here. But it did make me think a lot about \'85
 in a sense, why people do what they do. What are the different motivating clusters that lead to a happy life? And I\rquote ve always had the idea, actually, that there\rquote s a kind of \'85
 an element in British society, which is not written about much, of people \'85 this is not in the book, I may say, but it\rquote s there to \'85 perhaps \'85 would have done better to have paid more attentio
n to. People who are not on the middle-class career ratchet, and are not really hard up and struggling to make ends meet, but they\rquote 
re leading very interesting lives based on their hobbies and their activities and their interests, and they go camping, and they go fishing, and they are interested in \'85 in craft fairs, and they \'85
 the sort of people, actually, that you get very much up and down the borders, and come out here to live this kind of way. And they\rquote re everywhere, in a sense, that, you know, the ramble
rs, the hikers, and these people are not much interested, as far as I can make out, in reading the newspapers and finding out what\rquote 
s going on in the world, and being involved in great ambitious projects. They spend next winter doing line dancing, you know, or they \'85 have some project to do with \'85 learning to fly \'85
 get a dinghy and mess about and go to the reservoir and have races and things, you see. And their lives are focused on these things, and work is a secondary business. So they\rquote re not the kind of in
strumental working class, they, by and large, junior white collar jobs, but their focus is outside work. And success for them is getting the, you know, the cup for being \'85 doing the best ballet, or whatever it is. And that\rquote 
s the important thing in their lives. And if you read the newspapers, and listen to the news, this category is not the sort of person they\rquote re talking to. There\rquote s, \'93What shall we do about the poor\'94, and they\rquote 
re a category of people that things are done to, or \'93What shall we do about, you know, the teachers, or the professions\'94 and all these things. But the great mass of people just don\rquote 
t come into the story. And local papers are very much focused on these people, I think. So it\rquote s difficult not to speak about this without sounding patronisin
g, but I see this as an alternative, and perfectly valid, way of success. Not the success which means that you rise up in your particular thing, and end up with some, you know, going, or academic honour, or whatever the thing happens to be. So that
\rquote s what got me interested then, in the idea of \'93What is success?\'94 And then I got two strands of this, which not everyone sees from the title, \'93After\'94 being seeking success, and \'93After\'94
 being following success. And those two elements in it seem to me interesting. Why go after it, and what happens when you\rquote 
ve got it? And that really should have led me to a much more thoughtful analysis of the values of contemporary society, and comparing the very successful ones that I\rquote ve interviewed with some of these people I\rquote m tal
king about, that have alternative value sets, and talk about the way that these quite distinct views of what makes the good life, are co-existing in our society, and where this is the basis for any kind of political response or \'85 it\rquote 
s what the sociological implications should be. But to carry on my confession, and this is one of the pernicious things about what\rquote s happened to university life, you know, a book had to be done quite quickly for the RAE. It really was \'85
