s now since become a judge. So I actually got very good people. I mean, one of the tragedies of it is, that when I wanted a politician, I asked about about who would be a good one, and the advice I got, at that time, was that \'93There\rquote 
s rising chap called Tony Blair, who\rquote s really, you know, ready to talk to you, if you\rquote d like to do it. We\rquote ve sounded him out\'94. And I didn\rquote t do it, because I\rquote d just got enough then, so I thought, \'93Well, I\rquote 
ll miss out on that\'94. So it gives the indication that my network was quite good. So it was Ray Pahl\rquote s network. So, anyway, I wrote a sort of spoof \'85 a sort of Appendix on Method, where I said I 
was adopting the Mars bars method. And Mars bars meant, Methods Are Resembling Saloon Bar Sociology. It was a sort of joke against myself. And I said that, you know, because of the development of \'85
 forces in methodology, there was little books on every aspect of qualitative methodology, and I thought there was a case for one on Mars bars, you see, because there\rquote 
s this series that Sage Publications has where they produce these little books, costing \'85 very expensive little books, about 90 pages, which students buy, you know, text on courses. So I said, you know, \'93Time for this\'94
. And it was a joke! The whole thing was a joke! Blow me, I got a letter from the publisher, saying that they were fascinated about this, and if it was at all possible for me to actually do this, they\rquote 
d be delighted to publish it! So, I mean, I just couldn\rquote t believe that people didn\rquote t have \'85
