\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, partly it\rquote s because \'85 a younger person couldn\rquote t have done the kind of interviewing, I don
\rquote t think, that I did. People spoke to me very much as an equal, and were prepared to almost treat me as a kind of father figure in some cases, and told me things they wouldn\rquote t have told younger people. In fac
t, I said something about this at one of Paul Thompson\rquote 
s seminars, which I think was really quite interesting, that you get different stories, depending on your age, as an interviewer. Michael Roper, talking to the managers, in his book, or for his thesis, got them into the role of, \'93
Now, young chap, let me tell you what it\rquote s like at \'85\'94 and they were kind of patronising, giving him tips, you know, trying to get this young stag to be a big stag like them one day. But, you see, when they spoke to me, it was u
tterly different. They were talking as if they might have done to some father confessor. And that was interesting. And so, in a sense, I was capitalising on the fact that I could get this kind of response, and so I was enjoying it. But \'85
 no, my puzzle was really just curiosity. Why do they do it? What keeps them going? And then when they\rquote ve done it, do they think it\rquote 
s worthwhile? And this distinction between satisfaction and gratification which I was strong on at the time, the gratification never gets fully \'85
 well, gratification leads you on to want more gratification. So the film star who gets the Oscar wants the next Oscar, and all the more applause or whatever, and there\rquote 
s no limit to it. Whereas the satisfaction comes from a job well done. And so you can get the people that spend most of their lives in this other category, the people who are looking for self-fulfilment outside their employment, still doing \'85
 perhaps more satisfied, but without the gratification. Gratification doesn\rquote t last, satisfaction does. So, possibly, the good society is a society that can produce everybody generating their satisfaction, whether they\rquote 
re doing the most humble, you know, caring job in a local residential home, or whether they\rquote re \'85 you know, running the Treasury. But it\rquote s
 a kind of ethos of public service at the top which, again, was an interesting thing that Thatcher undermined the public altruism, in the sense of public service, and put everybody into \'85 basically, getting more money \'85 putting it \'85
 big salaries and big pay outs and so forth. So I suppose I wanted to put some kind of critique against that. I had some kind of idealistic thing about, \'93This is not the way the world should go\'94
. With a degree of irritation at the way money was driving everybody in the eighties. It was a sort of fight back against that. I think there was a political undertone of \'85
 of resentment, really, that these financial values were becoming so dominant, and making life less good. I mean, other people have written about this far better. A book by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Robert Lane{\*\xmlclose} on }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Market Experience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and one or two Americans, not many, have actually written serious, very solid books about why people aren
\rquote t happy. Why aren\rquote t they happy? You know, we\rquote ve got all this more wealth, and yet we\rquote re much more stressed, much more back pain, a lot more diseases related to people\rquote s psychological \'85
 distress of one sort or another. So I suppose, going back to Wright-Mills\rquote s dictum about the public issues and private troubles, there seemed to be a huge amount of private troubles. People weren\rquote t happy, they were miserable. They still 
\'85 the feel-good factor wasn\rquote t there. And, going back to Durkheim, a lot of this is there in Durkheim, in his discussion of suicide, about the raising of appetites, and the fact that these appetites were never fully \'85 satisfied \'85
 focusing on the gratification. So there was a kind of unease about \'93What\rquote s life all about?\'94 under the sort of style of government. I was totally anti-pathetic towards really, although people said that maybe it was necessary, and if it hadn
\rquote t happened in the way it did, it would have to happen in some other way. But I wasn\rquote t very happy at all, what was happening to a whole series of public life through the 1980s. It was such a damaging time.
