d somehow created a gap for myself by attacking the notion of community, without having thought through what I would, what I would put in its place, you see. But then they challenged me and said, \'93Well, what would it \'85 \'94 And I was asked to give s
o
me lectures, and write more pieces, which I did. And in doing this, looked also at the survey material, because it happened, fortuitously, that whilst this discussion about community had led me into friends in a sort of public debate arena, my work at the
 Centre at Essex, was about how \'85 the \'85 problems of unemployment, (we simply got a grant from Unilever when I was involved with this) the problems of unemployment could be, somehow, alleviated, by people\rquote s social linkages. And there\rquote 
s a well-known debate in sociology about the strength of weak ties, from the American Granovetter and so forth. And so there was a younger researcher at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} working on this, and I was working with her and others, and they started looking at the way in which \'85
 I think a lot of people with friends are more likely to find employment, than if they didn\rquote t. So I suppose to get something out of the British Household Panel Study, on this topic and found that people were much mo
re likely to go to friends after divorce, and things like that, and, of course, there was more divorce. And so it didn\rquote 
t take me long to go through the existing literature, and to recognise that in the area of family, friend-like relationships are becoming more important, because people - the kin they like, they\rquote 
re more likely to respond to and accept their obligations, than the kin they don\rquote t like. So I stumbled on something that I thought was really quite, quite important here, that people were reconsidering their \'85
 their sense of obligations of what they should do in society, in a very small-scale way, with a small circle of friends who mattered to them. And you could say that people have always had friends, and there\rquote s nothing new about this. That in a s
ense, in one sense, is true. But what friends are has changed over time. And I think may be that the sense of solidarity and commitment and trust that\rquote 
s part of the base of a good society, that might in the past have been in the public realm, has been privatised. That public duty responsibility is now private duty responsibility. And the trust that you\rquote 
d have as a colleague in a company or a profession, has gone away, because you don\rquote t trust them, they\rquote re more likely to stab you in the back, perhaps. So thi
s rather nebulous world of friendship seemed to me to be becoming very very important. And the more I looked at it, the more important and interesting it became. And I went back through the philosophy of it from Aristotle and so on, about what is a friend
, and I realised that the word \'93friend\'94 is far too general a term. It covers a whole range of different range of relationships which, actually, haven\rquote t been properly categorised. And in all the surveys that I\rquote 
ve looked at, you know, there wasn\rquote t much attempt to find out what people meant by a friend. You know, \'93When did you last see your friend?\'94 And to some people, \'93friend\'94
 means someone you just go and play tennis with, to other people it can mean a variety of things, including being so close to that perso
n, that that person is more important than any other person around. They can help them develop the sort of person they are, their identity, how they communicate well and so forth. And that may be a spouse, it may not be. So we just have one simple word to
 cover this whole range of relationships. And so when we \'85 some people, I guess, are not psychologically able to be as close as the pure form of friendship could actually be. They just, they haven\rquote t got the capacity, you know, whatever it is 
\'85 problems of early attachment and things, making them difficult to form these kind of attachments. So some people have more friend-like qualities within them. And they should bring them out. And so when you\rquote 
re asking them about their friends, you\rquote re asking about quite d
ifferent things. Now, obviously, when you ask about kinship, you know, a son is a son, and a daughter is a daughter. And whilst you may have different ways of performing these roles, by and large there\rquote 
s the legal support, and you get inheritance, and there\rquote 
s a whole lot of things that institutionalise the structure of kin relations, which is not there for friends. So it seemed to me that this is a whole area of social life which is really crucially important for understanding social change, social cohesion
, this idea of what it is to be a good citizen, and a whole load of things like this. There are also very practical aspects to it, which \'85
 I think the present government is interested in, because the importance of peer pressure and so on, relates to teenag
e crime, and the capacity to get into the employment market. Friends are very important for social support, for the care of the elderly, finding jobs. Friends are more important than family for a lot of this. So the more I thought about it, the more I rea
l
ised that the sociologists had, perhaps, been missing a lot of the point about it, but by focussing on, you know, women have these friends, men have those friends, middle-class have these friends, and I looked at it in terms of these variables, rather tha
n looking at the sort of function of this kind of \'93social glue\'94, which is the phrase I took, the friendship as a kind of social glue. And it\rquote 
s changing. Now, that has to be demonstrated. So we put in a proposal for a research grant, which we doubted that we
 were going to get, in order to explore the changing meaning of friendship, and to discover whether it is a kind of metaphor for a new kind of morality, that\rquote 
s interesting, the amount that people are talking about, as having been undermined by Thatcher, is there, but in the private sphere, and not observed. People \'85
 to begin with, when I said I was interested in friends, people said, you know, this is some kind of non-serious, jokey thing. But it takes a time for them to realise this may be one of the most 
central elements to understand the way in which society changes. So I think \'85
 confessed it was a degree of chance that I got interested - although then one tends to re-write the past, and it just happened that 25 years ago, Paul Barker, who was editor of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 New Society}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
, and was doing a book on the different variables that sociologists used to describe people, and class and age and gender, and he wondered why friends had not, friends and associates had not been one of the key elements. And I was actually asked 
to write that chapter in that book which I did, and I didn\rquote t have the wit to realise the importance of what I was looking at then. And so I did the \'85
 I was in the old sociological tradition of, you know, do you have friends? Are the people more like you, or different from you? And it was all sort of structured and didn\rquote 
t lead anywhere. So it took a long time for the real significance of friends to come through. Maybe the significance has changed over that intervening period. I\rquote m very excited now about the project, and the possibility of doing work on that.
