\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
And who is going to be doing the work with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I mean, that\rquote s quite a thoughtful question, becau
se I had this group that were working together in the Centre at Essex, and one of my jobs there was to encourage, is to encourage young researchers to get their own project, and to lead them on, develop their careers, which is what I like doing, and there
\rquote s no reason for me to be worrying about, you know, my own position, so I can just help others. Now, Karen O\rquote Reilly was very interested in this particular project, as was Liz Spencer. Liz Spencer, I\rquote 
d worked with for many years, many years ago, when she was actually a graduate student at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and also she\rquote d got a research grant on another aspect, but she was there years ago. And then she got a job with the Social Community Planning Research, and wa
s very skilled as a quantitative interviewer. And she happened to live near the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
Essex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, having got a family and all the rest of it. And so I tried to tempt her back, to say \'85 here was somebody with great skill, she was responsible for a lot of the interviewing with the \'85
 the British Survey on Sexual Attitudes, so she\rquote s a very perceptive interviewer, and good at it. And she was interested in this topic, so I got her along, but we agreed that the crucial person in this was Karen O\rquote 
Reilly, because she was going to be the one that was employed by the Centre and was going to be \'85 we couldn\rquote t put her in as Chief Investigator, because she wasn\rquote t experienced enough, but the idea was that she would largely be res
ponsible for the project, and then she could talk about this. And so she was in as a co-applicant. But then we got let down by the ESRC who didn\rquote 
t consider our application at the meeting in April, which they said they were going to consider it. They claim \'85 well, I said why not? But anyway, they didn\rquote 
t. And she lost faith in the fact that she was going to get the money, and took a job in the Centre elsewhere. Now we\rquote ve got the money, she\rquote s one of the applicants, Liz and I are, as it were, part-time consulta
nts, and the main person that applied for the money has gone off. So how this is going to be resolved, we don\rquote t know. But it is a bit irritating that, having set it up for somebody \'85 but she says, \'93Well, I couldn\rquote t be sure \'85
 you know, had we not got the money, I made the right decision\'94. But \'85 so \'85 so that\rquote s awkward. But assuming that we can sort that out, she\rquote ll \'85
 Karen will work on it for at least a day a week, and we might have to find somebody else. But it will be galling that she\rquote ll then have to be see
ing somebody else doing the project she wanted to do herself, while she does something different. I mean, that\rquote s just a really irritating thing. But I\rquote d have thought \'85 back \'85
 to my astonishment, the grant is, because of the overheads, is larger than the grant we got for the Sheppey Project. That\rquote s because 40 per cent has to go and overheads to the University, which does seem ludicrous, given that we\rquote 
re aiming at a modest number of interviews, although they might be all over the country. And what we want to do is see the changing meaning of friendship, over the life course of people. So it\rquote 
s this longitudinal approach which is so important. And seeing what people mean about best friends, and what the development of friend-like relationships amongst kin means,
 and, well, just explore, really, how people are using and what they mean by friends and friend-like relationships. It\rquote 
s almost uncharted territory, which is extraordinary when you think about it, given these are crucially important social relationships in people\rquote s lives. So I\rquote m very excited about that, and I\rquote ve been doing some reading, and I\rquote 
ve just agreed to write a book, a short book, on friends and friendship, which will be about 45,000 words, which means I\rquote ll be reading all the literature, which is a good discipline, and just summarise what\rquote s known. I don\rquote 
t have to be \'85 the nature of the book is the sort of introduction to the topic, but it\rquote s a good thing to do at this particular time, and then we\rquote ll write, you know, scholarly things thereafter. Which means that now, my \'85
 you know, career as a researcher, has gone into another phase, which will take some years to work through. So \'85 because, you know, the project will last two and a half years, and you know, there\rquote ll be stuff to write after that, so I was
 really thinking about another four or five years. But I can\rquote 
t think of a better topic to be working on, really, or with nicer people. Liz and I are friends. Well, we have to work out what that means, as part of the project! And people will always say that
, that the research that one does, is to some extent linked to the experiences of life that one\rquote s had, and already people are saying, \'93Well, you know, Ray is interested in friends now, because he\rquote 
s got the time to appreciate friends for himself, whereas, you know, when he was earlier, he was rushing on in his career, he didn\rquote t see the significance of it quite so much\'94. And so I think back about my own experience \'85
 and a lot of the work I\rquote ve done as a sociologist, has been actually because I\rquote ve been working with friends. So when I look back \'85 but I didn\rquote t twig this, you see. When I was back \'85
 I think it was something like 1972 or so, when I did this other previous piece on friends for Paul Barker, if I\rquote d thought about myself more, and what I was doing, and the importance of friends for me, I\rquote 
d have written a far better piece. But because I was too much a sociologist, going on the sociological literature \'85 so I think maybe I\rquote ve got confidence now to stand back without being so totally embraced by the role of so
ciologist. So instead of just going to \'85 if I went now and said, \'93What does the literature say about friendship?\'94 I wouldn\rquote t get very far at all, because now I think \'85
 well, the literature, maybe, is important, but I will think about it simply because I think about it, you see, as Ray Pahl, rather than someone who\rquote 
ll read all the literature and then think about it. Now, there may be other topics that one has to grow into, in a way. I mean, I felt, for instance, when I was younger, that I couldn\rquote t really see myself developing political sociology. I just didn
\rquote t feel I was politically aware enough. I can remember thinking that. I didn\rquote t \'85 well, some people, of course, they\rquote re really terrifically committed to it, because they\rquote re involved politically. Because of 
the nature of the sort of person I was, I just didn\rquote t get involved in that. So I think it\rquote s true that there is a sort of interplay between one\rquote 
s own experience and biography, and the kinds of topics that one gets into. Not in an over-simple way, I mean, I think, when I said earlier that people who were divorced tend to rely on friends more. But people say, \'93Oh, he\rquote 
s got interested in friends because he\rquote s been through a divorce, and he\rquote s not so bound up in the family\'94, although I would have thought that the 
people who are really as close to me as anyone could be, are my children. But then I could reinterpret that in terms of the friend-like relationships with them. So one does actually think about one\rquote 
s biographical experience in this. There is a degree of chance. I mentioned, you know, I came from community into friendship, I was almost pushed into it. And I think, you see, that those that stick with the sociological fashion, miss out a lot. I\rquote 
ve probably not done that, which may have been just by chance a good thing, because \'85 sociological fashion is very arbitrary in the way that it moves from one, you know, theme to the next and so forth, and it just \'85 misses a lot. I mean, there
\rquote s \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But maybe you\rquote 
re also involved in creating those themes, if you\rquote re maybe standing outside of that \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. I don\rquote t feel I\rquote m \'85 I don\rquote t feel I\rquote 
m in it, somehow. So, in a sense, being marginal, people will say \'93You\rquote re marginal to be a sociologist\'94, but sometimes I feel a bit marginal to sociology, I don\rquote t feel obliged
 to go through the kind of sociological camp, or to follow the sociological tradition. I don\rquote t think it\rquote s that marvellous really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Can I just move on slightly, because you
\rquote ve mentioned \'93chance\'94 quite a lot in the last few minutes, and yet we\rquote ve talked off tape, and, I think, on tape as well, a bit about how \'85
 what the patterns have been throughout your professional career, and how one thing has led on to another, and I wondered if you wanted to say more about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I\rquote ve provided accounts for a lot of the things I\rquote 
ve done, which may not be true accounts, they may be accounts at the time. But what is a true account? I mean there\rquote s a topic in itself! And I remember that I justified being interested in these Hertfordshire 
villages because, as I said, I was living in a village myself, and saw the thing happening around me. I was interested in the managers because my job obliged me to work with them, and that made me realise that there was a problem there. The job sort of pu
s
hed it in front of my nose. Then, I think, working with the government over those years, in the Department of the Environment, undoubtedly gave me the idea of the managers of the urban system, which was so widely imputed as the sort of theoretical develop
ment I\rquote d contributed, but it was because I had been outside sociology as, perhaps, one of the managers, because that was \'85 or meeting them, that coming back from that experience outside made me see something that perhaps I wouldn\rquote 
t have seen from within. So people like Manuel Castells was saying, you know, the urban doesn\rquote t exist. I was seeing people in a private club, called the Land Use Society, which I may not have mentioned, which I was involved with, where \'85
 it met once a month, I think, and there were people who were really the movers and shakers of land development, big property developers, the Permanent Secretary of the Department, and so forth. It was one of these sort of \'85
 all went off to a meal after afterwards \endash  [at Rules in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Covent Garden{\*\xmlclose}
] a clubby sort of thing. There were some women members, but mostly it was men. And these people were people who would be talking very informally, off the cuff, about developing dock land, or creating new towns, or having some massive infrastructural 
thing, and sitting there listening to all this, I realized, well you know to say that the urban doesn\rquote t exist \'85 you think about the power, they\rquote re moving things, they\rquote re making decisions, they\rquote 
re talking to Ministers, this is a world that we, in the textbooks of urban sociology, it\rquote s not in there at all. How could sociologists know about this? This was a private club, that I wasn\rquote 
t meant to talk about the fact that I was there. The whole thing was confidential. And so without sort of going into conspiracy v
iews of how the world works, it was quite clear that some people have a hell of a lot of power, and their power actually leads to things happening, and that to imagine that it\rquote s all some kind of a \'85 \'85 almost a \'85
 impersonal forces, seemed to me to be nonsense. But the Marxists would say, \'93inevitable forces of Capitalism or something, will lead to the city being in this kind of way\'94
. Well, yes and no. I mean, in one sense, of course, it is a capitalist society, and so the line is developed in a certain sort o
f way. But there was a considerable amount of intervention in the market. The market was socially embedded, as they now say, and that to see it is a complete untrammelled operation of Capitalism in the population of the country is all a nonsense. And, of 
course, now people will accept that. So, of course, there were these links between, you know, the structure and agency, as they put it. So \'85 I\rquote 
ve probably got a tendency to discover for myself, things that one could have got at, perhaps, by being more theoretically thorough, but it\rquote 
s by being there and recognising this was going on. So this developed my urban sociology. And then again, I think one\rquote s sort of irritation with na\'efve assumptions about how the world works, forcing \'85 you know, we need to do some so
ciology about this. So the drive to Sheppey was very much \'85 you know, a lot of people really living in this kind of way, as is being imputed to them. We don\rquote 
t know, really. So this is the curiosity. And people were saying that the only way they can possibl
y survive now, is, with this inflation in the mid-seventies, they must be on the fiddle. Well, you know, are they? And how easy is it? And what sort of fiddles and so forth? Let\rquote s go and look. So I suppose that one could categorise this \'85
 as one goes through life, one\rquote s own biography and experience throw up ideas. As a sociology teacher, perhaps I should mention that more, and by teaching, you read a lot of stuff, and that throws up questions that the literature doesn\rquote 
t seem to address. And I often find it very dispiriting, you know, you work up a course of lectures and \'85 I mean, the convention is you\rquote re bringing together what\rquote s written about the thing, and you say, \'93That\rquote s the knowledge\'94
. But I always found that by giving lectures, instead of giving answers, I got more questions! And I may have not been a very good teacher for the students, because I say, well, \'93We don\rquote t \'85
 they purport to say this all goes on, but actually, we don\rquote t know. It probably isn\rquote t that, but we\rquote ve got to do some research\'94. They say, \'93Well, tell us the truth\'94. And I say, \'93
Well, how can I possibly tell you about this, because this is mostly rubbish\'94, you know. Some people have done a bit of \'85 have done an article on this, that and the other, but this doesn\rquote t really tell you what\rquote s going on. So I\rquote 
ve been a bit sceptical, I suppose, about the knowledge that\rquote s called sociology, that people teach, and this is how our society works. Because when I\rquote ve got to the inside of it, I\rquote 
m not sure the way people describe it is true. So there\rquote s the teaching, there\rquote s the sort of story that is sociology, this is a kind of story, there is one\rquote s own experience, and there is the politically learned. They\rquote 
re the sort of elements, I think, and it was a backwards and forwards flow between them. I think that \'85 it sounds very pragmatic, really. Probably is. I\rquote 
m not driven by an overwhelming desire to solve some fundamental theoretical question, because, in retrospect, these theoretical questions seem to change quite dramatically, and my sort of mentor in theory wou
ld be David Lockwood, has probably accepted in his book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Solidarity and Schism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
, that some of the basic dilemmas that sociology students grapple with in theory courses, aren\rquote t resolvable. And you\rquote ve got to come to terms with some kind of ambiguity. And that\rquote 
s a pretty complicated thing for students between 18 and 21 to get. So what they\rquote re taught instead, is not what\rquote 
s known, but some lesser level that they can sort of learn for the purpose of passing exams, which is depressing to have to be doing that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Just talking about David Lockwood, and he
\rquote s obviously been quite an important influence in earlier decades, and I wondered who or what has been the greatest influence on your thinking, really, in the nineties, in this decade? Or who and what, even?
