\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Mmm. Well, various people obviously have \'85 have influenced me. I mean, I got much \'85
 I got the kind of sceptical stance from Ernest Gellner, because Ernest Gellner was over there in Prague, and we talked together and drank together, 
and saw quite a bit of each other. I think probably, on a sort of friendly basis, I got lots of ideas from Krishan Kumar, over the \'85 but almost as a friend, because he \'85 he and I taught courses together, and people just chat about ideas and \'85
 and what he was doing and what I was doing. And he would read, and I would read, and so I think that it\rquote s in the \'85 debates there, with him. So I\rquote ve got various friends that have been more important, really, to talk \'85 I wouldn\rquote 
t want to pick up this book or that book that irritates me \'85 and people like Claire Wallace too, I\rquote 
ve been talking with her, about work, on and off, all this period. And to some extent, of course, people that have been there from a long time, are still there, people like Erving Goffman, who was somebody who you couldn\rquote 
t fit into any sort of sociological tradition or niche, but somehow \'85 certainly when we come back to thinking about social relationships of the more micro sort, then he does become very important. But \'85 there\rquote s Pierre Bourdieu everyone
 would quote as being important. And Zygmunt Bauman, but, I mean, I read \'85 I read Bauman and \'85
 and Bourdieu, but whether they actually lead me to doing something different in the way that I actually do my research, I think not, really. I mean, I ought to look up at my bookshelf for inspiration. I mentioned this book by Lane, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The Market Experience}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , that did strike me as being a really good book. That people just don\rquote 
t get their main satisfaction or happiness from their main market experience, which is in the labour market. I thought that was really full of interest. Also, I think \'85
 yeah, I mean, there are people like Mike Savage, in his book on the middle-class, and J. Gershuny\rquote s articles about the household, that \'85 I much admire and respect, and which \'85 if y
ou asked me to give 20 colleagues whose work I respect and read, and feel I\rquote m at one with, Rosemary Crompton on class, and Michael Anderson and Frank Bechhofer on the Household, up in Edinburgh. There\rquote s a group of people that \'85 I wouldn
\rquote t say that they were great mentors, like, perhaps I might have said for David Lockwood, but they give a feeling of a sort of continuity that \'85 if \'85 if \'85 arrogantly, if all sociology was based on this group of 20, then it wouldn\rquote 
t be such a bad \'85 although it\rquote s terribly arrogant to say that! And, you know, a lot of people might be very offended. But I just am not really in the cultural studies mode of sociology, as is evident. And so to some extent, there\rquote 
s a slightly old-fashioned empirical tradition, which I\rquote ve stayed with, which is an empirical tradition based on \'85 a rather rough and ready theoretical grounding, pretty pragmatic really, and I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
ve changed much in that perspective, most of my career. I haven\rquote t, as many people have done, have moved strongly into a k
ind of Marxist tradition and then reacted against it, a bit like that. I ranted quite strongly against the Fabian tradition, I have to say. That\rquote 
s what my experience with the working with Government as one did, and really felt that that was dangerous, and the sort of \'85 the public schoolishness of it all. The prefects.
\par 
