\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, her \'85 yes, that\rquote s right. And she, I think, is probably much more managerialist, one might say. So I
\rquote m much more anarchistic and less structured than she would be, about the whole thing. Yeah, I, I, I like it best when people say that I have just made them think differently, stimulated them, got them going on a different direction. And because I
\rquote m not so easily labelled, I think I can do that. I don\rquote t have that much difficulty in thinking of ideas about what could be researched on what to do, I\rquote m probably more likely to be irritated by \'85 responding against other people
\rquote s notions, and not being drawn into camps. There\rquote s this kind of Bolshyness about it that\rquote s probably there. And if I can encourage other people to pick up something \'85
 with luck, they can be more creative, and more adventurous really. I like being adventurous, if possible. The danger is that if you\rquote re too
 adventurous, you are irresponsible and you chuck away a lot of, you know, good things, as well. But maybe sociology \'85 ought to be more adventurous, and less tied to the canon, because they\rquote 
ve agreed now that the canon has let them down, the social sort of canon is very uncertain, what it might be and why it was put there. I mean, there\rquote 
s been literature about this recently. So I think that to be a sociologist is a good and honourable profession, but I wish it wasn\rquote t \'85 it\rquote s too big, really, in my view. And I think that the way it\rquote s become structured with \lquote A
\rquote  level, and lots of students going through and so forth, they\rquote re teaching a kind of invention, and I feel very ill at ease with that invention, basically, I\rquote d say. And \'85 I don\rquote t know what to do about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Okay. Shall we move on? One thing I wanted to ask you about is, sort of moving on totally now to another area of your life. You\rquote ve obviously travelled and worked a great deal in Eastern Europe, throughout your career, and that\rquote 
s brought you som
e lasting relationships with people, and countries that were new to you, and I wondered if also there were other parts of the world that you have strong connections with, travelled to a lot, or whatever, and have a great love for, or feelings about?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, I think that I\rquote m very much a European. I feel very ill-at-ease in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}United States{\*\xmlclose}. Immensely homesick, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}, I\rquote m always desperate to get back, which annoys Krishnan Kumar and others too, because, if anything, I hav
e a slight antipathy towards \'85 I feel very strange in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}, I don\rquote t like it at all. Whereas I feel very much at home in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France
{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Italy{\*\xmlclose} and so on. I did have a house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Italy{\*\xmlclose} for ten years. So I\rquote m
 very much at ease there. More, more, I would say. I mean, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Eastern Europe{\*\xmlclose} is the sort of strangeness, or was, it\rquote s less so now. And I think it\rquote 
s quite good, in fact, essential, I would have thought, for sociologists to have some feeling of st
rangeness of other culture, and I think it would be very odd if sociologists can only work within their own culture and their own language, really. Not that I\rquote m that smart in languages, but I\rquote 
ve always been able to read French, and now Italian. And to try and understand society from within is bound to be a dangerous and misleading sort of notion. So I feel very comfortable, actually, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Europe
{\*\xmlclose}, and feel at ease, whether it be the Northern or Southern part. Yeah, I feel that I\rquote m a European, and there\rquote s enough there to keep me very happy. I\rquote ve no great urge to spend time in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}South Africa{\*\xmlclose}, or \'85 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Brazil{\*\xmlclose}, or wherever. And I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m going to feel that I\rquote ve missed out through my life by not having travelled across {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}China{\*\xmlclose}, although maybe I might want to do that! No, I think that \'85
 I feel European, I enjoy Europe, and I think I get a lot of diversity within {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Europe{\*\xmlclose}, to satisfy me. 
