\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, when I was a student, I bought pictures and records, you know, if I had some money. I don\rquote 
t know quite how that happened, but that seemed to me what one did. And I wish I\rquote d kept some of the things that I\rquote 
d bought from those days! But having started on the idea that one buys pictures, like some people might buy books or whatever, I was intereste
d in prints and the like in the sixties, and then in the early seventies, I got some money for doing something, some kind of a \'85 consultancy or something, and I decided I\rquote 
d put that money into a sort of collecting fund. And I started to collect English wat
ercolours. And it just happened that, in those years, the prices were just zooming up. And so as my taste developed, I sold and bought again. And I seemed to have quite a good eye, and so I actually \'85 knew various dealers, and I\rquote 
d go around the place and buy \'85 I just got into the way of buying in quantities, in a way! And it was just relatively easy, if one bought things and one didn\rquote 
t like them, one could sell them again for more money than one paid for it. So that became a sort of separate thing. And when I went down to see my parents in Bournemouth, there was a dealer down there I used to go and visit, and there was another one in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}London{\*\xmlclose}, and I just got to know them, and just became quite an absorbing \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Why English watercolours?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Why English watercolours? I suppose they were very accessible, and one could \'85
 I could find them in just about every antique shop in those days. One used to go along and \'85 and I got the books and learnt a bit about it. But then I get bored with the English watercolours, because they all seem to be \'85 they\rquote 
re a bit over-pretty, you know, and I didn\rquote t find them as challenging. So I got, through knowing another collector/dealer, interested in figure drawings, 18th century drawings I moved on to, English. An
d then from there, I got interested in Old Master drawings, and that\rquote 
s a highly specialised area, and Italian drawings of the 15th, 16th century, and attribution is a big problem, and so forth. But I got into the way of having quite a reasonable eye, I thi
nk. And again, I used to buy and sell as a way of improving my taste. I mean, I wasn\rquote t always sure which sort of drawings \'85 it really annoys me, the things that I\rquote 
ve had and have sold. I remember, there was one drawing that I bought from a dealer, and he assured me that it wasn\rquote t by Fuseli, although \'85 a Swiss, but worked in England in the 18th century, and there have been exhibitions of Fuseli\rquote 
s work, and I thought that, really, that this drawing was all right, and I saw \'85 I went to the exhibition at the Ta
te, and there was something made me think it was very, very okay. But, foolishly, I sold it to another dealer. And then a few years later, I went to an exhibition at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}British{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Museum{\*\xmlclose}, of the most distinguished drawings that the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}British{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Museum{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} had acquired for the last five years, and there I saw my drawing! I was a bit annoyed about that. So, you know, it does happen. I\rquote 
d like to have other things, too. Anyway, the years went by, and th
en I got interested in 20th century drawing. I got more confidence I suppose. I just worked through from things that I could relate to, to things that were more challenging, and I just got \'85
 my taste just developed, I suppose. Some people seem to know, straightaway, what they like, and so on, but I wasn\rquote t so sure. And I don\rquote t think I could have got that confidence without first handling an awful lot of \'85
 and then I had a phase when I got interested in sculpture, and bought sculpture and things. But, by and large, the lucky thing is that because I started so early, the collection has built up for very little money, but just by \'85
 by dealer/collecting. And I got friendly with dealers, and I\rquote d bring things that I\rquote d want to change, and they\rquote d \'85 and I\rquote d say, \'93What do you want for it?\'94 and I would give them a price, and they\rquote d say, \'93Fine
\'94. And that happened, and so now, I\rquote ve got, really, as you can see, a lot of things.
