 sentimental reasons, as much as anything. And, you know, I could go round the room and say, \'93That, I stayed with the artist, and the following morning I chose one\'94, and \'93That was given to me by a friend\'94, and you know, \'93That one was this
\'94, and so forth. And I got interested in African sculpture. So I\rquote ve got a very broad, eclectic taste, I would say. People are quite surprised that I can spread from contemporary abstract to \'85 and I quite like buying from \'85
 practising artists. I quite like the idea \'85 I\rquote ve got \'85 that\rquote s the ultimate confidence, to go to \'85 you don\rquote t have the market to guide you, you\rquote 
ve just got your eye, you know, artists that are not well-known. And, I mean, that one up there, the blue one, that\rquote s by a neighbour\rquote s daughter who\rquote s at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Art{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, aged 19, but I think it\rquote s jolly good. And she\rquote 
s just done that. And, you know, if that was done by some famous artist, it would be a huge thing. But she just said \'93Yes\'94
, and was very pleased that I had it! And one of the things I can do now is, if my tastes change, if I wanted something else, I could simply take a proportion of the things that I \'85
