\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 \'85 art collection, and really, how you
\rquote d gone about doing it. And I wondered if you could say more about where the interest came from to collect, and why you enjoy that \'85 the wheeling and dealing it seems a bit like, rather than just having a collection of paintings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. I think that that\rquote s an interesting question, that I puzzle about myself, because my parents weren\rquote 
t particularly interested in art, although I did have one of my father\rquote s relatives was a well known artist in Germany, and was Professor of Art at Stuttgart. But whether, you know, one has a genetic predisposition, I don\rquote 
t know. But as my collecting\rquote s continued, it has really become very important to me, and anyone that knows me would say, \'93Well, not to know about my interest in art, you\rquote re missing a lot out about me\'94. And I think that it\rquote 
s a very private interest. And the fact that I wheel and deal, as you say, or change the collection, is simply a way of reflecting my changing taste. And one of the ways in which I really come to know what my taste is, is by havin
g a thing. I mean, some people can go to art galleries and come away knowing what they like, and what they want to keep in their minds. But to some extent, I\rquote m never sure until I\rquote 
ve had it on the wall for some time. And often, the things that appeal to me initially, I bore with, whereas those, that I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m going to live with, they actually become much more part of me. So that experience has taught me that you can\rquote t be so sure, when you just immediately look at something, what is going to \'85 now I\rquote v
e got more of a feeling of the sort of things I\rquote m going to live with better, and it\rquote s a very personal, individualistic thing. And how one develops taste is a \'85 you know, I\rquote ve not really thought about much. But I feel that I\rquote 
ve got some kind of aesthetic sensibility that needs to be fed, and if I\rquote m away, I miss having works of art about me. And when I come back, and they\rquote re pleased that they can find some kind of \'85 \'85 part of my identity that I\rquote 
m comfortable with, and if it\rquote s not there, then I\rquote m not firing on all cylinders! And I spend a lot of time moving pictures about my house, and always have done, partly because, if you leave them where they are too long, you don\rquote 
t notice them, and, therefore, you have to move them to \'85 and partly because pictures need to be seen in context, I think, and in different lights and different positions, they\rquote 
re different pictures. And I spend a lot of time, actually, moving objects about, and it matters a lot to me, where objects are placed, so that \'85 what\rquote s this Chinese Feng Shui thing, where \'85 and I \'85
 I think, I am a natural Feng Shui person! And I will be in a room, and the table is not right, and I\rquote ll have to move it a bit, until it is, to my view, right, in the aesthetic sense. And so the \'85 my house tends to be, since it\rquote s now \'93
my house\'94 and not a shared house, a bit sparse, from some people\rquote s point of view, not the homey thing of things lying about, maybe. Or \'85 well, it depends on where you\rquote re looking! But, but I don\rquote t count books! But \'85
 my feelings about art and music, and we haven\rquote t mentioned music, but are very important to me, and are very private, in that collecting drawings is a thing that not many people are interested in, and so I can\rquote 
t sort of show off with them, or except to a very very few people who are knowledgeable about these things. And a lot of people are slightly intimidated by pictures, because they\rquote re not sure of their own taste, and they don\rquote 
t like to offer a comment in case they show themselves to be \'85 you know, ignorant, as it were, about it, whereas they can be much more \'85 if they talk about a film they\rquote ve seen. But pictures, to many people, they\rquote 
re scared of. And they don\rquote t know what they\rquote re looking at, unless they\rquote ve got some confidence, or they\rquote ve been trained up as an artist or whatever. So I\rquote m wondering now, if I\rquote 
m doing this for some kind of social display? Well, it can\rquote t really be that, because firstly, I am dissatisfied with things that are more accessible to people. I mean, sometimes the most accessible pictures people have loved, and said, \'93Oh,
 why have you got rid of that, Ray? We used to come and enjoy it\'94, and I\rquote d just say, \'93I got bored with it\'94. So it\rquote s developing a certain side of me that\rquote s important. And the same with, with music. I mean, it\rquote 
s very private, conservative to play music, and to listen to Bach over and over again, and different performances of Bach. And I\rquote 
d be lost a bit without that. And to some extent, it cuts you off because people do feel a little bit intimidated about \'85 you know, they might think I\rquote m highbrow, or not dealing with the pop music and things that \'85
