\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, except that \'85
 well, everybody has pictures up, and as I say, if you feel a little bit insecure about commenting on pictures, and they don\rquote t know that I\rquote ve got other pictures that are lying in a cupboard, that I circulate around. So since most people don
\rquote t have many pictures, even, you know, one\rquote s colleagues as academics, they\rquote d have a few pictures, it doesn\rquote t sort of dawn on them that somebody else might have a lot. It\rquote 
s not a thing they think about. Artists might say, \'93Well, of course, you\rquote d have pictures about\'94. So they would not spend that much time, probably, looking at pictures on the wall. And they don\rquote t go all round the house 
looking at everything, they just happen to be in one room, and see there\rquote s a picture there, and say, \'93Well, that\rquote s not what I would have had\'94, or whatever. So it\rquote s curiously invisible, actually. But it means that \'85 it\rquote 
s interesting that my \'85 my children are interested, and they\rquote ve got a good eye. Maybe it\rquote s rubbed off on them, because I do actually show them and talk to them about it, from an early age, so maybe I\rquote ve handed on something there, I
\rquote ll just have to wait and see. But it\rquote s a private \'85 urge to satisfy the eye in a certain way, and also the ear. So I can spend a lot of time on my own, being perfectly content, with those \'85 because even though people might think I
\rquote m a very sociable and outgoing person, there\rquote s a whole lot of me which, by definition, they won\rquote t see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 What interests me is that you\rquote 
re not satisfied just to have pictures, full stop, but that you\rquote re continually changing, and thinking of that as developing your taste, as you put it, and your understanding, maybe, of the world of art. It sounds to me very much like there\rquote 
s a parallel there with your research, that you\rquote re constantly searching and progressing, and looking at new ideas, and that your art, your interest in art, is something like that as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, maybe I\rquote m driven 
by the fear of boredom! You might like to consider that as the clue! But where I sit, all the books behind me are books about art, although I can\rquote t claim I\rquote 
ve read them all. But a lot of them are works of reference. And one of the things I enjoy is if I get a drawing that I\rquote ve chosen by eye, I\rquote 
ve bought at an auction, because I like the drawing, it is then a kind of challenge, this is a sort of hobby, obviously, of trying to find more about it, so one could put an attribution on it. Now, there are two ways of looking at this. There\rquote 
s one way of saying, \'93Well, obviously, if I could put an attribution on a drawing, it increases its value, and then I can exchange it for something else and get more\'94, or, \'93I can get the satisfaction \'85 satisfaction of having shown
 that my eye has \'85\'94 And I think there\rquote s a lot of that in it. I\rquote d go for the second one, although the first one does apply. But it\rquote s a skill, in the same way, I suppose, that somebody who was skilled as \'85
 shooting targets, and they could hit the target frequently, and they get satisfaction about their skill there, I get satisfaction from my eye, in that sense, serving me well.
