\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid5903709\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The group, that\rquote s right, yeah. There was a crowd of us that were not at all deferential about \'85
 about the academic business. And we \'85 well, we didn\rquote t really think geography was much of a subject, to be quite honest. There was a guy that had done philosophy, and I think, basically, at that stage, geography didn\rquote t really \'85 wasn
\rquote t very self-conscious about itself, and moving along into sociology since then and certainly new geography. But I think perhaps the stance of the teaching was that other people have got it wrong, but we know it right. And then we said, \'93
Well, even you don\rquote t know it\rquote s right\'94. But anyway, we used to be quite blas\'e9 about going to what we thought were the frontiers of whatever things we were writing about, and if we didn\rquote t \'85 in a way that students never se
emed to afterwards \'85 I remember going off and trying to read stuff, as an undergraduate, in French and Spanish, and you know, bringing it into essays, in the most obscure journals, we\rquote 
d dig around in the University Library to find out who the people were that we thought were at the frontiers of whatever it was, and we\rquote d struggle away at it. We\rquote d look at their evidence, and if the evidence wasn\rquote 
t any good, we would say, \'93Well \'85\'94 So we were very critical, very very critical really, and not at all accepting that what we were being taught was the truth.
