\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Michele}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 :\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Just a couple more questions really. We were talking over lunch about why is it you\rquote ve done so much research, that you\rquote ve really \'85 a lot of academic teachers, as you were, wouldn\rquote 
t have focused so much on research, and that you did throughout your career, and why was that? What made you want to do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6424810\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, the thing is, research is much more fun, to my mind, because \'85
 what you have to do, teaching undergraduates, you do, well, you sort of close things off. I know that \'85 and they would say, \'93No, you don\rquote t do that\'94, and certainly the students at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose} wouldn\rquote t say that. But basically, you have to categorise, and make some kind of order, and say, \'93This is how it is\'94. Okay? Well, raise questions when you\rquote re a post-graduate. An example I\rquote ve often used is if \'85
 if you want to tell people why it rains, there\rquote s an answer you give to kids in primary school about why it rains, there\rquote s an answer you give at university, about saturated adiabatic lapse rates or something as I remember, and that\rquote 
s one answer. And then you get to post-graduate, and no one knows why it rains, you see. Now, I\rquote m more interested in going \'85 why no one knows that it rains, and I\rquote m not so interested in clarifying the answers that\rquote 
s at whatever level it is. It\rquote s much more fun. And it means that, also, it varies, you\rquote re in control of what you do a lot more. And it\rquote s fun. It\rquote s just kind of exploring. It\rquote s trying to find something fresh. You\rquote 
ve got a puzzle, and you try and solve the puzzle of what\rquote s going on. And so it seems to me hardly a question worth asking, who else \'85 why would you want to do anything else? You know, it\rquote s much more interesting to do research. I\rquote 
ve always been, I don\rquote t know, since an undergraduate, when I had the chance to do a research paper, you know, a project, a small research thing. It gives you freedom, it gives you the chance to be adventurous, it means you\rquote 
re in control of what you do, you can let your ideas go \'85 you\rquote re away from discipline which I\rquote m not very good at probably, you\rquote 
ll be slightly undisciplined, you can think of any ways of doing it in your own time, and the way you want to do it. It\rquote s a kind of freedom really. And there\rquote s all the fun of writing up about it, and trying to work out what it all means. It
\rquote s a hobby, it\rquote s \'85 you know, why do anything else? And people say \'85 and for many years, I was odd at the University of Kent, because I was doing research, getting research grants, while other people were busy just 
doing their lecture course, and thinking that was their job. You know, they\rquote d give the lectures, then during the vacation they\rquote d read a few books to make the lectures better, and that would be their life. They wouldn\rquote 
t do research. In fact, I was quite a pattern looking back on it not so long ago, what some of them did, people just didn\rquote t do research. They\rquote 
d write a book based on their thesis, maybe, and then later on they might write a text book based on their lectures, and that would be about it. So I\rquote ve always enjoyed doing that. And, as I said, I wouldn\rquote 
t have become a university teacher, unless I could do research. And the reason that I went part-time in 1984, was because the nature of the university teacher\rquote s job had changed, and I had to do much more administration. So I\rquote 
d rather take half a salary and do what I wanted to do, than get the full salary and do what the job had become. I didn\rquote t become a university teacher to become a manager to sack my mates, basically. I just didn\rquote t, you know, that\rquote s not
 what I thought it was all about. And it\rquote s interesting now that the kind of place where you can do the kind of work that I became a university teacher to do, is not in standard university Departments. The fact that I\rquote 
m at this Research Institute at Essex, where we\rquote re all doing research, is nearer to the atmosphere of why I left adult education to become \'85 than there would be if I was still in the Department, where they\rquote 
re churning out endless lecture courses, supervising endless graduate students, and also publishing. They\rquote re having a terrible life. I mean, really, the life of a university teacher now, is so dreadful, compared to what it was when I started. It
\rquote s awful really. I\rquote m sorry to say this, but it\rquote s become just a nightmare, and they really have to work terribly hard. They could never work up an art collection, they could never keep their garden \'85
\par 
