\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 After Success}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  have got this as the last question! I mean, the hesitation and the long pause is because of \'85
 it has to be something to do with my marriage, maybe the best and the worst together. But that would figure in some way, because that has been so important to me, having been married for so long, and then not being married. But I\rquote 
ve changed, and maybe I\rquote m not a suitable person to be married to anybody. Maybe I\rquote ve done Jan a really good turn, possibly. I just don\rquote t know. But who am I to say that? But clearly, I think \'85
 it would be a bit of a funny life if one \'85 having been so close to a partner for all that time, if that doesn\rquote t play an important part in determining the best and the worst. And I think that it has made me come to terms with myself a lot
 more, what has happened. But sometimes I think back, and one of the times that I\rquote ve been really at my happiest, I\rquote m torn now to say whether it\rquote s time with others, or time on my own. So maybe \'85 you see, that\rquote 
s why as one gets older, one comes to terms with solitude, whereas when one was younger, one would think, \'93Gosh, how awful. No one\rquote s inviting me out. I\rquote m on my own this summer. What\rquote s going on?\'94
 But later on, one really values that. So that\rquote s why I say that it\rquote s difficult to answer these questions, and I should bear this in mind when doing my research, that what appeared at the time to be the best, in retrospect, may not be. So 
\'85 I mean, all these questions, I mean, one you might have asked me is, \'93What are you most proud of?\'94 Now, how can one compare the pride of having taught a graduate student who\rquote 
s gone off and done all kinds of great things like Claire Wallace, I\rquote m really proud, and was proud, I\rquote m almost as proud of her as I am of my children. And yet, of course, the children is different, so I\rquote m proud of them. One\rquote 
s proud of the fact that one\rquote s turned out a lot of writing about sociology, which may have been \'85 a lot of it not terribly good, but some of it, you know, of interest. And maybe I was most proud of juggling everything. Just managing to not 
get completely swamped, and maybe \'85 that\rquote s a big clue, that \'85 one wants \'85 somehow, maybe a great weakness, that maybe it\rquote s a lack of commitment, the fact that I could criticise myself. Why didn\rquote 
t I stay in one area? But Dick Scase, a friend of mine, Professor Scase, often said to me, to my astonishment, he said, \'93If you\rquote d stayed with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Managers and their Wives}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  and the work that followed from that, on the Directors and so on, you would have gone off and been head of the London Business School\'94, and I just \'85 he\rquote 
s said that more than once, you see. And I think, \'93What a waste, because if I\rquote d done that, I wouldn\rquote t have done all the other things\'94. So maybe there\rquote s \'85 that\rquote s a lack of commitment to that one line. Or if I\rquote 
d stayed in urban sociology, I might have been, you know, well, I would have been, endlessly chairing this, that and the other in the urban thing, and been nothing but an urban sociologist. 
