s a good place to end, I think. Thank you.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Part Four: Interview with Paul Thompson held on 15th August, 2004 at Bishop\rquote s Castle, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Shropshire{\*\xmlclose}
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Ray, we\rquote re filling in one or two little bits from your interview. One of the points in the earlier interview you made was that you felt your Hertfordshire ethnography was rather na\'ef
ve in some ways. Now, what did you mean when you said that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, whether na\'efve was the right word or not, it was certainly not as goo
d as it should have been. Because, remember, I came from social geography, and the idea of social geography was much less subtle, really, in terms of exploring social relationships. Why should it be? They were interested in the geographical linkages betwe
en people and their activities. And whilst that was quite subtle, and there was some quite complicated work being done by people like Haggerstrandt and others in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Sweden{\*\xmlclose}
, on activity patterns, it was rather mechanistic. When I went to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in 1965, I was drawn into a completely different culture, although I\rquote d read a bit about it through the work of Bill Williams. To be immersed in the social anthropology of the Mediterranean area, led b
y Paul Stirling, and his students who came and gave weekly seminars, made me realise that the way I had approached the three villages in Hertfordshire was too mechanistic. I think maybe \'93mechanistic\'94 would be a better word than \'93na\'efve\'94
, because it was soph
isticated in terms of geography, but unsophisticated in terms of anthropology. And since my aspiration was to move more towards that kind of ethnography, then I was, to some extent, embarrassed. But bear in mind that the sociological tradition at that tim
e was very much of the survey, and so I hadn\rquote 
t realised that I was, in a sense, marginal, or perhaps, a pioneer, in moving away from the rather narrow surveys, narrow in my terms, of the Ruth Glass/John Westergaard approach, where they wanted to generalise 
from larger samples of populations if possible. So that\rquote s, I think, to unpack a bit, what I meant by that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
I think you were suggesting, last night, too, that the Mediterranean anthropologists were a very important bridge between the earlier colonial tradition, and the need to do an anthropology in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Western Europe
{\*\xmlclose} in the cities.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That\rquote s true. I think that \'85 I really was impressed, in the sixties, by the wor
k of the Rhodes Livingston Institute, and Clyde Mitchell in particular, because it was Clyde Mitchell who really introduced, in a rigorous way, the idea of social networks. Now, certainly John Barnes, in his earlier paper, \'93
Class, Committees in a Norwegian Parish\'94, had actually developed the notion of network. And Elizabeth Bott. I\rquote 
d read Bott and Barnes, but it was Clyde Mitchell that really made the jump of seeing how networks could operate in communities and in urban areas. And that seemed to me to be an
 immensely fruitful bridge, if you like, between the village-focused ethnography of the traditional anthropologist \endash  sitting in the square and seeing what people said \endash 
 and the more diffuse pattern of social relationships that was typical for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose} in the sixties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
The other point I would think would be that the contact with anthropology meant that your almost instinctive participant observation in Hertfordshire afterwards became a more conscious part of your research.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Remem
ber that I had actually done the study of these two villages in the French Alps, and without having any training at all, I got the idea that the only way to find out was to go round and talk to people. No way could I do a survey, you know, I had limited t
ime, so just getting the feel of the place - I feel, very strongly that, and I\rquote ve always had that. If you pressed me, \'93What do you mean by the feel of the place?\'94 I\rquote 
d be very hard pressed to answer you, to say really what I meant by that. But I certainly had that almost intuitively, and it could have come from Vidal de la Blush, that I mentioned earlier, because he wrote in this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Personalit\'e9 de la France}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  that each place did have its distinctive personality, which was partly due to the climate and the soil and
 the culture of the people and all this kind of thing. So, that, I think, was quite a strong, I won\rquote 
t say subconscious, but it was an element in my thinking, that you had to get the feel of the place, and personality. The fact that la Blush, a geographer, used the word \'93personality\'94
, I think, was interesting. So, not being too aware of the interconnection of these strands \'85 But you must recognise that, in the 1960s, sociology was a tremendously exciting and growing discipline, and I wasn\rquote t really too aware 
of what that was, having come from geography. So [I was] listening to the lectures of Lockwood and Goldthorpe in Cambridge, reading Bill Williams, being suggested by John Westergaard class was all, and surveys were all, [and then] moving into the Rhodes L
ivingston Institute type of anthropology, which I was reading at Cambridge before I went to Kent. I think that\rquote s interesting, I can\rquote 
t remember what put me onto that, why I got into Clyde Mitchell so early. Then I think a very very important influence, which I didn\rquote t mention in the longer interview, was the volume that Michael Banton edited on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Social Anthropology of Complex Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , because that was a real step, by anthropologists, to recognise that the work they\rquote 
d been doing could come back and inform the analysis of complex societies. I think that really was an important marker for a number of people who were working, qualitatively, doing ethnography, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain
{\*\xmlclose}, in the sixties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And where was that published?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Was it \rquote 66? It wa
s the Association of Social Anthropologists Annual Conference Volume. You know, every year they produced a volume, and at the time, it was very very avant garde for anthropologists to be coming back to look at their own country. The Evans-Pritchard view w
as still quite strong. And so there were these two currents: the currents of network in Central Africa - in Northern Rhodesia as it then was \endash 
 studies of networks there; and the studies of these Mediterranean societies, so that people like Paul Stirling, who I believe did supervise Ernest Gellner\rquote 
s thesis, and Freddie Bailey at Sussex, were immensely important, in the sixties, in developing a social anthropology of contemporary British society \endash  as another European society. So there were Ph.D. studies of Cypriots in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}London{\*\xmlclose}. I don\rquote t know what was going on at the LSE in social anthropology, because I was not involved with that, but I suspect there was some going on there too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Now, Paul Stirling, could you possibly give us a description of him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Paul Stirling! (LAUGHS) Well, I should dig out what I said at his Memorial Service, where I gave a more considered account. Paul was immensely charming and immensely infuriating, but made a fetish of pretence about his own incompetence. He\rquote d alwa
ys say that he was making a balls-up, and even on the most auspicious occasions he\rquote d swear a lot and say, \'93God, I\rquote ve got a total cock-up I\rquote ve made of all this!\'94 But he had a kind of charisma \endash 
 small people sometimes have this, they push out more \endash  and he w
as intellectually very sharp. And the thing that impressed me about Paul is that even if he knew nothing at all about the topic, when people came to give seminars, he could think on his feet, amazingly astutely. He could come up with an insight, and he ga
ve the impression \endash  and I think it was an impression \endash  that this was all just native wit, as if he\rquote d never read anything, and he\rquote d never been taught anything, it was just that he\rquote 
d got this amazing kind of capacity to generate insight and sparkling comment. The great thing that all the people at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}
 would say about him is that he was immensely supportive of people, even if he wasn\rquote t particularly interested in the area they were in, he really supported his staff, and he built up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}
 by being immensely eclectic. And what he always said is, \'93I really don\rquote t care what people are interested in. What they\rquote ve got to be is intellectually creative. So I\rquote ll always go for the best person\'94
. And, of course, that was infuriating, because we need an appointment in this particular area, or that particular area, and he\rquote 
d choose somebody quite else, simply because he found them much more sparkling than the people that were actually, in a more limited way, qualified for the post. He was a very endearing man, and people were by turns, enraged and charmed by him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And do you think, in terms of methodology, you actually learnt anything from him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Definitely. His great contention was, as he would put it, \'93The world is too fucking complicated to understand
\'94. He would just say that. He said, \'93You can\rquote t really - it\rquote s pretentious to claim that you understand what\rquote s going on. It\rquote s much too complicated\'94
. And so his lesson, which I picked up, was that over-simple analyses were almost certainly a l
oad of cock, and not to be considered very seriously. And so he made me immensely sceptical of the existing tradition, because he was so good at seeing that the subtleties and complexities of social life being [were] almost beyond the grasp of social scie
ntists, but you must do your best to get there. So you\rquote re bound to be a failure, and a brave failure was better than a self-deluding success.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And what about in terms of fieldwork, did you learn anything from him in that way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, his fieldwork strategies, and those of his students \endash 
 and perhaps I learnt more from his students, who were a little bit more disciplined \endash  was just endlessly to - he changed later on but at the time - endlessly to ask questions and to be alive and to be alert and to l
isten. And I think that the phrase that stuck in my mind at that time, was some graduate student was out in the field, and was in some difficulty, and writing back, as they did, to their supervisors \endash  anthropologists \endash  \'93What shall I do?
\'94 And it was John Davis who said, but it could have been Paul, \'93Listen to the gossip\'94. And that, probably [for] Paul and John and the rest of them, that was their thing \endash  \'93Listen to the gossip\'94. Be prepared for the unexpected. Don
\rquote t go in with your blinkers. Listen to the gossip\'94. And I think that got very strongly through to me at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So there\rquote s another point you wanted to make?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Yes. I think one of the interesting things about the sixties is that sociology was developing very rapidly. I was moving away fro
m geography, I was influenced by the survey approach of John Westergaard, and the Mediterranean anthropology of Paul Stirling and his students, so I was, in a sense, marginal to all of this, and had to make up my own position as between the geography I
\rquote d left, the sociology I was coming towards, and the social anthropology that was there in my daily life. I had to work out a sort of \'93Pahl position\'94, holding these different elements together.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It would be interesting to hear some more thoughts about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Managers and their Wives}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, there were distinct phases of it. Phase I, where the men were on a management course in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}, and I met them all and knew them, face-to-face, so that\rquote s how I got to know them, because I was on the cour
se with them. And they agreed to collaborate in this research, and they filled in a short questionnaire, which I got them to do, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}
. The second phase, with their agreement, was to send one to their wives, which was, I think, rather innovative at the time, to be finding out about their family life, and their wives\rquote  approach to their husbands\rquote 
 work and so on, and that was very successful. And that was done at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I say \'93successful\'94, because we got a very good response rate. And so that was fine. But then we needed to explore further, and that\rquote 
s where, curiously, the link between the sociology of the survey and the social anthropology of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Mediterranean{\*\xmlclose} came together, because Marie Corbin, who was one of Paul Stirling\rquote 
s graduate students, did the fieldwork. That is written up in the Appendix, as I\rquote ve said. And then Jan came in after all of this, to help me write it up, because, as is evident, I was doing about 6
0 different things at the same time, and by having her collaborating with me, it ensured that the writing-up was done more quickly, because she was a kind of progress chaser - having her expecting me to get things done by certain times. She had the limita
tion of looking after young children at the same time, but each of us prodded the other to get on with it, and the book was written, even though I was writing, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Whose City?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  and doing the work in the government at the same time. So it was a very busy period, that, and I don\rquote t think the work would have been done without Jan\rquote s help and support. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Do you think that not having done those in-depth interviews yourself was a disadvantage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It pushed the writing-up more towards the material that we had to h
and, which was the questionnaires, so that it looks more quantitative than it should have done. But a lot of the insights came from Marie Corbin who, obviously, took an active part in reading the drafts and in commenting. So, in sense, it was a check on w
hat we were doing. If we were saying silly things, as a result of the survey, she could say, \'93No, when I was doing the interviews in their homes, this just didn\rquote t come out\'94, or \'93this wasn\rquote t the case\'94
. So I feel that it was quite a good collaborative effort 
from that point of view, and I think that her account shows just how subtly she approached the interviews, which was very difficult, because she was interviewing both the wife, the husband and the wife together, and then sometimes the husband again, on hi
s own. Well, not interviewing, but talking to, and getting the feel. So, yes, in an ideal world, I should have done the interviewing, but I was just immensely pressed, and I didn\rquote 
t have the money, because to go round the country to do it, and to be away from the University, were just not possible at that time \endash  the early years of the University. It couldn\rquote t have been done without Marie Corbin. It just couldn\rquote 
t have been done.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And how far was she involved in the interpretation, the analysis of the material?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Only insofar as we\rquote d show her the drafts, and she\rquote 
d comment on them. So there was no question of her being a hidden third author - we didn\rquote t do her down. That\rquote s why I w
as insistent that her name should be on the Appendix, that it was her work for that, because that was her main contribution. And she was, of course, doing her own work, and it was hard for her, because she was being taken away from her research on souther
n {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Spain{\*\xmlclose} \endash  Ronda.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 In this Appendix, what do you think are the most important points she makes about the fieldwork?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The layering. Undoubtedly, the most important thing was the different stories that she got from different contexts. 
That was a huge revelation to me at the time. What the men said at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose} was different from what they said at home, and what the wives would then say about them, and what they\rquote 
d say afterwards, when they knew that Marie had talked to their wives. So it was this layering of reality. It made me very sceptical, I have to say, of na\'ef
ve surveys that go round and ask people questions, because at what level are they tapping into? And the fact that there was this discrepancy, if you like, between what came in the survey results, and what came in Marie\rquote 
s results, pushed me, I suppose, towards recognising the importance of qualitative work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Good. And one last point. It was definitely innovative of you to introduce the wives into this study, bu
t it seems as if it brought you trouble, rather than praise!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
I got a considerable amount of quite aggressive flak from the growing Feminist Movement of the early seventies, for assuming that managers were men, and that they had their wives. Why wasn\rquote 
t it wives and their managers that was the crack! And so although, when we started it, correctly it was innovative ... I remember my editor at Penguin Books saying, \'93What are you going to have for the title?\'94 And I remember replying, \'93
Well, really, it\rquote s about managers and their wives. That\rquote s what it\rquote s about!\'94 I think she would have preferred a more zappy title, but she couldn\rquote 
t argue with the fact that that, indeed, was what it was about! But [with] the resentment that picked up, the book just went underground almost, I couldn\rquote 
t use it for teaching, because women were resentful, and very suspicious. Because by the title, it was another work of patriarchy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, it was a study of the patriarchal type of relationship, wasn\rquote t it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But the subtlety of Feminist scholarship, at that time, didn\rquote t quite go as far as that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No. And do you think it\rquote s had any long-term influence?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, it\rquote 
s day may still be there, because I was astonished to read, when doing research on my current work on friendship, in an American book, edited by Nardy, and I was reading about friendship, there was this really perceptive piece, and I thought, \'93
God, that\rquote s really right!\'94 and I looked up the footnotes, and to my amazement, I\rquote d written it! (LAUGHS) And it was from }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Managers and their Wives}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , about friendship. And I think that the fact that Mike Savage is looking back on that material, indicates that it was a very scarce resource. There just weren\rquote 
t many studies being done of that, at that time, and I should, perhaps, h
ave been more aware of that. But the trouble was, I got seduced by the urban work, and that just took me right away from this, apart from the research that I did with Jack Winkler on directors, which was all fieldwork, all qualitative fieldwork, and which
 I shared with him, that followed up. But again, that got swamped, and, as you know, that\rquote s a sad story, because the book never got published.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Okay. Thank you. So you could you say a bit more about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Whose City}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 ? and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Patterns of Urban Life? 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Patterns of Urban Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  is a straightforward thing that came out of my teaching \endash  Urban Sociology \endash 
 and so that was a text which was taken up by the Open University, and was just part of what one does as a university teacher. But the activity that I wa
s most involved with from 1968-1972, was working, in various capacities, for the Department of the Environment, and the study for the South-East Regional Plan, and the Greater London Development Plan. And at the time, I was heavily immersed in that, deali
ng with the practical day-to-day work that was involved, because I was seconded from the University. But only afterwards did I realise that, actually, I was a participant observer in a very interesting period of development of the planning process in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}. So without recognising it at the time, I developed this thesis - the \'93Managerialist Thesis\'94 so-called - that scarce urban resources which are allocated by the managers \endash 
 whoever these might be \endash  that could do much to reduce, or make worse, the social conditions of people in cities. And this became known as the \'93Managerialist Thesis\'94. It was only when Colin Bell asked me to write a piece on \'93
Doing Sociological Research\'94, that I looked back on this experience and was able to see my role as a participant observer, which I wasn\rquote t really recognising at the time. It\rquote s a great sadness that I hadn\rquote 
t got the wit to keep a diary. If I\rquote d kept a diary over those four years, it would have been an amazingly useful resource - oh dear, the mistakes of one\rquote s
 youth! That was a big mistake. But I was busy, really really busy, reading the stuff, so, I mean, some days you\rquote d be starting at eight o\rquote clock in the morning, and going right on till six, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
London{\*\xmlclose}. And so with that pressure of work, it was very hard, at the end of the day, to keep a diary going.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Good. Thank you. Okay?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, not only was there a scorn and scepticism by Feminists about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Managers and their Wives}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , but it hit a really bad patch, coming out, as it did, in the early seventies. There was a tremendous envie de bous (?? \endash 
 228) amongst sociologists, that the working class was what everyone was looking at, and what you had to be interested in was poverty and collective action. Frank Parkin\rquote s book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Class, Inequality and Political Order}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , came out just a year after }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Managers and their Wives}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , and to be in the same Department where everyone was discussing, \'93Why aren\rquote t the workers rebelling?\'94 \'93And what about the structure of consciousness and action?\'94 - to be writing about the middle
-class managers and their wives was almost a betrayal. "You\rquote re getting a salary as a sociologist, and you\rquote re spending your time looking at the middle-class? Shame upon you!" And so it wasn\rquote 
t at all the leather-jacketed sociology that was popular at the time! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So, for one reason or other, you\rquote re saying that you feel you underrated the book?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, yes, I was slightly ashamed of it, because it was annoying both my wacky sociological colleagues, and the Feminists, and if it was actually being well-received by the captains of industry, this was a bad thing! (LAUGHS) There was a lot of debate, at
 the time, about if you\rquote re studying industrial relations, whose side are we on? As Becker\rquote s famous paper, \'93Whose side are we on?\'94
 should we be looking at the top dogs, the middle dogs, or the underdogs? And by and large, the sociology of the time of Becker 
and Alvin Gouldner were saying, you must give voice to the powerless. The powerful have got quite enough. So the fact that I was being sympathetic to middle dogs, was almost a betrayal of one\rquote s calling as a sociologist \endash 
 and I use that word advisedly \'93calling\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, in a way, you might say that After Success returns to that theme at a slightly higher social level, doesn
\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 After Success}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  was a development of a small project that I did of yuppies in the City of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}London{\*\xmlclose}, where I interviewed a dozen or so people who all left the same 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}College{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and that made me interested to pursue the idea of interviewing people who were at the top of different kinds of professions. I think I\rquote ve explained this, because of the na\'ef
ve notion, at the time, that people only worked if they were given lots of money. It was clear from my yuppie interviews that many of the young men, particularly, said they didn\rquote t want to be tied to City hours and Cit
y work for the rest of their lives. So what I did was to think what I could manage, in the way of interviews, because I think this is an important point. Very often one neglects to recognise the constraints of time, when one\rquote 
s doing other things, unless one\rquote 
s got secondment. So I reckoned I could do about 20 interviews, and I decided that I would choose particular occupations, and then think of a way of finding someone that would represent these. So when I wanted a top lawyer, I went to my colleagues in the
 Department of Law at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and said, \'93
Do you know somebody that\rquote s far away from here, that would be suitable for this kind of research?\'94 And I got some very good advice, and got an excellent interview, although not someone that appears in the book - but it\rquote 
s one of the best interviews. And similarly, if I wanted a consultant, I went to other colleagues, and got a surgeon, and so forth. So in this way, I built up a collection of really very influential and important people. I asked the Chairman of the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University of Essex Court{\*\xmlclose} to advise me about somebody in the City, and again, he was very well-placed, and he could give me the name of somebody. So I think it would have been very diffic
ult for a younger sociologist to have got that kind of - I won\rquote t use the word \'93sample\'94 - collection of interviews, because it meant that people had to be confident enough in me to know that I wouldn\rquote 
t embarrass them, because they were the one that introduced me to the person, and so I had a sort of responsibility to my contact person. Then I went around to interview these people, wherever they were, in their offices.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Now, can I ask you, why did you interview them in their offices?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Because I was interested in their work. I introduced myself as saying, \'93
I want to know something about how you view your career, and your interest in success\'94. And people are pretty flattered to know that they\rquote re being interviewed about how successful they are. Th
ey think that, particularly, by a more senior other academic \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And would they give enough time for an interview?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, this is what\rquote s extraordinary. Interviewing a Permanent Secretary was an enormous burden on her \endash 
 there, I\rquote ve given that away! \endash  her time. But, absolutely frankly, I was astonished at how the various people I interviewed \endash  the generals and the top civil servants, and the top barrister, now a famous judge \endash 
 how readily they were prepared to talk, very personally and very privately, about their hopes and fears and ambitions. That reminds me, the barrister, I actually did interview in his home, but I think that was exceptional.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Do you think that the office context really allows you to get into somebody\rquote s personality? Or do yo
u get more of a front?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Yes. No! (LAUGHS) Yes to your first question, no to the second. The reason that I was so confident was that when Jack Winkler and I did our interviews of the captains of industry, in the early seventies, we were absolutely asto
nished how, at the end of the day, when they\rquote d been Mr. Powerful Businessman throughout the day, they\rquote 
d push their papers off the desk, lean back, and they were just ready to talk. They wanted to talk about their own personal lives and things that were aff
ecting them. And we were amazed at how they almost asked to be interviewed, they wanted a confidante that could hear what they were worried about and so forth. So I was really very confident. I knew that people were absolutely ready to talk about their wi
ves, and their affairs, and their sexual dysfunctions \endash  and these are all actual things that happened \endash 
 to me, openly, even though, in some cases, I would see them again, and they were still prepared to be so immensely open. I was amazed. I really was amazed! And all I can say is, I think the grey hairs helped me, and that they were looking, perhaps 
\endash  and I say this slightly arrogantly \endash  as, you know, as two equal people. \'93You\rquote re a well-known sociologist Professor, I\rquote m a well-known General\'94, or \'93I\rquote m a whatever\'94
, and so they would talk to me as an equal. And I felt, very strongly, that a younger sociologist just could not have achieved that. Although, having talked to our colleague at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, what\rquote s his name? The chap that did the managers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Oh, Michael Roper?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Michael Roper, I think, told me, also, that he was surprised at how open they were to him, even though he was younger, so maybe I\rquote m over-emphasising that. And maybe - we\rquote ve discussed t
his, Michael and I - maybe we were over-diffident in expecting people to be resentful or resistant to talking so personally and privately about their hopes and fears. But I had no problem at all. And even when I went back for the second interview \endash 
 because all of them had two interviews \endash 
 and there were personal and private things at the first interview that I wanted to be unpacked a bit, and I asked about these, there was no resistance. Except in one case where the person told me very private personal thin
gs, on the understanding I wouldn\rquote t publish it, but was still able to see the tape-recorder running and say it all to me. So that was very surprising. And I still haven\rquote 
t got it quite clear how it was so easy. One thing, I think, must be important, is that the people who introduced me were trusted. And the fact that I was coming to the General by somebody, whoever it was, whom they knew, and said, \'93
Well, somebody who is a friend of this person, whom I know as an equal, so is to be trusted\'94. So there was more a feeling of someone that you know as a friend, because of the personal link, rather than someone who just knocks on the door and says, \'93
May I interview you?\'94 So it was remarkably easy, actually. But I wouldn\rquote t necessarily expect it always to be so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
And what would you say were the differences between interviewing these kind of people and interviewing sort of more ordinary people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, the first thing that comes to mind is interviewing the TV producer in my book, because he was so second-gues
sing, he was so reflexive, and I think this is what the more intelligent, or more self-aware people are like, different from the person who you just knock on the door in the housing estate, because they are immediately thinking of ways you\rquote 
re going to interpret their answer. They\rquote re responding to that interpretation, and giving you a second answer, and then when one responds oneself, they are debating. The fact that you\rquote 
ve asked this question after that first question, means that you\rquote re thinking this, but you\rquote 
re wrong in thinking this, because - and so they would almost guide the interview for me, or at least, this TV man did. Now, to have that degree of self-awareness and reflexivity, and also analytical consideration of what they\rquote re doing and why they
\rquote re doing, was testing, very testing for me, and very different from just some friendly woman that was telling about her daily life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And what about the problem of confidentiality, how did you deal with that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. It was a difficult one this, and actually, one of the best interviews I didn\rquote t use, because I couldn
\rquote t conceive of a way of disguising it. And I discussed it with the person, and she was extremely resistant to any way in which her comments could be traced to her. It would have been difficult. And so that\rquote 
s in the archive but not in the book. But mostly, I just changed the place or changed the name. Somebody like a barrister, there are so many barristers that it would be very hard to, you know, find out who it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And what did you actually promise them, before the interview?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 In terms of anonymity? That they wouldn\rquote t be recognised. And I checked it with them. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So they saw the text that was to go into the book?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Some saw the text, some chose the name \endash  their pseudonym \endash  they chose their mother\rquote 
s name or something. But they were all, the ones that are in the book, were happy. One chap objected to some kind of interpretation I put on it, but he said, \'93I don\rquote t think you\rquote re right\'94. And I think I put that in the book: \'93
I think this, but the chap didn\rquote t think it was right\'94. So I don\rquote t think there was any bad feeling at all in there. Partly because I fudged it by not using the most sensitive and easily recognisable material. Which was a pi
ty. Well, I say this of the book, that the top women, who are much more easily identifiable, don\rquote 
t appear. I was going to write a further piece on that, and was committed to do so, in a collection of essays in a book. But then I got very ill at that partic
ular time, and so that has never happened, so the material has never been analysed. Who knows whether it ever will? But it\rquote s a shame, because it\rquote s some of the best material.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, you wanted to add a point about the second interview?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, becau
se further to this notion of their greater reflexivity and awareness of what was going on, they all had the opportunity of reading the first transcript of the first interview, before I came to the second interview. And I would say to them, \'93
Is there anything you want to change or amend, in terms of accuracy?\'94 And by looking at themselves in this way, two things happened. Firstly, they got a degree of objectivity about themselves that, perhaps, they don\rquote t have normally when they
\rquote re just responding. It was a flow of questions, so they could look at the pattern of what was emerging, and they would then comment on that pattern as if they were almost an author with me, because they\rquote re all very intelligent people. \'93
How are you going to interpret this or that about my life?\'94 Or, \'93I don\rquote t think, you know, that the emphasis was right here\'94
. Now, this is dangerous because, in the second interview, they were in a position to guide me, knowing more about what they\rquote d already said about themselves. So I was torn, quite a l
ot of the time, [between thinking I was] learning more about this person in the second interview, or are they now putting up smoke screens to divert me from things that they\rquote d said in the first interview, that they didn\rquote 
t want me to pursue? So it\rquote s a rather complicated issue, this, and one that I\rquote 
ve always wanted to discuss, methodologically, with colleagues in the field, about what the effect with this particular category of respondent is, of giving them two interviews.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So let\rquote s talk a little bit ab
out the Russian Project, which, in fact we did together. You had had this long involvement with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}, a long interest in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
, and also you had the Summer School at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Kent{\*\xmlclose}. Was that for Russian [students]? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, [from the] former Soviet Union, which included, now, these independent places like 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Georgia{\*\xmlclose}. There students from the whole of the former {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Soviet Union{\*\xmlclose}. I had a long-standing interest in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Soviet Union{\*\xmlclose}, had be
en travelling there from the early seventies, and had met various people who had contacts there, and I was appointed, eventually by the ESRC, to be on the Managing Committee of their East-West Programme. Now, this East-West Programme was set up before 
\rquote 89, or more or less at the same time, so they hadn\rquote 
t really thought that all the changes, revolutionary changes, were going to take place. So they rather scrabbled together various suggestions for research, to document the transition. And as I recollect, you 
and I felt that a qualitative study would be useful and valuable at this particular time when things were changing so rapidly in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Soviet Union{\*\xmlclose}
. And secondly, and most importantly, when people were prepared to talk for the first time, in a way they\rquote d been much too inhibited to do previously. So it seemed that the conditions were right, and that anyone with interests in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Soviet Union{\*\xmlclose} would be encouraged to get involved. Now, you were interested in, and had already been involved with changing family relationships.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. And I\rquote d also been to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}
, because the Russian oral history movement had developed in the glasnost period, and I\rquote d been invited there, and met various people that I thought we might possibly be able to work with.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That\rquote 
s right. So with the sort of slight insider knowledge I had of the ESRC wanting to promote this kind of research, and having new contacts from the students on the Summer School, and having my own interest in the informal 
economy, and how people were managing with the collapse of economic arrangements, we got together and thought how best to do this. Well, obviously, it had to be Russian-speaking people, and we were criticised, I think, by the ESRC, that neither of us were
 Russian speakers. But we were able to say that we\rquote d got exceptionally good contacts. In my case, there was a young researcher called Dina Khapaeva, who was interested in working with us, and you had your contacts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 There was Dasha Khubuva also in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}
, but Jonathan Cohen proved to be the anchor person in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}. He was doing a Ph.D. in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose} at that time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. So we believed that our respective contacts \endash  you in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
Moscow{\*\xmlclose}, and mine, as it happened, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose} \endash  would be a good way in to get an oral history project established. But as I recollect, we weren\rquote 
t given as much money as we actually asked for. We were cut back quite substantially.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 No, I think we decided to apply for a pilot, and then we weren\rquote 
t able to go beyond that. So all we carried out was the pilot.
\par  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Ah! That\rquote s right, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Incidentally, on the language point, I had learnt Russian years before, and I did try to recover my Russian. I did 
\lquote A\rquote  Level Russian as part of my National Service. So I\rquote d had a sort of earlier interest in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose} myself \endash  not as sustained, though, as yours.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So I think that, well, the situation at the time, where there were so few people with any knowledge and contacts 
\endash  that was the crucial thing. We were really well placed for contacts, the Summer School - of course, I had contacts that go back many years. Well, we still had the problem of who was going to be the manager between us and the actual inte
rviewers, and who were going to be the interviewers. So you had your plan for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}, and I had the idea of working through an Institute in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose}. But when we met [Golofast], the Director of the Institute, in Paris, it seemed that he was more interested in getting resources for his Institute, and was asking for quite a lot of money that we didn\rquote 
t think was actually going to go to the interviewers. So, Dina Khapaeva, a highly competent person, and well-connected, in a sense, volunteered to be the contact person for {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose}
, to find people that we would then train up. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Now, the difficult thing was for us to have a clear kind of interview guide that would be understandable for people in a variety of social situations in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
, and also to get some kind of sample of people. Now, I recollect having help from Miss Zerenko \endash  I forget her Christian name \endash  and meeting her in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 with drafts of our pilot schedule, so that she would eventually help to translate this. I think that\rquote 
s how it happened. Getting our English interview schedule translated into Russian, in a way that really made sense in the Russian context, was a challenge that we had to overcome. And I remember working q
uite closely with this Miss Zerenko, who was very helpful indeed, and had got a lot of experience of doing survey kind of work, but not in oral history. So we managed that, I think, successfully. We had a good research instrument. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But one interesting point about that was that, originally, I remember Dina felt that we couldn\rquote 
t start the interviews by talking about grandparents, because that would be [seen as a dangerous question, asking about ancestors who might have been politically on the wrong side.] 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 In fact, the situation had changed so rapidly, since she\rquote 
d been there, I guess, that that wasn\rquote t a problem at all. We were able to start talking by about people\rquote s memories of grandparents. And the whole Interview Guide was basically about families an
d social change. We tried to interview two generations within each family.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
But we were also interested in the forms of support between generations, and what informal work they might be engaged in. And again, that could have been seen to be delicate, 
in that, you know, it was informal, and not within the surveillance of the authorities. But again, people seemed to be pretty open when we came to the interviews about this. But we were, perhaps, over-cautious. I do remember being very worried about wheth
e
r we would be refused interviews by people who felt that it was all too delicate, or too intrusive. So we fell over backwards to get through that cultural barrier, by having these contacts - Dina and other people, this Miss Zerenko, particularly - who wer
e quite good at seeing how what we were interested in, in our context, could be extrapolated to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
 without making too many concessions to a situation which we thought might be difficult. So that did take us some time, doing that, and there
 was a lot of coming and going, and perhaps you remember talking about it with Daniel Bertaux. We did spend a lot of time on the Interview Guide, to make sure that was right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But Daniel Bertaux had already started doing his work in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia
{\*\xmlclose}, which was more family - not genealogy, in the strict sense, but studies of that kind.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yeah.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And the other problematic area, of course, which you mentioned earlier, was the sample, wasn\rquote 
t it, because one couldn\rquote t translate a Western occupational study, we felt, to the Russian situation. We spent a lot of time talking about that, didn\rquote t we.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 We did. We did. So these are all appropriate things to work on in a pilot study, to try various options.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 But do you remember about the solut
ion to the sample problem? Because we decided that access to resources was, in many ways, more crucial than actual job levels, and we tried to build that into the sample.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 We did, yes. I can\rquote t actually recollect, though, whether we asked the interview
ers to find certain kinds of people. Is that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes, we did. Yes, yes. We had a quota.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That\rquote 
s right, and then they went off and found the people. But the important stage that followed the devising of the Schedule was the t
raining of the interviewers, who had their own preconceptions because of their own different backgrounds. Psychologists in the case of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose}. They weren\rquote 
t all in the culture of oral history, and so we had to have seminars or workshops. That was arranged in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose} by Dina, and your colleague in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}, and that, I think, was a very important part of the whole enterprise, and we don\rquote t know, really, what effect that training has had on their futures, o
f the people that we had. But that, in itself, was worth doing, I think, as an exercise, and you, Paul, did that, and brought people together and dealt with their questions, and made it quite clear to them what was expected. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Then the next problem was a 
serious one really, in that we had to get the material transcribed and translated, and these were quite difficult things to do, because whilst we were able to get the material transcribed in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow
{\*\xmlclose}, how did we do it in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}St. Petersburg{\*\xmlclose}? Or did it all go down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Moscow{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That I don\rquote t remember, no. But anyway, we only had the money to transcribe ten interviews, wasn\rquote 
t it? So we selected what looked the most promising ten interviews.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, Dina read them, rem
ember. Dina went through the transcripts and made some judgements for us about ones. But we were, I think, to be honest, we were very dependent upon her to make judgements about what was in the transcript of the tapes, and she listened to it all, and she 
did a huge amount of translating herself. In fact, I think most of it. And that was a very time-consuming and difficult thing, but she was, I think, very bright at doing it, although her English wasn\rquote 
t [perfect], I think we got the sociological sense, becau
se of her understanding, but not always in proper grammatical form. And I think the richness of the data surprised us. Some of the interviews were going to be better than others, but on balance, given that this was a tricky period of social change, I thin
k the way that we handled it, and the support we got from our Russian colleagues, to my mind, was good enough, or more than good enough, to have quite a major project. It could have gone on and been really successful. And I think it\rquote 
s really sad that, for whatever reason, our work wasn\rquote t taken up by the East-West Initiatives Committee of the ESRC. When other work which \endash  I mean, I know, being on the inside \endash 
 was pretty much worthless, because it was set up before \rquote 89, some of the political sociology, and was
 dealing with situations that were long changed, but the ESRC wasted its money on some of these expensive projects. Whether there was any kind of bias against qualitative research, I don\rquote t know. I suspect that there might have been.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, no, I think we got more that there was a bias against us as outsiders, that we hadn\rquote t been Russianists.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 That may be partly it, yes. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Certainly there was a phase when we were pretty annoyed with the way we\rquote d been treated.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 We certainly were. We were. Well, I think, in retrospect, there\rquote 
s no question that we were badly treated, and that there wasn\rquote t the sympathetic understanding by the old style sort of Kremlinologists, specialists in the Communist system, who actually didn\rquote t adapt to the transition, and didn\rquote 
t recognise the sort of pioneering work we were really doing. Which is a shame, because that was an opportunity that we hadn\rquote t realised, but we see now, was a window that was open for a time, and then was shut. I carried on doing a bit mo
re work with Dina Khapaeva, on \endash  I got a little bit more money \endash 
 to be able to interview Russian managers and the cultural misperceptions that they might have about doing business with the West, and I did some interviews myself in St. Petersburg, and so di
d Dina, and that has been published under her name. It was directed by me, but the actual work that I did was really for her, because it was her understanding of the situation that was the driving force. Again, that\rquote 
s a project which I think could have gone on further, and although I tried very hard to get funding for Dina, from various British companies, and as it turns out, they were foolish not to fund it, because this became \endash  and it\rquote 
s a well-known thing \endash  this lack of understanding of the way the Russi
an situation is working, and the cultural complexities of doing business with the Russians, has turned out to be one of the most crucial things. So, again, a slight feeling of sadness, that something that was really so important, didn\rquote 
t get the funding. I think that the economists took over rather violently, in the period of transition, and rather insensitively, and the push towards the capitalist economy in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
 was done without really the sociological understanding that would have been really useful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I agree. But we did produce the joint article.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 We produced the joint article from that, and that was published in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 festschrift}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  for Paul Stirling, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 When History Accelerates}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , edited by Chris Hann.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And so then, also, I did go
 on to use the material myself, because Daniel was doing these studies of families, he developed a family interview technique, trying to look at how families got through this Soviet era, with particularly interesting material on the elite families. So I d
ecided to link up with him. And then we also find Anna Rotkirch, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Helsinki{\*\xmlclose}, who\rquote s been working on sexuality in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
, and we\rquote ve edited a joint volume [On Living Through Soviet Russia]. Now, that includes a paper I did with Victoria Semenova, who\rquote s been involved in longitudinal studies in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}
, a sociologist, and it\rquote s about parents and children and the ways of bringing up parents and children in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Russia{\*\xmlclose}. That is mainly based on our interviews, there\rquote s some of Daniel
\rquote s material that is used, and it\rquote s looking at the way that different social groups brought up children, and also the ways in which the new young entrepreneurs were brought up. And the interesting thing that came out was that the standard 
male-headed family did not produce innovative new young entrepreneurs. The young entrepreneurs seemed to come from female-headed families or families where the women were dominant.
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
So, you know, there were two outcomes. But I totally agree with you, it\rquote s very very rich material. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
I think one of the real, well, bad reflections on British social science, is that, inevitably, before 1989, qualitative research was just impossible in that area \endash  virtually. And the social science community didn\rquote t grasp th
at this great opportunity for doing qualitative work, and the people weren\rquote t prepared for it, because there just weren\rquote 
t people skilled in the Russian world, who were qualitative researchers. So the fact that Paul and I were in there, for a variety of almo
st serendipitous reasons, was a huge bonus, and should have been recognised as such, because no one else was prepared to do it. So it\rquote s not a question of us not being fluent Russian speakers, the fact that we\rquote 
d got these contacts was of inestimable value, but it was wasted \endash  although, as you say, some was published \endash  but much more could have been done. And there\rquote 
s a lesson there, I think, that the wrong kind of research, perhaps, may have been done, simply because that\rquote s what the old style Sovietologists knew about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Okay. So let\rquote 
s now turn to the Friendship Project. Because when you were interviewed, Ray, in 1998, you thought about that, and you explained about the origins, but it would be good to know how you carried it out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, I think, without question, it was the most carefully prepared and methodologically sophisticated piece of qualitative research that I\rquote ve been involved with. So from that point of view, I think that it\rquote 
s almost a landmark in doing this kind of research. The details are published in a volume edited by Chris Phillipson \endash  which was a paper we gave to an ESRC Seminar \endash 
 and also will be in our forthcoming book, so that the actual methodological details \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Will be an appendix to the book?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Or
 perhaps even in a main chapter of the book. So the nub of the methodological approach is published in a book edited by Chris Phillipson, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Social Networks and Social Exclusion}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 . We feel that the methodology was particularly innovative, because we were concer
ned to find the whole of an individual's significant social world, and there had been various approaches to this in the past. One way we thought was to look at people\rquote 
s address books, or a list of people that they sent Christmas cards to, but that, in pilo
t work, was just too unwieldy. We did some interviews, and they just took forever to record, and you learnt about far too many people. So one of the problems with qualitative research is always the practicalities of time and energy, you have to cut back i
n some way, unless you\rquote 
re going to interview the same people, as some people do, every Friday afternoon for a year. So the method we hit on was very very effective, where we produced, for the interviewees, who, I must explain, were very carefully selected. 
We got a sample, a purposive sample, by creating a matrix of the various categories that we wanted to be represented, and then paying a research agency to find examples of these particular categories, in different parts of the country. So whilst we
\rquote re not looking for a representative sample, it was a purposive sample, and more thoroughly brought together than any other qualitative study that I\rquote ve been involved with \endash  but at some cost, evidently. So once we\rquote 
d got the people in agreement, through the agency, to do the interview, we would send them a letter explaining something about it, and 20 sticky labels, and we\rquote d ask them to put - not to use them all if they didn\rquote 
t want to, but to write on these labels, those that were most important to them now. That was a very important phrase, \'93Those people who are most important to you now, and their relationship to you, and where they live, and how far away\'94
, and so forth. And when we came to the interview, we came with a large piece of paper with concentric circles dr
awn on them, and asked the people to put these labels on to the diagram. And while they were doing that, we asked them more about who they were, why they were putting them where they were, and so on, and once all the sticky labels had been put on, we then
 asked people to consider what the implications of what they then saw, for the first time, was. And this was really interesting, because what we\rquote 
d actually done for them was to make them prioritise their relationships in terms, not of social distance \endash  and that\rquote s important, because people thought it may have been there \endash 
 but in terms of their importance to them now, and then to say, you know, how would you label these different levels of closeness? And people would say, \'93Well, these ones in the middle are the rocks of my life\'94
, or something, and they would have their own labels for the different degrees of closeness. Because one of the problems of researching a topic like friends, is that, of course, no one really is sure what the word \'93friend\'94 means. It can 
mean anything from someone who you play with tennis now and again, to someone you\rquote ve known for 30 years and is more like a brother or a sister. So by not emphasising the word \'93friend\'94
 while we were doing the interviewing, this could emerge from what the people said. And when they looked at their whole \'93personal community\'94 as we called it, they would see the whole, there\rquote 
d be a social construct that they, themselves, had created, and they would then reflect on this, and we would then allow them to move people from different rings, if they felt, \'93Well, I don\rquote t really think that person is equivalent to that person
\'94, and so forth. And we\rquote d also encouraged them not to be swayed by normative pressures. So if they said, \'93I suppose I\rquote d better put my mum in the middle\'94, we would say, \'93Well, only if you really think that\rquote 
s where she belongs\'94, and they\rquote d say, \'93Well, actually, I don\rquote t get on with my mum\'94, and they\rquote d put her further out. So once they were reassured that they could put what actually was true for them, rath
er than what was expected of them, they got a different picture. So that was a very thorough and very time-consuming part of the interview. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Then we went back through various stages of their lives, because they\rquote d already completed a short schedule before we arrived, which we\rquote d sent them with the introductory letter. If their first job had been a nurse, we would say, \'93
When you were a nurse, did you have any close friend there that you haven\rquote t mentioned now?\'94 Or anybody that was important to them. And then they would say, \'93Yes, but we\rquote ve lost touch\'94, or \'93I forgot about them\'94
, and so forth. So whilst we originally wanted to do a sort of oral history of people\rquote s relationships as they went through their lives, this took too long, but this compromise worked very
 well. I think that is important, that it was a compromise, but it worked very well. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Then another phase of the interview was to ask them who they turned to under various circumstances \endash  whether, if they were ill, who would help them, or if they wanted advice on this, that or the other, who they\rquote 
d borrow money from and so forth \endash  the function aspects.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So there was quite a lot of pilot work on which the final interview version was based?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Yes. Yes, there was pilot work, definitely, on all of this. And we\rquote 
d got quite a streamlined interview schedule, well not interview schedule, but what you call it? Guide. So that other people who were interviewing with us, could follow up very closely. And we had no problem in differences between the interviews
. I did some of the interviews, a broad cross-section, I suppose. But in the end, there were 60, and they were, of course, quite lengthy, and scattered about the country, so Liz Spencer and I believe that the quality of our material was as good as we
\rquote d ever got, because we\rquote d thought it through so carefully beforehand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Was there a third person involved in the interviewing, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Four. There was Jane Ritchie, who\rquote d invented, with Liz, the so-called \'93charting method of analysis\'94
 which we could com
e to, and she had been in charge of the Qualitative Research Section of Social Community Planning Research, so was highly, highly skilled as an interviewer, an absolutely brilliant interviewer. And Liz is a particularly good interviewer. I did my best! (L
AUGHS) But I\rquote 
d never been so closely focused in doing qualitative research, because I would be more likely to go off on tangents, but I was kept very firm to the thing. And, yes, there were one or two other people, too, that interviewed. But the material wa
s very comparable, irrespective of who interviewed, because of having this model of the personal community. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 I don\rquote 
t think I need to go into any great detail about the charting method that Liz devised, but again, it was immensely time-consuming, and it did produce material which anybody coming afterwards could easily see what we\rquote d said, what we\rquote 
d done, and the basis of our conclusions. Now, this is extremely important, and not at all common in qualitative research. Because John Goldthorpe, in his \'93Critique of Qualitative Research\'94, in a well-known article in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 The British Journal of Sociology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , has claimed that, unlike some forms of research, there\rquote s so much subjectivity that you can\rquote 
t go back and check the interpretations of the people that have done it. In 
our case, it can be done. And we were very very insistent that we would not pluck out comments or verbatim remarks, to illustrate a theme that we were particularly concerned about, unless it could be justified in terms of the whole of the transcript. The 
charting method allows you to do this, it allows you to look across. I don\rquote t want to go into the detail of it, but it has the advantage \'85
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Can you describe it in two or three sentences, though? That would help, I think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 It\rquote s hard to do that. It 
would require longer. Basically, what you do is, you index the transcript according to a coding frame of either the theoretical issues you\rquote 
re interested in, and/or the things that have emerged from preliminary reading of the transcripts. So you have a mode
l of the whole range of issues that you might wish to discuss, and these are all indexed, in terms of headings and sub-headings. And so what one does is, one puts them down the side of the transcript, and then these are transferred on to \'93
first order charts\'94 according to theme \endash  thematic charts \endash  and then these are abstracted down, so that in the end, you can see \endash  if you have a big enough piece of paper, as it were \endash 
 a matrix with all your respondents, the 60 respondents, down the side, and then all the po
ssible themes across the top. But then this gets refined and refined and refined, so there are different charts for different topics. And the comments are either put on to the charts \endash  if they\rquote re short ones, verbatim \endash  or there
\rquote s the index to where they ca
n be found in the transcript. So any argument that we develop is based not on, you know, a one chance phrase by somebody, but by the fact that it is cumulated off in one of these topic charts. And so anybody looking at the charts, if these were deposited 
in the future, would see how we\rquote ve transferred what is in the transcript, into the text of the final report, and where the logic of our argument took us. So the logic is supported by the evidence at every stage. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Now, this doesn\rquote t, of course, take away th
e need for imaginative interpretation, but the basis for that imaginative interpretation is put there. I think the degree of thoroughness of this, for me, takes it a step further. I believe, when I ended the long interview in 1998, the previous interview,
 I think the last thing I said was that my best work is yet to come. And I think, in terms of qualitative research, the work that I\rquote 
ve done with Liz Spencer is better, methodologically, and more advanced in its combination of sociological imagination and methodological rigour, than anything I\rquote ve done before. So, to my surprise, what I said then seems to be correct!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Fine. And I think it would be nice if you could say a bit more about Liz herself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Well, Liz was an exceptionally talented person to work with, because she had had years of work for the SCPR, as a qualitative researcher, and has had experience of a whole range of different issues and topics. So as an interviewer, she was far more experi
enced than, let\rquote 
s say, an academic who had to combine research with other responsibilities. She did nothing but research for year after year after year. So from that point of view, she was a more experienced researcher than a typical academic. And secondly,
 she had an immense capacity for hard work. I mean, she was someone who would, if jobs had to be done, she would be up at four o\rquote 
clock in the morning, and would simply do them, or stay up till midnight. So from that point of view, deadlines were kept, interviews were done, under very very hard conditions, because she had other work to do as well, but it was done. 
\par  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2767477 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
Thirdly, she was particularly perceptive and imaginative, I think, in interpreting and understanding the material that we gathered. She had the
 most astonishing capacity to seemingly memorise the people, in great detail, and to refer to them, in terms of their pseudonyms, easily, in the 60 cases. She\rquote 
d have the whole of this [in her mind], largely because she did so much of the charting, and the charting just enables you to understand the material so well. I\rquote 
d done some, but not as much as she did. So the qualities that she contributed were very powerful and very strong, and it\rquote s totally appropriate that she is the senior author in the book, the f
irst author, in the book that we are publishing together. I suppose I contributed more in the way of broader sociological ideas, but the way that we worked together was extremely creative and fruitful, and I think that, in this case, two authors are far b
etter than one.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1197548 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And she does specialise in methodology too, doesn\rquote t she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 She specialises in methodology, and she has been employed taking Summer Schools in the former 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Soviet Union{\*\xmlclose} and various other European countries, and she\rquote s internationally acknowledged as being in the forefront of qualitative research. She\rquote 
s been asked by the Cabinet Office to write a report on the state of the art in Britain, and I think that although it may not be very palatable to our colleagues in the United States \endash 
 I know of no qualitative research in America that is of the standard that Liz has done in this country \endash  there\rquote 
s no one as sophisticated, and, indeed, qualitative research is still being done in the United States, of the old-fashioned, feel it i
n your heart, sort of thing, without having that rigorous follow through, which we have. And I think that it will be possible for future scholars to come back to our material and see things, perhaps, with different perspectives. So it\rquote 
s a historical source of social life in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Britain{\*\xmlclose} at the beginning of the 21st century, that has much wider significance than simply the book that\rquote s come out of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 And how long have you known her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Liz, I\rquote ve known for coming up to 30 years, I suppose. Middle seventies. And we\rquote 
ve worked on various other things. But she\rquote s an exceptionally talented social researcher, and I think, has enabled me, really, to do work that is of a different order. I think that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 
After Success}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  was full of insight and imagination,
 but not so disciplined. I mean, it sounds pompous to say it was full - but insight and imagination need to be structured in a way that Liz has encouraged me to do. So, from that point of view, I think my work has advanced.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 So just one last question, which is, what do you think has been the most influential work that you\rquote ve done?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid2767477\charrsid2767477 Ray:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Well, since I\rquote ve been addressing different audiences, there\rquote s different kinds of influence, that\rquote 
s the problem. Because for a long time, geographers thought I was a geographer, and my early work in Hertfordshire, which was my Ph.D., has been referred to as \'93a classic study\'94. So in Geography, that\rquote 
s still taught to students, I think. So that\rquote s quite surprising. In the urban field, my managerialist thesis became a kind of
 orthodoxy of the Weberian orthodoxy, and went in the text books and led to, I think, worldwide attention, and people have written critical articles and books about it for many years, so that the managerialist thesis was clearly important. In the area of 
work, I think that I was largely influential in changing the conception of the Sociology of Work, to the Sociology of Employment and Work, because before I did my work, my research on Sheppey and with Jay Gershuny, there\rquote d been texts in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}, called \'93The Sociology of Work\'94, when they meant \'93The Sociology of Employment\'94
. But because of informal work and domestic work, which now people are recognising [as work] So the title of the journal, BSA Journal, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Work, Employment and Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 , I\rquote m pretty sure was due to the fact of things that I was writing at the time that changed their conception of work. So I think I\rquote ve changed people\rquote s ideas about what work is. And also, I
\rquote ve put into the current vocabulary, which one sees in the press and elsewhere, t
he distinction between the "work rich" and "time poor", and the idea of "work rich" multiple earner households. I think that that probably my notion about work, whether it\rquote s accredited to me or not, will remain. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Divisions of Labour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477  is also seen as a classi
c work. This, again, is part of this notion of opening up the whole idea of work to all forms of work, and I think the work on the informal economy probably will be there as a landmark. But, curiously, I suspect that my sceptical article about the importa
nce of social class, which has been reprinted in various places, will live on, simply because students like to have things in their essays, and if you\rquote re highly critical of a concept, it\rquote 
s almost easier to be remembered for that, even though its later shown that perhaps I overstated the case. So because I spread around between geography and urban studies and work, and so, it may well be, I hope that the book that\rquote 
s coming out with Liz, will be more of a lasting impact than any of the others, because I think it might well be the best. But who is to know until I\rquote m dead, you\rquote ll never know!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1197548\charrsid2767477 Thank you, Ray. Thank you so much.
\par 
